http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-4&fd=R&url=http://toledoblade.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070531/OPINION03/705310349&cid=1116692882&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ toledoblade.com -- Creation myth promotion is irresponsible Thursday, 30 days search Letters to the Editor &#149; Snip & Save &#149; Shop Blade products &#149; Front Page Reprints New Car Dealer Guide Letters to the Editor Article published Thursday, myth promotion is irresponsible I thought this was 2007, not 1007! For your heretofore respected newspaper to feature, as front-page serious news, the opening of a self-styled "Creation Museum" whose purpose is to indoctrinate the gullible and ignorant with foolish, unscientific, and incidentally unoriginal fables is an indelible stain upon your integrity. For any rational person to claim the earth was created in six days some 6,000 years ago is so patently ludicrous, such an impossibility, and so preposterously counter to established proven science as to be worth only scorn and ridicule. Furthermore, the assertion by this "Answers in Genesis" group that Biblical creation is true is ipso facto false. Just read the first two chapters of Genesis to find two separate (1:1-2:3 and 2:4b-25) conflicting and inconsistent, e.g. order of creation, accounts which themselves are derivative with background in older Near Eastern mythology, e.g. the flood and creation myths in "Epic of Gilgamesh" and "Enuma Elish"! Answers in Genesis indeed! Which account? These people are pathetic. But you know better and, therefore, your article is a cheap, irresponsible pandering to superstitious readers; at best this belongs in a small paragraph with the "Star Wars" anniversary story in the escapism section. To impart cover of credibility and respectability to emotion-driven drivel and its attendant squandering of $27 million is intellectually reprehensible journalism and to promote and publicize humbug as reliable, important news just feeds garbage disguised as sustenance to the misguided, the lost, and those so anxious for security they will believe the unbelievable. For shame! Evolution not science, rather a sacred cow A May 28 article reprinted from the [Los Angeles] Times is a lie promoted by an obviously atheistic author. Evolution parades behind a mask of "science," but is really a sacred cow that is as factual as Greek mythology. It contradicts even the most basic laws of thermodynamics. Only a fool who is trying to escape accountability before the Creator would believe such far-fetched jargon. Creationism welcomes and encourages investigation. However, how the universe began is a matter of history, not science. The Bible is a book of history that factually records the historical events of creation. Unless you are willfully blind, the fact that the universe operates by design is a simple deduction from everything you see in the cosmos. It is evolution that is an assault on science. Potential is strong for light rail in city Thank you for the article on light rail in Toledo. As a former Toledoan now living in St. Louis, I can vouch for the benefits of the Metro mass transit system here, including the Metrolink rail lines. Toledo will need to do its homework carefully and assess its options realistically to design an effective network of bus and rail lines, but the potential is certainly there. In St. Louis, stops at educational institutions, hospitals, and other large employers create a steady demand that helps supplement the event traffic from sports events, concerts, etc. I think Toledo could find a successful mix as well, and I wish the region success as it explores its options. I can't wait to buy my first TARTA rail ticket. Transit system could boost area tourism After traveling to many cities in this great nation of ours, I was excited to read that Toledo is seriously considering a light rail system. This type of mass transit not only can be environmentally friendlier than autos, but it can provide a fast method of getting downtown and stimulate economic growth. What seriously disappointed me, though, was that no mention was made of running light rail to and from the local airport. Can you imagine a bigger push for the "Buy Local-Fly Local" campaign than if citizens of Toledo were able to take a light rail to the airport for a fraction of the cost of parking there? Conversely, as the city tries to boost its tourism and convention business, can you imagine if air travelers were able to hop on a light rail and have quick access to the downtown hotels? Better yet, hop on a light rail and be dumped out at the SeaGate Convention Centre, Fifth Third Field, or the new downtown sports arena? This can be done. Twenty years ago I got my first experience traveling via light rail from the suburbs of Cleveland to the downtown district - years before Jacobs Field opened up. In Chicago, Toronto, San Francisco/Oakland, New York and many other cities, a light rail or subway has a stop right next to their baseball fields and arenas. Heck, even Detroit, whose downtown revitalization has only just begun, has a monorail system that takes travelers throughout the downtown area. I only hope that our local leaders can think this far out, and not just to their next election. Reducing oil imports can help war effort During World War II we supported our troops by making sacrifices at home while they were overseas fighting. This required rationing of scarce commodities such as gasoline, tires, automobiles, and certain foods. As we fight the current war, which is going on all over the world, we are reluctant to make any sacrifice at home. Apparently a large number of us do not understand we are at war with an enemy who has sworn to wipe us off this earth. This enemy recruits followers from any area of discontent in any country. He answers to no sovereign nation but receives support from nations who find that this disruptive force can serve their purposes. One way we could help is to reduce imports of oil. Our dependence on these imports is making some foreign countries rich and allowing some of this money to flow to the various groups that are committed to our destruction. In other words, we are financing the groups our troops are fighting and dying to allow us to live free. Some of the ways we could reduce oil imports are to raise the corporate average fleet economy standard each year for automobiles; establish a CAFE average for non-commercial trucks; have an excise tax on vehicles that do not at least meet the CAFE averages and use the proceeds to support alternative sources of energy, and pass legislation that would reduce the importation of oil by 10 percent of the amount imported in the prior year. If we allow that pattern each year for 20 years I believe we would be importing approximately 12 percent of what we are currently importing. Supply and demand is elementary concept Have you ever watched Are You Smarter Than a Fifth Grader? That is the show that came to mind when I read the letter titled, "Why is diesel cheaper than unleaded?" I thought just about everyone knew about supply and demand. Although the fuel indeed comes from the same barrel, gasoline is a more refined fuel. Diesel is a heavy fuel and in the winter when people are using more (heavy) heating oil, the cost of diesel goes up. In the summer, when people are using less heavy fuel and more gasoline for their cars, mowers, boats, etc., the cost of gasoline goes up. Ergo, supply and demand. I'm pretty sure I learned this in elementary school. Where's the coverage of fallen troops? As a reader of The Blade, I was very sorry to read about Officer Keith Dressel getting killed in the line of duty, but enough is enough. We had to see on TV a solid week about his funeral, and read about it every day, and still we hear about him and his family. It was his job! What about our soldiers getting killed in the line of duty? One hundred and four were killed in the Iraq war in April. You reported it like, ho-hum, another bunch killed. Does anyone think or even care about the families they left behind? Creation Museum's era dawns: Facility offers 'dinosaurs' and biblical perspective &#149; Snip & Save &#149; Shop Blade products &#149; Front Page Reprints Reader Topics and Debate. &copy; 2007 The Blade. By using this service, you accept the terms of our . Please read them. The Toledo Blade Company, 541 N. Superior St., Toledo, OH 43660 , (419) 724-6000 To contact a specific department or an individual person, The Toledo Times &reg;
