http://space.newscientist.com/article/dn11958-cosmonauts-take-space-walk-in-shield-upgrade.html&cid Cosmonauts take space walk in shield upgrade - space - 31 May 2007 - New Scientist Space Cosmonauts take space walk in shield upgrade 13:30 31 May 2007 New Scientist Space and Reuters Flight engineer Oleg Kotov handles new shields for the Zvezda service module. Part of the international space station since 2000, Zvezda is only now having shields installed to fend off dangerous space junk (Image: NASA TV) New report highlights threats to space station New spacecraft fuel gauge may reduce space junk World's only space dust detector binned Two crew members ventured from the international space station on Wednesday to install metal shields designed to protect against the impact of orbital debris. Station commander Fyodor Yurchikhin and flight engineer Oleg Kotov floated out of an airlock on the Russian side of the station at 15.05 EDT (19.05 GMT), about an hour later than planned, due to a glitch with communications equipment. They were back inside about five and a half hours later. During the outing, the cosmonauts fitted five aluminium debris impact shields to the forward part of the crew's living quarters, a Russian-built module known as Zvezda that has been in orbit for seven years. The shields measure about 60 by 90 centimetres, and weigh up to 9 kilograms. Yurchikhin and Kotov also rerouted cables for satellite-navigation equipment that will be needed when Europe's uncrewed cargo ship makes its debut flight to the station later this year. NASA wants the Russian module upgraded to meet US safety standards. It was launched despite substandard shielding after Russia and the United States agreed to upgrade the structure once it was in orbit. That work began in 2002, but was interrupted by the 2003 Columbia disaster and subsequent grounding of the space shuttle fleet. Yurchikhin and Kotov have another spacewalk planned for June 6 to finish installing the shields, which are designed to protect against small and medium-sized particles of debris. At 17,500 miles per hour (28,162 kilometres per hour) even something as small as a fleck of paint can cause severe damage to the station. An impact with orbital debris "is our biggest risk," said Kirk Shireman, NASA's space station deputy programme manager. Other shielding upgrades to Russian-made station components are pending. If all the improvements are made, the chance a piece of debris or a micrometeoroid would puncture the station drops to 29 per cent from 55 per cent over its expected 15-year life, according to an independent task force report published in February. Construction of the $100-billion project is scheduled for completion in 2010, at which time the shuttle fleet is to be retired. For exclusive news and expert analysis every week to New Scientist Print Edition For what's in New Scientist magazine this week see for our free newsletter Moon might be best place to study Earth's climate Cosmonauts take space walk in shield upgrade Core of the galaxy catapults stars our way Water reveals the perfect spot for other Earths 'Seat belts' restrain galaxies' black holes Moon might be best place to study Earth's climate 16:46 31 May 2007 Fetuses experience stress earlier than thought 16:07 31 May 2007 Cosmonauts take space walk in shield upgrade 13:30 31 May 2007 Spintronic logic gate promises computing advance 12:05 31 May 2007 16:32 30 May 2007 File-sharing sites are being subverted for web attacks 12:36 30 May 2007 About New Scientist magazine © Copyright Reed Business Information Ltd.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-1&fd=R&url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/microsoft/Story/0,,2091771,00.html&cid=1116802255&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ Table-style computer with touch screen tipped as next big thing | Special reports | Guardian Unlimited Skip to main content Comment is free blog Arts & entertainment blog Tabletop touch screen tipped as next big thing Microsoft's coffee table: the future of computing? Microsoft buys online advertiser for record &#163;3bn Global frenzy as takeovers hit &#163;1 trillion Yahoo! shares soar on Microsoft merger talk Pressure builds on Microsoft over patents Kroes: Microsoft abusing position Google to erase information on billions of internet searches Microsoft could face new antitrust fines Microsoft warns of danger to digital music after record $1.5bn fine Table-style computer with touch screen tipped as next big thing Bobbie Johnson, technology correspondent Thursday an era when computers get ever smaller and more portable, it seems almost a throwback; but software giant Microsoft hopes a &pound;5,000 coffee table bristling with technology could be the next big step forward. Surface, a table-style PC with a touch-sensitive screen which replaces a traditional mouse and keyboard, was unveiled in California yesterday. Using a so-called "multi-touch" interface, people can move items around in front of them with their fingers or write on the table using a pen. The device, which measures 75cm (30in) across, may echo some of the earliest computer games built into the surface of pub tables, but Microsoft hopes it will launch a new generation of computers. Steve Ballmer, chief executive of Microsoft, said: "We envision a time when surface computing technologies will be pervasive, from tabletops and counters to the hallway mirror." The Surface table can interact with other devices such as mobile phones, music players and digital cameras. Users can place compatible gadgets on to the table and have the computer recognise them wirelessly. Matt Rosoff, an analyst with independent research group Directions on Microsoft, said: "Once you open it up to applications, what you can think of is limitless." The Surface will go on sale in the US later this year with a price tag of between $5,000 and $10,000 (&pound;2,026- &pound;5,041). But Microsoft claims that the price will drop quickly as more people buy it. Within three to five years it could be cheap enough for home users, although initially it is expected to be bought by large companies. Starwood hotels, which owns the Sheraton chain, has said it will install the Surface at its premises, and other early takers include the Las Vegas casino group Harrah's and mobile phone operator T-Mobile, which plans to use Surface PCs as displays in its high street shops. Touch screen computers have long been tipped as the next big thing, and a series of developments have pushed the technology to the forefront in recent months, including the forthcoming iPhone from Apple, which features a touchable screen instead of the buttons usually found on a mobile phone. The Surface machine can recognise several different touches at the same time, allowing people to use multiple fingers or have several people using the computer simultaneously. Stephen Brewster, of the University of Glasgow's department of computing science, said: "Using a PC is very much a solitary activity, but there's something very tangible about having something that you can share with other people." More from the Online team Send it to a friend Join our dating site today Guardian Unlimited &copy; Guardian News and Media Limited 2007
