ged with mail fraud, identity theft, fraud and money laundering, Soloway advertised a mass e-mail service that sent messages to an opt-in list of addresses but didn't actually use such a permission-based list, the indictment said. He also sold software products that customers could use themselves to send out mass e-mails. However, the product often didn't work, and if it did, it sent e-mails using forged headers. He also failed to offer promised support services, according to the court documents. In addition, when customers complained, Soloway threatened additional fees and referral to a collection agency. Soloway is also accused of sending out tens of millions of e-mails, often using forged e-mail addresses and domains in the "from" line, advertising his services. As a result, some people who legitimately owned the e-mail address or domain were blamed for the spam and were blacklisted by Internet service providers. The indictment also said that Soloway used programs and many different proxy computers in an effort to hide the source of the messages. Soloway conducted the spamming activities at least from late 2003 through early this year, according to the indictment. If convicted, Soloway faces fines of over $772,000, which is the amount he illegally obtained from his activities, as well as forfeiture of other money and property. Reprinted with permission from Story copyright 2006 International Data Group. All rights reserved. Dell opens new R&D center in India Japanese airline still unsure about earlier reservation systems failure Apple to put YouTube on Apple TV " If you're not frightened by the Chinese economic juggernaut, this may give you pause: China has been developing sophisticated tools..." " Google's planned purchase of ad giant DoubleClick should be stopped for a simple reason: It will make Google the world's..." Read more Government/Regulations posts Mozilla patches 6 Firefox bugs Jobs, Gates trade jests at rare joint appearance Jobs: Windows is hell itS