http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-6&fd=R&url=http://www.forbes.com/home/technology/2007/05/29/novell-linux-earnings-tech-cx_bc_0530novell.html&cid=1116797290&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ Novell's Dilemma - Forbes.com Computer Hardware & Software 05.30.07, 6:00 AM ET because of its partnership with . Hate Novell because its business stinks. ) tried to clear the air last week, big time. The Waltham, Mass., software company wrapped up a review of its options accounting practices that began late last year, and announced that it won't need to restate a decade's worth of financial results. The company also provided details on a controversial pact with Microsoft )--in a nutshell, Novell hasn't agreed to sell the scaly hides of 100 open-source developers to Bill Gates in exchange for a boxcar full of gold bars. Now it's back to business as usual. Unfortunately for Novell, business isn't good. Analysts expect the company's second-quarter earnings will come in around $4.7 million on Wednesday--that's a drop of of 50%. Worse yet, sales are set to slide to $235.1 million from $278.3 million. As a result, over the past year Novell's shares have plodded along, dropping from $7.82 to $7.55. The problem? For the past 10 years, booming sales of cheap software from Microsoft and open-source software vendors have sapped sales of Novell's venerable NetWare offering. Novell tried to adapt, first by repositioning itself as a vendor of open-source software with a string of acquisitions in 2003. Then it ticked off many of its newfound friends by announcing a deal with open-source foe Microsoft last November. One of Novell's open-source developers even resigned over the arrangement. Since then, there has been widespread speculation about the deal's terms. Novell offered up many of the details when it released its annual report last week after wrapping up its accounting review. It's now clear that Novell didn't agree that Linux violates any of Microsoft's patents--a key issue for the Linux faithful. True believers aren't satisfied with the arrangement--which has Microsoft selling support from Novell for open-source software--but some concede it could have been worse. The real bad news, of course, is that Novell also made its earlier preliminary results for the first quarter official: It confirmed that it lost $19.9 million on $229.6 million in sales. The upside? Novell has more than $1.8 billion worth of cash and short-term investments. And with its accounting review wrapped up, the company can now spread a little of that money around. The company could start buying back shares or it may even reward open-source developers with a few acquisitions, analysts say. Spreading a little of its money around in the open-source community may not make it any more popular, but at least it won't be the only software company accused of selling out. More On This Topic Novell Loss Alarms Investors ",">"); transformedStoryStr=transformedStoryStr.replaceAll(""","\""); out.write(transformedStoryStr); %--> Advertisement: Related Business Topics > Time and Attendance Systems Brought to you by the sponsors below A new book from brings the Himalaya experience home.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-4&fd=R&url=http://www.redherring.com/Article.aspx%3Fa%3D22429%26hed%3DNeighborhood%2BNetworks%2B%26sector%3DIndustries%26subsector%3DInternetAndServices&cid=1116788683&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ RED HERRING | Neighborhood Networks Thursday, the RH community - it's FREE Forget the welcome mat. Fatdoor wants you to meet your neighbors online. Raj Abhyanker knocked on more than 3,000 doors during his 2005 bid to become a city council member in the Silicon Valley suburb of . His efforts didnât land him a seat on the council, but they did plant the seed for his newest venture. Struck by how little people seemed to know others in their neighborhood, Mr. Abhayanker soon started work on Fatdoor, a social networking service that is designed to help neighbors get to know each other. âPeople spend more time on their computer now than they do talking to their neighbors face to face,â said Mr. Abhyanker, a patent attorney whose startup launched Monday night. Co-founded by Mr. Abhyanker and Chandu Thota, the lead developer of Microsoftâs Virtual Earth mapping software, Fatdoor users can map out their addresses on top of Microsoft maps and network with the people who live nearby. Fatdoor tools allow users to send messages to their neighbors, and form hyper-local groups around certain topics. âThereâs no easy or efficient way to reach out to the neighborhood with one button, to let them know that you lost a pet or youâre having work done on your house,â said Mr. Thota. With $1 million in funding from former PayPal CEO Bill Harris and Bertram Capital managing director Jeff Drazan, Fatdoor has tapped into growing investor interest in location specific sites designed to attract local residents and advertisers. But Fatdoor is moving into an increasingly crowded market that includes zip-code-based social networking and news delivery sites such as Outside.in and Backfence. Yahoo Groups and Meetup, meanwhile, let neighbors form groups. âIf you can aggregate traffic for small local businesses, everybody is trying to tap into that,â said media analyst Greg Sterling. A key challenge for these sites is to get enough users in a given location to contribute content so the sites do not appear empty. Fatdoor, for example, is seeding its site with Yellow Pages content. The company is also trying to forge relationships with local clubs in the hopes theyâll encourage members to sign up for the service, which started its test run in Ironically, Mr. Thota hopes to drive awareness of his new site the old fashioned wayâby word of mouth. âOnce you satisfy a couple of users in the neighborhood, theyâll start evangelizing the product to neighbors,â said Mr. Thota. âItâs very event driven. When people have a block party we see more signups from that street that night.â Outside.in highlights the hyper-local. Touchscreen technology allows for group computing. Sweden Opens Second Life Embassy Apple TV to Feature YouTube eBay Makes Social Networking Play Could not find the linkURL in the DB: /Article.aspx?a=22429&hed=Neighborhood+Networks+&sector=Industries&subsector=InternetAndServices. Letter from the Editor &copy; 1993-2006 Red Herring, Inc. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-1&fd=R&url=http://www.ndtvprofit.com/homepage/news.asp%3Fid%3D300758&cid=1116797290&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ Novell won't be punished for Microsoft deal - source BOSTON (Reuters) - A foundation that owns rights to much of the code behind Linux software has decided not to carry out threats to punish Novell Inc. over a deal with Microsoft Corp, a person familiar with the matter said. The nonprofit Free Software Foundation had threatened to take punitive action against Novell for entering into a patent agreement with Microsoft, whose Windows operating system is a rival to Linux and is seen as a foe by the open source community. Some saw the deal as endorsing Microsoft's claims that it holds patents to intellectual property behind some open source software. The foundation was reviewing whether to block Novell from getting access to the foundation-controlled components of Linux that will be distributed under the terms of a new licensing agreement that is being finalized. One of the pioneering forces behind the open source software movement, the foundation has decided not to include any language in the final draft of the agreement that will punish Novell, according to the person familiar with the foundation's deliberations. "This is good news for Novell," said Katherine Egbert, an analyst with Jefferies & Co." The foundation controls rights to a group of programs known as the GNU operating system, an important part of Linux. The group does not control the software's namesake, the Linux kernel, which is owned by another nonprofit, the Linux Foundation. Free Software Foundation Executive Director Peter Brown would not discuss the foundation's decision, but confirmed that it had finalized its proceedings. Novell and its main rival Red Hat Inc. sell standardized versions of Linux with custom features, maintenance plans and technical support. The two companies also sell other types of open source software, including OpenOffice, which competes with Microsoft Word; Excel and PowerPoint programs; and XenSource, a rival to EMC Corp.'s VMware software that boosts the efficiency of server computers. Sales of Novell's SUSE Linux products accounted for 5 percent of the $967 million in revenue that the company reported last year. The deal with Microsoft has turned into a far bigger cash generator, bringing in two upfront payments totaling $348 million. The two companies agreed to sell their products jointly, develop technologies that make it easier for businesses to use Linux alongside Windows software, and not sue each other's customers for any patent violations when using their software. Some members of the open source community said that deal would undermine the patent security of Linux software and give Microsoft an edge in persuading businesses to use Microsoft products over Linux and other types of open source software. The foundation is scheduled to disclose its decision on the Novell matter by June 4 on its Web site, www.fsf.org, when it will post the final draft of the new license, which is known as the General Public License version 3, or GPLv3. Novell Chief Financial Officer Dana Russell declined comment on the matter. Chidambaram says inflation declines to 5.06 pct Finance Minister Palaniappan Chidambaram said on Thursday that wholesale price inflation had declined to 5.06 percent i... Chidambaram says inflation declines to 5.06 pct Finance Minister Palaniappan Chidambaram said on Thursday that wholesale price inflation had declined to 5.06 percent i... Rains may leave 3 mln tonnes sugar cane uncrushed Early arrival of monsoon rains may force sugar factories in Maharashtra and Karnataka to shut operations leaving at lea... Cabinet approves new airport for Mumbai Union cabinet on Thursday approved construction of a new airport in Mumbai, the country's financial capital, the civil ... TCS says margins take big hit on rupee rise India's top software services exporter, Tata Consultancy Servic