ons for display on maps. O'Reilly Where 2.0 Conference 2007 in San Jose, Google debuted Street View, a feature that it said gives Google Maps users the perspective of drivers and pedestrians in a city. That offers a deeper and more detailed view of locations than aerial images provide, Google claimed. The search engine market leader initially is providing Street View imagery in its maps of New York, Las Vegas, Miami, Denver and the San Francisco Bay Area. It said that more cities will be added "in the near future." has been at the forefront of immersive online maps, having introduced in late 2005 so-called bird's-eye views that enabled users to tilt aerial images and view them from different angles. Last November, Microsoft began making 3-D views of cities available in its Windows Live Search Maps software, a feature that lets users zoom in and out of urban areas and get what Microsoft describes as photorealistic views of buildings and other landmarks. On Tuesday, the software vendor of cities for which it offers 3-D views, adding New York and eight other locations. Meanwhile, Google said its new Mapplets technology supports the development of lightweight applications for Google Maps, similar to the way that can be used with the company's iGoogle personalized home page. From a technical standpoint, Mapplets are Gadgets that can be coded to manipulate maps using Javascript calls derived from the application programming interface for Google Maps, according to the company. Previously, developers could build an application on top of Google Maps and make it available on a specific Web site. Now, Google said, developers and end users alike can package multiple Mapplets on a single map to create mashups of the "mini applications" supported by the new technology. Mapplets are currently supported on a developer's of Google Maps for users who want to try them out. Developers can find more information about how to create Mapplets on a separate on Google's Web site. Reprinted w