 said, then shrugged, paused and smiled. "It's like giving a glass of ice water to somebody in hell," he said. Although the comment likely won't rank with one of Jobs' most famous Windows swipes -- his "The only problem with is they just have no taste, they have absolutely no taste" -- the remark got a loud laugh from the D: audience. Ironically, during a later Q&A with attendees, Jobs acknowledged that he has read some of the entries on "The Secret Diary of Steve Jobs" blog, where an unidentified writer known as Fake Steve Jobs (FSJ) poses as the Apple CEO. On the blog today, FSJ commented on "his" Windows = hell riff. "The analogy isn't perfect," said FSJ. "You can't get out of hell . You can get out of Windows." Related Computerworld Analysis and Discussion: How Steve Jobs blew his iPhone keynote Bill Gates' piracy confession Gates: I need more visas (and flying beer) Steve Jobs, Slayer of DRM Mac OS X better than Vista which is better than XP which is better than ... Apple's mobile phone: A must-have product, or will it go the way of the Newton? Jobs, Gates trade jests at rare joint appearance Steve Jobs to speak at WWDC; A look back at past shows How Steve Jobs blew his iPhone keynote " Pilot fish arrives at work one day to find everyone in IT in a panic. "The story was that our..." " After my software installation fiasco with Kodak's EasyShare 5300 multifunction ink jet printer last week, the last thing..." Read more Windows posts Mozilla patches 6 Firefox bugs Jobs, Gates trade jests at rare joint appearance Jobs: Windows is hell itSMF-USA says online election may have been compromised Nine burning questions about how Vista is Hackers can hijack PCs using Firefox add-ons Don't Believe the Hype: The 21 Biggest Technology Flops We fondly recall 21 overpromoted products and technologies that utterly failed to live up to their hype. You choose the biggest flop of all. Why cell phones are still grounded Cell phone calls are banned from flights because neither the 