http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-0&fd=R&url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/front/4849501.html&cid=1116827240&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ NASA chief doubts urgency of global warming | Chron.com - Houston Chronicle " width="11" height="11" border="0"> Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Travel News & Features Legal & Public Notices May 30, 2007, 11:53PM NASA chief doubts global warming is front-burner issue Remarks called irresponsible by environmentalists Copyright 2007 Houston Chronicle NASA Administrator Michael Griffin, whose agency's observations of the Earth have helped to confirm a global rise in temperature, said he doubts that global warming is an issue mankind should address. "I have no doubt that global  that a trend of global warming exists," Griffin told National Public Radio's in an interview set for broadcast today. "I'm not sure it's fair to say that is a problem we must wrestle with." NPR made a transcript of Griffin's remarks available Wednesday. "To assume that is a problem is to assume that the state of the Earth's climate today is the optimal climate, the best climate that we could have or ever have had and that we need to take steps to make sure it doesn't change," he said. "First of all, I don't think it's within the power of human beings to assure that the climate does not change, as millions of years of history have shown. "Second of all, I guess I would ask which human beings  where and when  are to be accorded the privilege of deciding that this particular climate that we might have right here today, right now, is the best climate for all other human beings. I think that's a rather arrogant position for people to take." Environmental groups criticized Griffin's remarks as irresponsible. Griffin's remarks suggest NASA is prepared to ignore the findings gathered by its own satellites and scientists, said Philip Clapp, president of the National Environmental Trust, a nonpartisan watchdog group. "The science performed by NASA as well as scientists around the world shows that global warming is no longer an environmental issue. It's a rapidly advancing human disaster," Clapp said. "Millions of people across the world will face hunger, flooding from a rise in sea levels and water scarcity. To try to hide that by saying we don't know what the climate should be is ignoring the science of his own agency." However, David Mould, NASA's chief spokesman, said Griffin was attempting in his remarks to characterize the space agency's role in assessing environmental issues. "NASA is providing the vast majority of the data on global climate. We analyze some of the data," Mould said. "But the policies beyond the analysis of the data, he was trying to say, are outside the scope of NASA's mission. Others, including Congress, will decide that." Indeed, Griffin said in the interview that NASA is chartered by Congress to study global warming and not to combat it. But Griffin's assessment merely reflects a Bush administration reluctance to address a major environmental problem, according to David Willett, chief spokesman for the Sierra Club, the nation's oldest environmental advocacy group. "What makes it doubly concerning is that NASA is on the front line, really able to sound the warning bell of what's happening to our planet because they get the planet-wide view," Wiliett said. "They have given the scientific consensus already. They should feel an obligation to be looking at the issue of global warming as a problem that needs to be addressed, not as a phenomenon that simply needs to be studied." Last year, James Hansen, the space agency's chief climatologist, charged that a young political appointee in the agency's public affairs branch had tried to stop him from speaking out on his long-standing concerns over global warming. When Congress took issue, Griffin responded with a policy that affirmed the agency's commitment to open scientific and technical inquiry and public disclosure. NASA chief doubts urgency of global warming Man arrested for allegedly flashing HISD students New hurricane forecast calls for 5 intense storms High bacteria counts at Galveston beaches Baby girl's survival of hanging called a miracle Continental sues union over pilot who drank Civil unions bill signed in New Hampshire Ex-NASA staffer alleges political attack A PR scandal rocks NASA Enron expected a lot in exchange for political gifts Once on death row, it might not matter Civilians in shuttle probe on NASA's payroll Law firm's Enron work comes under scrutiny Hear what Neil Armstrong really said on the moon Griffin on global warming: Don't bother Lawyers fear legal impact of Andersen Part 2: Borderline cases raise questions about death penalty Buy Photos & Page Prints 2005-Present Historic Page Prints 1901-2004 Copyright Notice & Privacy Policy
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-2&fd=R&url=http://www.earthtimes.org/articles/show/67811.html&cid=1116692882&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ The science of Genesis: two museums open in North America The science of Genesis: two museums open in North America Wed, 30 May 2007 23:16:01GMT Create your own RSS Washington - Creationism, in a direct challenge to Charles Darwin's theory of evolution, has found a new means of spreading its message in the United States. Two new museums are opening this summer in the United States and Canada, which present the story of Earth's creation according to the literal teachings of the Bible in the Book of Genesis. The Creation Museum in Petersburg, Kentucky, across the Mississippi River from Cincinnati, Ohio, opened on Monday and describes itself as a "counter (to) evolutionary natural history museums that turn minds against Scripture ­ and Jesus Christ, the Creator of the universe." The Big Valley Creation Science Museum is slated to open Saturday in the Canadian province of Alberta. The US has long been more open to the ideas of creation than most countries, but what makes these museums unique is that they tackle Darwin's evolutionary theory head-on, offering up scientific evidence to back the creationist's version of events. Both for example proudly display fossils, bones and high-tech models of dinosaurs. The 27-million-dollar Kentucky museum has what critics described as Disney-like rides and showcases that place prehistoric children among the giant reptiles. The problem according to scientists: dinosaurs roamed the planet more than 60 million years ago. Creationists contend that the world is no more than 6,000 years old and say the museums display "considerable evidence that not only did dinosaurs exist recently, but that humans existed with them," according to the Big Valley museum in Canada. Museums are only the latest battleground in a decades-long struggle for supremacy between the two camps, beginning with a court ruling in Tennessee in 1927 - known in the US as the Scopes Monkey Trial - that upheld a state law barring evolution from being taught in schools. It took the US Supreme Court another 40 years to rule such laws unconstitutional, and another 20 years after that to strike creationism out of scientific teaching entirely. In 1987 the court ruled that creation could be taught in current affairs, philosophy or history classes, but not as a science. Though a majority of Americans believe there was some form of divine intervention in the world's development, proponents of creationism have gained back little ground since the 1987 ruling. According to a 2005 poll by the magazine Science, only 40 per cent of Americans accept a theory of evolution that leaves no room for divine intervention, compared to about 95 per cent of scientists. But a majority also believe that evolution, and not creation, should be taught in science class. That hasn't stopped a vocal group of mainly Protestant, Evangelical Christians from launching efforts to keep creationist teaching in public schools as a counterweight to Darwinism. School boards in various US states over the last decade have tried to place restrictions on teaching evolution - such as a "disclaimer" in textbooks - but none of the initiatives have lasted long. Now, with the opening of the two museums dedicated to creationism, it has been the turn of the scientific community to protest. More than 900 scientists in Kentucky, Ohio and Indiana signed a petition arguing that the museum's teachings were scientifically inaccurate, and voicing concern about the effect it might have on students. "Students who accept this material as scientifically valid are unlikely to succeed in science courses at the college level," according to the petition, launched by the National Centre for Science Education. "These students will need remedial instruction in the nature of science." At least 3,500 teachers from around the US signed an even stronger worded petition charging the organization running the US museum, Answers in Genesis (AIG), with "a nefarious campaign to institutionalize a lie." "This opposition hates the fact that the Creation Museum is showing the world that the Bible's history is confirmed by real science," Ken Ham, president of AIG, wrote in his internet blog. dpa cc prUS-Religion/Science/ FEATURE: The science of Genesis: two museums open in North America By Chris Cermak, dpa = Washington- Creationism, in a direct challenge to Charles Darwin's theory of evolution, has found a new means of spreading its message in the United States. Two new museums are opening this summer in the United States and Canada, which present the story of Earth's creation according to the literal teachings of the Bible in the Book of Genesis. The Creation Museum in Petersburg, Kentucky, across the Mississippi River from Cincinnati, Ohio, opened on May 28 and describes itself as a "counter (to) evolutionary natural history museums that turn minds against Scripture ­ and Jesus Christ, the Creator of the universe." The Big Valley Creation Science Museum opens June 5 in the state of Alberta, Canada. The US has long been more open to the ideas of creation than most countries, but what makes these museums unique is that they tackle Darwin's evolutionary theory head-on, offering up scientific evidence to back the creationist's version of events. Both for example proudly display fossils, bones and high-tech models of dinosaurs. The 27-million-dollar Kentucky museum has what critics described as Disney-like rides and showcases that place prehistoric children among the giant reptiles. The problem according to scientists: dinosaurs roamed the planet more than 60 million years ago. Creationists contend that the world is no more than 6,000 years old and say the museums display "considerable evidence that not only did dinosaurs exist recently, but that humans existed with them," according to the Big Valley museum in Canada. Museums are only the latest battleground in a decades-long struggle for supremacy between the two camps, beginning with a court ruling in Tennessee in 1927 - known in the US as the Scopes Monkey Trial - that upheld a state law barring evolution from being taught in schools. It took the US Supreme Court another 40 years to rule such laws unconstitutional, and another 20 years after that to strike creationism out of scientific teaching entirely. In 1987 the court ruled that creation could be taught in current affairs, philosophy or history classes, but not as a science. Though a majority of Americans believe there was some form of divine intervention in the world's development, proponents of creationism have gained back little ground since the 1987 ruling. According to a 2005 poll by the magazine Science, only 40 per cent of Americans accept a theory of evolution that leaves no room for divine intervention, compared to about 95 per cent of scientists. But a majority also believe that evolution, and not creation, should be taught in science class. That hasn't stopped a vocal group of mainly Protestant, Evangelical Christians from launching efforts to keep creationist teaching in public schools as a counterweight to Darwinism. School boards in various US states over the last decade have tried to place restrictions on teaching evolution - such as a "disclaimer" in textbooks - but none of the initiatives have lasted long. Now, with the opening of the two museums dedicated to creationism, it has been the turn of the scientific community to protest. More than 900 scientists in Kentucky, Ohio and Indiana signed a petition arguing that the museum's teachings were scientifically inaccurate, and voicing concern about the effect it might have on students. "Students who accept this material as scientifically valid are unlikely to succeed in science courses at the college level," according to the petition, launched by the National Centre for Science Education. "These students will need remedial instruction in the nature of science." At least 3,500 teachers from around the US signed an even stronger worded petition charging the organization running the US museum, Answers in Genesis (AIG), with "a nefarious campaign to institutionalize a lie." "This opposition hates the fact that the Creation Museum is showing the world that the Bible's history is confirmed by real science," Ken Ham, president of AIG, wrote in his internet blog. Copyright &copy; 2007 Respective Author Email this article (Click Here) Share this article on &raquo; - Dinosaurs in Noah's Ark...at Ky's Creation Museum | 30 May 2007 Archaeologists uncover fertility shrine in central Greece World record price set for Aboriginal painting Cannes rolls out the red carpet for 60th festival Pierre Boulez: Janacek in Vienna will be last opera production Rabindranath Tagore - his work will live for generations The views expressed in the articles are not necessarily those of earthtimes.org and we accept no responsibility for the views or opinions expressed in the articles either direct or indirect. , All Rights Reserved.
