http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-6&fd=R&url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/afp_world_business/view/279395/1/.html&cid=1116735750&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ Friday, June 01, 2007 7 Day News Archive Apple sells music without piracy protection Posted: 31 May 2007 0729 hrs > " onclick="Next();" src="/images/butt_next.gif" width="18" height="15" /> SAN FRANCISCO: Apple on Wednesday began selling music free of anti-copying software at its iTunes online store, stripping away copyright protection lambasted by the company's iconic chief executive. Apple launched iTunes Plus with a menu of EMI Group music including songs from Coldplay, The Rolling Stones, Frank Sinatra, John Coltrane, Pink Floyd, and Paul McCartney. Songs cost US&#036;1.29 each, 30 cents more than standard iTunes offerings, but are "virtually indistinguishable from original recordings" and aren't fettered by Digital Rights Management (DRM) software that blocks copying, Apple said. "Our customers are very excited about the freedom and amazing sound quality of iTunes Plus," Apple chief executive Steve Jobs said in a release. "We expect more than half of the songs on iTunes will be offered in iTunes Plus versions by the end of this year." Jobs denounced digital rights management software in February in an open letter calling on the music recording industry to abandon the practice of insisting it be incorporated into digital music sold online. Major recording studios fired back that the safeguard is needed to prevent pirates from making myriad unauthorised copies and denying owners their due payments for music. Cupertino, California-based Apple and EMI, based in Britain, formed an alliance in April to sell DRM-free music. "This is a tremendous milestone for digital music," EMI Group chief executive Eric Nicoli said of the new iTunes offering. "Consumers are going to love listening to higher quality iTunes Plus tracks from their favourite EMI artists with no usage restrictions." The removal of DRM software means that for the first time, music bought at iTunes can be played on rival MP3 players, including Microsoft's Zune. US economy slows to crawl, but some see rebound Mazda to recall over 260,000 cars China stocks close mixed, concerns remain after tax hike Malaysia's Proton reports losses for four straight quarters ANA considers low-cost carrier Malaysian, Philippine firms launch first SMS remittance service Hoya to finally launch bid for Pentax in June Microsoft rethinks computer with coffee-table design Dollar gains against euro on Fed minutes Ryanair orders 27 Boeing aircraft worth US&#036;1.9b Hong Kong set for grand opening of new terminal Star Alliance hopes to bring in Indian, Russian airlines India grows faster-than-expected 9.4% South Koreans find huge oilfield off Kamchatka Peninsula China to open up key domestic air routes to competition China Eastern says no final deal with Singapore Airlines yet SKorea current account deficit hits 10-year high BHP Billiton names new chief executive YouTube videos to play on Apple TV Apple sells music without piracy protection Bristol-Myers Squibb pleads guilty to lying about patent deal Entropia to create cash-based Internet world in China Fed members see economy rebounding, 'upside' inflation risks Four Ernst & Young partners indicted for tax shelter fraud BP refining marketing chief John Manzoni steps down Malaysian firm may have overstated revenues by &#036;157m CBS buys Internet music-sharing network Last.fm Japan's Matsushita says 3 million appliances at risk of fire IT retailer CDW to be bought by equity firm Malaysia's Maxis to spend 15 billion ringgit to grow existing markets Copyright &copy; MCN International Pte Ltd. All Rights Reserved. Use of this Site is subject to our of use. Your continued use of this Site shall be construed as your agreement to abide by our
