http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-3&fd=R&url=http://australianit.news.com.au/articles/0,7204,21824769%255E15306,00.html&cid=1116814949&ei=jv1eRobJFYXoqgPDpanNDQ Palm unveils compact PC | Australian IT AEST Palm unveils compact PC Franklin Paul in New York | PALM has introduced a compact portable computer to accompany its Treo smartphone. The new "Foleo" is about the size of a hardcover book and, at 1.1kg, half the weight of other small laptop computers. It is designed to be used with a smartphone, to help business travellers better manage their email and documents by offering a 10-inch screen, full keyboard and wireless. Palm, best known for personal digital assistants (PDAs) and Treo phones, said it expected the Foleo to eventually work with rival smartphones such as Research In Motion's BlackBerry and Apple's iPhone, although it has not discussed technology-sharing agreements with those companies. Company founder Jeff Hawkins said he expected unit sales of Foleo, priced at $US599 ($729) to be smaller than Treo units sales at first. "Ultimately, it will make smartphones more successful," Mr Hawkins said. "The volume we anticipate selling of Foleo initially will be small compared to the volume of Treos. It's not going to be a driver in the short term. But it allows us to rethink how you design smartphones." The Foleo may signal a shift in focus for Palm, which dominated the market for personal digital assistants (PDAs) after it launched its original Palm Pilot in 1996. Its PDA sales dwarfed those of rivals such as Hewlett-Packard and Sony, but PDA demand dwindled early in this decade as similar features were built into cheaper mobile phones. Palm's Treo, which combines a phone with its PDA operating system, eventually became the company's signature product with shipments of 2.3 million units in the last fiscal year. Tim Bajarin, an analyst with Creative Strategies in San Jose, said mass appeal for the Foleo is not likely, since smartphones represented a fraction of the overall mobile phone market and only a portion of those customers would be interested in carrying a separate device. Moreover, many business travellers were resigned to carrying a smartphone and a full portable computer. "I will argue that this product is for the 'road warrior.' It's not probably for mainstream, it's more of a business tool," Mr Bajarin said. The Foleo will compete with low-cost laptop PCs. "It will hit a nerve with a certain segment and in that sense has a lot of potential," he said. With Foleo, Palm enters the burgeoning world of open source computing. Palm's device would also compete with Dell, which last week started selling Linux-based PCs. "One big unknown is what happens if the open source world decides to embrace (Foleo), as the first mobile Linux portable. It actually has potential ... if the open source world decides that this is a powerful way of expending the Linux franchise," Mr Bajarin said. Separately, Palm chief executive Ed Colligan played down speculation that the company was for sale, saying that the new product proves it is working on innovation. "We're not focused on figuring out how to sell the company," he said on the CNBC television network. Email To A Friend Email To A Friend Information provided on this page will not be used for any other purpose than to notify the recipient of the article you have chosen. From here you can use the Social Web links to save Palm unveils compact PC to a social bookmarking site. Microsoft's new PC surfaces A million say Do Not Call ACCC Singapore's lapdog - Telstra Google takes big step offline Alleged 'spam king' arrested TiVo posts maiden profit Inline video player has not loaded - you can still go directly to the video player Also in Australian IT Alleged 'spam king' arrested A 27-year-old man described as one of the world's most prolific spammers has been arrested in the US. Google takes big step offline Top speed for $50 HP opens Defence account HEWLETT-PACKARD Australia ha