http://www.chicagotribune.com/business/chi-070530itunes-story,0,6913562.story%3Fcoll%3Dchi-bizfront-hed&cid Apple begins selling unprotected EMI music on iTunes | Chicago Tribune A $100 million mystery Red wolf pups unveiled at Lincoln Park Zoo Billboard called racy, wrong A most hollow oratory on Memorial Day Harry Potter theme park coming to Orlando's Universal Studios Stocks Up After Takeover News, GDP Data New York Stock Exchange City disaster chief resigns Apple begins selling unprotected EMI music on iTunes Published May 30, 2007, 10:53 AM CDT Apple Inc. began selling digital music from EMI Group Plc without copyright protection software on its iTunes store, giving Chief Executive Officer Steve Jobs a victory in his campaign to see all online songs sold that way. EMI announced in April it would offer its catalog, excluding music by The Beatles, without digital rights management software. Apple is selling the DRM-free songs for $1.29 each through a new "iTunes Plus" service and continues to offer copy-protected versions for 99 cents, the company said today in a statement. Jobs in February asked EMI, Universal Music Group, Sony BMG Music Entertainment and Warner Music Group Corp. to let Apple remove DRM software from iTunes tracks. While the software helps stop illegal copying, it doesn't let buyers play songs on devices other than Apple's iPod. EMI's move may pressure the other labels to follow suit. The four control 70 percent of the world's music. "How fast other music labels come on board depends on what happens with this grand Apple-EMI experiment," said Michael Gartenberg, an analyst at JupiterResearch in New York. "It was a seminal moment for the industry to have a hardware vendor and content owner talk about the implications for what a DRM-free world might look like." Shares of London-based EMI fell 1.5 pence to 274.75 pence. Cupertino, California-based Apple, also maker of the Macintosh computer, rose 91 cents to $115.26 at 11:05 a.m. New York time on the Nasdaq Stock Market. They climbed 35 percent this year before today. Separately, Apple today said it created an area on iTunes to offer free course lectures, language lessons and sports highlights from universities including Stanford and Duke. Apple expects more than half of the 5 million songs on iTunes to be offered in the DRM-free format by the end of the year, Jobs said today. EMI's DRM-free catalog numbers in the "hundreds of thousands" of songs, the company said. "We've seen a tremendous amount of interest from independent labels and even other major labels, and the other majors are interested in seeing how this goes," iTunes chief Eddy Cue said in an interview. "EMI has been a leader in this. Everybody else gets to watch and learn." Universal, Sony BMG and Warner have all experimented with selling unprotected tracks online. Jobs, 52, called on the labels to offer DRM-free music in an open letter on Apple's Web site that cast him as a champion for consumers. Songs purchased on iTunes only play on the iPod, while music bought from rival sites is tied to gadgets that work with their DRM systems, Jobs said in the Feb. 6 essay. EMI, the world's third-largest music label, said at the time it recognized the lack of flexibility between music players was "increasingly becoming an issue for music consumers." Two months later, Jobs joined EMI CEO Eric Nicoli on stage in London to announce the new licensing arrangement. Nicoli said the DRM-free options should help spur overall digital sales and may offset a decline in CD sales. EMI said digital music may account for 25 percent of revenue by 2010. EMI represents more than 1,300 artists, including Coldplay, the Rolling Stones, Pink Floyd, Norah Jones and Lily Allen, according to the company's Web site. While Apple will be the first to offer its DRM-free catalog, EMI said it expects to make the tracks available to other distribution partners. EMI said it expects a "significant jump" in sales because of the DRM-free option, which delivers songs with better audio quality, said Barney Wragg, head of the digital business at EMI. "There's a whole range of people who have been online who have been put off because they didn't understand this issue of interoperability," Wragg said in an interview. "We're really pleased that Apple had exactly the same vision that we did for how the market would develop." The DRM-free songs are twice as large as the copy-protected version and may take twice as long to download depending on the speed of customers' Internet connections, Cue said. The Beatles' catalog, which includes hits such as "Let It Be" and "Yesterday," isn't legally distributed on the Internet. While EMI has rights to distribute the group's recordings on CDs and other physical formats, Apple Corps Ltd. hasn't yet granted digital rights to the songs. Apple Corps is owned by Paul McCartney, Ringo Starr, John Lennon's widow Yoko Ono and the estate of George Harrison. McCartney, who began offering his solo catalog online for the first time in recent weeks, told BillBoard Magazine this month that a decision to sell the group's music online is "virtually settled." EMI had no news today about the Beatles move online, Wragg said. Through iTunes, which operates in 22 countries, Apple has sold more than 2.5 billion songs since April 2003. The service has more than 70 percent of the market for music downloads, according to the NPD Group Inc. in Port Washington, New York. Chicago Bears Super Bowl coverage Wonders of the world 10 for the road Send a news tip What's in it for you? The day's top stories e-mailed to you each weekday. Exclusive access to Tribune experts for help with homework or research A free archive search of a year's worth of Chicago Tribune stories. Advice for making the most of a special night out. This month's featured offers include: Subscriber Advantage members can enjoy special offers such as save $30 off a pair of Camelot tickets with Michael York receive FREE Child Admission to the Nature Museum and , courtesy of Chicago Tribune Subscriber Advantage.
