http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-2&fd=R&url=http://www.tgdaily.com/content/view/32261/128/&cid=1116814949&ei=jv1eRobJFYXoqgPDpanNDQ TG Daily - Palm Foleo: What were they thinking? Palm Foleo: What were they thinking? Wednesday, May 30, 2007 22:45 Opinion &ndash; We see a lot of new hardware and software that often leaves us scratching our head what the purpose and market opportunity of that new product could be. Palm set high expectations with a new mobile device that was announced to describe a new mobile category &ndash; and Foleo left us speechless. Palm can&rsquo;t be serious about this one. Palm unveils Foleo (10 images) ... Jeff Hawkins is without doubt one of the smartest guys in Silicon Valley. It is largely because of his vision that the PDA category was created in the second half of the 1990s; he brought us the first the first tablet-PC like device in the late 1980s; he was the first one to commercialize a smartphone in the form factor we are used to today and he continues to help Palm define a direction in a market that gets more competitive every day. When Palm told us yesterday that Jeff Hawkins was about to announce a new mobile device in a category we weren&rsquo;t aware of until today, of course we made sure that we wouldn&rsquo;t miss the webcast presentation. And since Hawkins turns 50 on June 1, we expected something big. Kinda like a birthday present that he would give to himself. And boy, what a present that was. We believe that there is a good chance that he won&rsquo;t forget Jeff Hawkins and Donna Dubinsky after the announcement of the Handspring Visor PDA in 2000. This new product, called Foleo, turns out to be something that looks like a small laptop computer, but it doesn&rsquo;t act like one. In fact, its functionality is much closer to that of a smartphone, but you can&rsquo;t use it to make calls. So what is it? It is an extension to the smartphone, a device that enables Palm to pitch to you two $500 products instead of only one. Hawkins said that Foleo is light, it feels good in your hand and it has a large keyboard and 10&rdquo; screen that come in handy when you want to view those pictures, PDF or Powerpoint attachments and write emails that are longer than just ten words &ndash; which admittedly is a painful task on today&rsquo;s smartphones. So there really is an interesting thought in this and it has some unique features, such as the instant on/off, but $500 for a large screen and keyboard for your cellphone? For a device that can&rsquo;t do anything by itself (well, ok, you can browse the web and send/receive emails, if there&rsquo;s a Wi-Fi connection close by), and a device that you would have to bring along on your business trips in addition to your cellphone, your laptop and your iPod? I somewhat have the feeling that Palm will need a small miracle to turn the Foleo into commercial success. But let&rsquo;s just imagine for a moment that this category does succeed: What else could follow? Apple could create a video iPod companion. A $300 portable, DVD-player-like device without the capability to play DVDs, but to stream videos from the iPod via Wi-Fi (I still hope that we will see this feature in iPods this year) or from a Compact Flash card. Would you buy such a product? I am not so sure. Jeff Hawkins during the unveiling of the Treo smartphone at Comdex Fall 2001. Hawkins believes that there is a substantial market opportunity for Foleo, as - according to a market survey - 24.2 million people use their smartphones to send and receive emails. But realistically, not all of those users have Palm OS and Windows Mobile devices. There are many users who have Blackberrys, Symbian-based phones and the future will bring lots of people using iPhones &ndash; all of which will not be supported by the first version of the Foleo. Take all of those people out of the equation and then subtract from that all those people who have Treos and Windows PDA phones and do not need notebooks during their business trips. Suddenly that market does not look quite as big anymore. The software side is another problem area for the Foleo. Beyond email and web browsing, there isn&rsquo;t really anything the device can do. And even web browsing is somewhat limited, as the device isn&rsquo;t strong enough to play YouTube videos, we were told. Some other applications are there as well, but according to Hawkins, software such as an image viewer was thrown in because the application apparently was created more or less by accident by someone on the side and not necessarily with the Foleo in mind. Foleo could benefit from unique applications, but it is exactly this area that appears to have no direction. The hopes are on a developer community that Palm hopes will grow around Foleo. Will that be enough? Gee guys, why doesn&rsquo;t Foleo have a VoIP application built in to make Wi-Fi calls? The good thing about the device is that we don&rsquo;t know too much about its specifications yet and Palm has time to revise the product. For $500, a large keyboard and a large screen are not enough. Even a processor that can handle video playback, reasonable flash storage, GPS capability and battery life of more five hours would make Foleo look like a risky business proposition. But then, we all may be wrong and Hawkins will be able to once again turn his vision into a successful product. We just aren&rsquo;t convinced yet. What do you think? Would you buy the Foleo? How would you use it? Let us know and write a comment in the form below. This product, for me, would determine Palm's future... May 30, 2007 23:32 This product, for me, would determine Palm's future, after a string of delays and lacklustre products. This is the nail in the coffin. Palm is finished. May 30, 2007 23:34 I would never buy something like this, its just one more electronic that I don't need, like things like the iphone that combine an MP3 player and a Phone...I already have a MP3 player, and a cellphone, why spend another $600 to get them...both...again? Same goes for Folio, I have a Smartphone, and I have a Laptop, My laptop has wireless, and a big keyboard, plus it can browse the internet, my Smartphone is a smaller more limited version of my laptop, why would I spend another $500 for a Larger MORE limited version of my Smartphone? May 30, 2007 23:37 Well, there are a lot of people who may need it... but for $500, it is not really worth it... maybe if it was say about $99 or so, i would not mind tryin it... i am sure hawkins will bring out some changes in it with some time.. it is best to just wait and watch i guess... Remember the IBM WorkPad Z50? May 30, 2007 23:38 I do, because I bought one when it was being discontinued. Very much like the Foleo, albeit without the wireless option and based on Windows CE. Don't get me wrong -- I still use the Z50 on occasion, but it's nowhere near my primary device for contact management, etc. Palm must believe it can successfully target a niche market, but without powerful dedicated applications, it'll be an uphill climb. May 30, 2007 23:44 If it can do Goole Apps for Education I will buy hundreds of them for students...think of this as a potential Web 2/Web 3 device, just the right specs for grades 4-8. Between a laptop and a handheld - a tweener! What do I think? May 30, 2007 23:48 You captured everything I thought about the Foleo. I use a Treo and it is a horrible product. I always thought of Palm as a being a innovative company, always ahead of the game and that the masses would eventually catch up. But boy...What the F#$% were they thinking.... I can already do way MORE with my Windows Mobile (H... I can already do way MORE with my Windows Mobile (HTC) phone/pocket PC, which cost considerably less. If I really need a large keyboard & screen, it probably means I need to use full-size software, in which case I might as well just open up my laptop and be done with it. So very, very weak Let's see, for $500 I can buy a device that has no real purpose except to extend the functionality of my cell phone (a device I generally see as a necessary evil as it is). Hmm... No, I think not. The foleo is a nice idea, but it does nothing but make your smartphone bigger.. Who wants to have a larger screen if that is all it does.. no video capability? Not in todays world.. I like Palm and have purchased many of their products. But I just do not see this one being a good venture without many many fixes from the current design. Wi-Fi is a standard, five hour battery life, what good is that at my desk at work... keyboard? I could type with my thumbs without paying $500... not worth it palm....try again... Truly disappointing product. Palm could've knocked this out of the park with a market killer, but they came up with this. I own a Nokia E61 myself - integrated WiFi, QWERTY keyboard, GPRS / EDGE / UTMS, etc, ability to open / edit most MS-Office formats - and this is a product that was launched almost a year ago. To compete with the iPhone, the upcoming Nokia N95, the existing Treo 680 / 700 and the new range of Blackberrys - $500 is a lot of dollar for a product that is best "described" as a companion / add-on Toshiba had the Libretto. Nobody bought it. And probably for the same reasons. When I want a portable device, I want to be able to put it somewhere, like in a pocket, on my belt, or (in the case of my Abacus PalmOS watch) on a wristband. When I don't care about portability, I use a fullsized notebook. Where does this fit? Foleo -- A sinking ship Personally, I would say that if the device is released by Palm as it has been described in this article, without a serious overhaul and a huge amount of additional functionality, interface-ability and interactivity added to it, it's going to wind up being an even bigger and faster flop than Sony's ill-starred PSP. Palm finally lost the plot People would have to be crazy to buy the Foleo. It's like dragging a laptop around that doesn't do anything useful. My daughter has a Fujitsu 10&#189;" widescreen ultraportable notebook that is the same size as the Foleo, but it's a real computer, not some toy. If you are going to cart around something of that size, get the Fujitsu or Asus tiny notebook. I use a HP 6828 PDA-phone and it probably does EVERYTHING that the Foleo and an accompanying smartphone can do, but it fits into my shirt pocket. I run three businesses from that PDA-phone and it syncs to my desktop when I'm in my office. How good is that? Why would a Blackberry or O2A Atom user change over to a Foleo? They'd have to be crazy. Palm has finally lost the plot. I used a Palm Professional when US Robotics owned the company and it was fantastic for its day. But the Palm OS was killed by the Windows-based PDAs and Palm has never recovered. The Foleo might be the final nail in Palm's coffin. Only if you could dial with it and it had bluetooth, so you could leave it in your pocket until needed The device is obviously for business where you do not need more than writing and answering email and browsing the net (blackberry?). The downside is it cannot make phone calls but the up side is that it's fast and easy to write your mails and to just check something small on the net. The above mentioned two positives (read keyboard and big screen/internet) makes the device more efficient and in a way fixes what a smart phone lacks. If it's light and has good practical battery time I'd say we have a winner. Of course I'm still talking about business. I'm A Business Owner of 2 Companies Someone mentioned that this is for business use. No way. I run 2 companies and wouldn't consider such a device for myself or any of my employees. I don't know any professional that would consider such a product unless they got it free at a convention show. Years ago I bought one of those Motorola StarTac cellphones - they were about $400-$600 when they first came out because they were tiny. Motorola sold an attachable electronic organizer with a bigger screen. I bought it because it attached directly to my cellphone. If I had to carry it as a 2nd device, I would have never considered it. To think this guy makes big bucks to come up with 1 cent ideas. I'm pretty sure that you can do everything that this device promise to do, with the laptop/notebook/sub-notebook you already have, and better. Why spend the money and carry the extra gadget? Great 2nd Web browser for homes (at $99) I think this thing is GREAT... if it was $99 - $150 and was marketted as a spare, portable, web browsing machine for homes with existing WIFI. But no one in their right mind would pay $500 - $600 for this underpowered laptop. Really.. how much could it cost for some chinese firm to put out a simple, light laptop just for wifi web browsing, but include a cheap say 20GB hd (keep the flash so it is still instant on). Or at the current price point, add a pc card slot and an evdo modem and that 20GB hd or a second SD slot. (so you can browse anywhere and save your data better). I think it has potential. It is a deffinitely a niche market item. Since it has wifi, it would be great for internet cafes and other similar places. How is this possible? Hawking is brilliant, his book "on intelligence" is remarkable, why is he behind something so seemingly pointless?! Toshiba preps release of Satellite HSDPA PDA phone Palm announces Foleo smartphone companion Sony Ericsson preps new Walkman phone W660i Palm Pilot inventor to unveil new mobile device Blackberry World Series CDMA/GSM phone hits store shelves Nissan says cellphones could nuke car keys Climber completes world's highest cell phone call Motorola to buy video compression firm Modulus Mobile-content enablement-platform providers on the rise, says iSuppli Sony Ericsson and Nokia welcome Apple to the handset market Preparing for the iPhone: Motorola introduces Razr2 phone Sony Ericsson introduces new phones Motorola patents self-powered displays China mobile phone subscribers at nearly 481 million in