http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-6&fd=R&url=http://www.nydailynews.com/money/2007/05/31/2007-05-31_apples_new_tune.html&cid=1116735750&ei=jv1eRobJFYXoqgPDpanNDQ Drops guard on music downloads; iPhone wins praise Drops guard on music downloads; iPhone wins praise Thursday, May 31st 2007, 4:00 AM Apple is hitting on all cylinders with its DRM-free iTunes Plus feature and big expectations for the iPhone. Apple began selling thousands of songs without copy protection yesterday, just as the tech darling's iPhone was getting a breathless boost from AT&T. The California company's iTunes Store launched the new song-selling strategy with music from EMI's massive catalogue, including works by the Rolling Stones, Pink Floyd and Coldplay. Free of digital rights management, or DRM, technology, the songs will cost 30 cents more than restricted songs, but will be playable on virtually any digital music player. In a separate development, a top AT&T official declared expectations for the iPhone, due out at the end of next month and distributed by AT&T, are "too low." "The iPhone is going to be a game-changer," added AT&T Chief Operating Officer Randall Stephenson, who spoke at an investor conference in New York. Next year, Apple expects to sell 10 million of the iPhones, which blend a mobile phone with the iPod music player. The iPhone will cost up to $499. AT&T's wireless unit, formerly known as Cingular, plans to use the iPhone to recruit subscribers. It now has 62.2 million wireless customers, the most in the U.S. The strong words of praise for the iPhone helped, but it analysts said it was mostly iTunes new sales pitch that propelled the company's shares in heavy trading yesterday. Apple stock rose nearly 4.5%, to a 52-week high of $118.77. Songs sold by iTunes free of restrictions will work for the first time directly on portable players other than Apple's iPod, including Microsoft's Zune. Analysts predicted that other digital music sellers will have little choice but to follow suit. The DRM-free tracks feature a higher sound quality and cost $1.29 apiece, compared to the usual 99-cent price. If available, users could upgrade existing purchases to DRM-free versions for 30 cents a song or $3 for most albums, Apple said. Earlier this year, Apple CEO Steve Jobs called on the four major record companies to sell songs online without copy-protection software. Yesterday, Jobs reiterated Apple expects that more than half of the 5 million songs on iTunes will feature a DRM-free version by the end of the year. Sign up to receive daily newsletters Buy an Ad link Use of this website signifies your agreement to the &copy; Copyright 2007 NYDailyNews.com. All rights reserved.
