 Java House, which sits on the wharf at the end of Bryant. The images that make up Google's Street View feature are taken by a small army of drivers with expensive, multiple lens cameras mounted to the tops of their cars. Streets for which Street View images are available show up with blue outlines on Google Maps. Google says Street View is available for major roads in San Francisco, New York, Las Vegas, Miami, and Denver. More cities will follow shortly, Google says. / 1000 max characters Hands On: Facebook Adds Video Google 'Gears' up for Offline Web Apps Where 2.0: Get News of the Neighborhood at Outside.in Palm Planning a Laptop-Like Smartphone Companion? Apple Launches iTunes Plus with DRM-Free Tracks Where 2.0: Timelapse Maps from Trulia Where 2.0: Sounds of the World Added to Google Maps LCD wide screen monitors &copy; 1998-2007, PC World Communications, Inc. Terms of Service Agreement PC World Latin America
http://www.sci-tech-today.com/news/Feds-Arrest--Spam-King--in-Seattle/story.xhtml%3Fstory_id%3D13300G97BHPK&cid Sci-Tech Today | Feds Arrest 'Spam King' in Seattle Technology, Discovery & Innovation Maximize your BPM Investment: Feds Arrest 'Spam King' in Seattle Some reports have suggested that "Spam King" Alan Soloway's arrest will cause a noticeable decrease in spam, but John Levine, a CAUCE board member, suggested that any decline would be minimal. Soloway's arrest will help, Levine said, but with spam increasing so much over the past few years, his arrest "won't make much difference." FDA Nixes Fast Track for Cancer Vaccine Ban on Selling Wildlife Might Fuel Trade Nine Hurricanes Forecast for 2007 Cancer Expected to Skyrocket in Asia Space Station Gets Protective Panels with HP's All-in-One Storage Systems. Simple and affordable ways to set I.T. free. Robert Alan Soloway, a 27-year-old Seattle resident dubbed "Spam King" by federal agents, was arrested on Wednesday and charged with multiple counts of fraud, wire fraud, e-mail fraud, aggravated identity theft, and money laundering. If convicted on the various counts, Soloway could face decades in prison. "It's good news for consumers," said John Levine, a board member of the Coalition Against Unsolicited Commercial E-Mail (CAUCE). "Soloway has been taunting the antispam community and federal officials for years, essentially daring them to come after him, and they finally did." In a 24-page indictment filed in the U.S. District Court for the District of Washington, U.S. Attorney Jeffrey C. Sullivan said that Soloway has been operating his illegal scheme since November 2003, and sent out tens of millions of spam e-mails in an effort to drum up business for his e-mail advertising software (which in turn would send out additional spam). Educating Juries on E-Mail Levine said that given Soloway's notoriety and relatively high profile, CAUCE had been wondering why it was taking so long for federal authorities to take action against him. "And now we know," Levine said. "Federal agents were building a very detailed and thorough list of charges that is not likely to fall apart at trial." The other challenge for federal prosecutors is the complexity of Internet-based fraud cases. Levine said that he served as a technical expert on one of the first spam cases in Virginia and prosecutors "spent a fortune" educating the jury on the technology involved. "It's definitely a little more complicated than 'A man walks into a bank with a gun and walks out with money,'" Levine said. "But I think that it will get steadily easier for federal prosecutors to bring these cases as the technology becomes more familiar to people." Not A CAN-SPAM Case What might surprise some people is that despite the fact that it involves e-mail and one of the nation's top spammers, the CAN-SPAM Act plays a minor role. "If you read the indictment," Levine pointed out, "the CAN-SPAM Act is barely mentioned. That reaffirms what CAUCE has been saying, that the CAN-SPAM Act is not in fact an effective law enforcement statute. Instead, this case is built on traditional criminal offenses like wire fraud and money laundering." At an arraignment on Wednesday afternoon, Soloway pleaded not guilty to all charges and was ordered held until a hearing on Monday. In addition to seeking Soloway's conviction on the various charges, the government is also looking to recover $773,000 that it says Soloway earned from his fraudulent business. Some reports have suggested that Soloway's arrest will cause a noticeable decrease in spam, but Levine suggested that any decline would unfortunately be minimal. "There's no question that [Soloway's] been responsible for a lot of spam," Levine said, "and his arrest will help. But the amount of spam has increased so much over the last couple of years that even his arrest won't make much difference." Increase visitor confidence on your site with the green address bar. When shoppers using Internet Explorer 7 visit a Web site secured with VeriSign Extended Validation SSL, the address bar turns green to let them know that the site they are on is highly authenticated and secure. Google Goes Large in South Korea DRM-Free Music Available on iTunes Feature Wars Intensify in Mapping Tech Microsoft Brings Computing to Tabletops Quanta Mum on Possible Son of iPhone Yahoo Photos Going Out for Good A one-click updated to Flickr service. Apple Irked by Ann Summers iGasm Ad Is racy ad too close for comfort? Study Finds Increasing Net Censorship New data from OpenNet Initiative. NewsFactor Network Enterprise I.T. Sites NewsFactor Network Enterprise Applications Sites NewsFactor Business and Innovation Sites How To Contact Us &#169; Copyright 2000-2007 NewsFactor Network. All rights reserved. Article rating technology by
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-2&fd=R&url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx%3Fid%3D270366&cid=1116342796&ei=jv1eRobJFYXoqgPDpanNDQ Wayward whales may be heading out to sea Make ninemsn your homepage Friday Jun 1 02:59 AEST Wayward whales may be heading out to sea Thursday May 31 10:17 AEST Two humpback whales that strayed 145 kms up a Californian river have disappeared from view and may be on their way out to open sea. "We have good news and we have no news," said Bernadette Fees, a spokeswoman with California's fish and game authority. VIDEO: Bound for open sea Whale sanctuary bid fails "We haven't sighted the whales this morning, so there is a possibility that they have made their way back out to their natural environment," she said. Wildlife officials had been attempting to herd the injured whales back to the ocean since they swam up the Sacramento River, deep in California's central valley, on May 15. It is believed that the mother and her calf, dubbed "Delta" and "Dawn" by scientists, had been injured by a passing boat. Biologists deployed a new technique at the weekend of directing the whales by spraying water some 300 meters (yards) ahead of them after earlier failing to direct them by playing recordings of humpbacks feeding, and by banging steel pipes to create offensive sounds. Experts are at a loss to explain why the two whales, which had been heading north on their spring migratory route which runs from Mexico along California into the northern Pacific, swam under the Golden Gate Bridge and through the San Francisco Bay to the Sacramento River. Send us your news tips, stories, photos and videos Murdered Russian 'spied for Britain' Richie speaks out on rehab and barbecue Apology averts row with Indonesia Court told Clarkson had residue on hands Mika proud to a 'pop' artist White House unveils new climate strategy No more Mr Nice Guy for Kevin Costner Paris Hilton's skin prepped for prison Viagra oysters face stiff opposition Bosnian in 