http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-2&fd=R&url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/business/317958_gatesjobs31.html&cid=1116799532&ei=jv1eRobJFYXoqgPDpanNDQ Gates and Jobs share stage and memories Skip ads and navigation Thursday, updated 8:38 a.m. PT Gates and Jobs share stage and memories Longtime rivals appear at digital conference THE NEW YORK TIMES CARLSBAD, Calif. -- In a highly anticipated encounter, Bill Gates of Microsoft Corp. and Steve Jobs of Apple took the stage Wednesday evening to relive old battles and alliances and speculate about the future of digital culture and technology. See Todd Bishop's blog for video highlights Rivals for three decades, the two executives have rarely appeared in public together and have generally been viewed as bitter rivals, despite occasional partnerships. In front of about 600 technology executives at the D: All Things Digital conference, which was sponsored by The Wall Street Journal, the two executives attracted the attention usually reserved for rock singers and Hollywood stars. However, attendees who came hoping for fireworks or a confrontation were disappointed. The mild tone to the session did not take anything away from the event, and after discussing the past and present of the computing industry, the two were greeted with a standing ovation. Gates and Jobs largely pioneered the personal-computer industry beginning in 1975 and 1976, and they spent part of the evening sharing memories of those days. Today "we ship these computers with 1 or 2 gigabytes and nobody remembers 128 kilobytes," Jobs said. Apple and Microsoft were business partners at the start of the computer era beginning in 1977 when Gates supplied a copy of the BASIC programming language for the Apple II computer. Later, Gates made an early bet on writing software for the Macintosh, two years before the computer was introduced in 1984. Neither was willing to acknowledge the possibility that the personal-computer era they helped create would end any time soon. "The PC has proven to be very resilient," Jobs said. At the same time, they called themselves believers in the explosion of hand-held communications devices, also known as "Post PC devices." Gates said he was sometimes frustrated by the fact that the players in the industry changed so quickly. "I miss it when people come and go. It's nice when people stick around, and it gives us some context," he said. Neither man was willing to say harsh things about the other, and Jobs summed up his feelings by quoting from the Beatles' song "Two of Us": " 'You and I have memories longer than the road that stretches out ahead'; that's clearly true here," he said. Jobs is widely credited for Apple's renaissance with a string of innovative products -- the iMac computer for consumers, the powerful PowerMac and PowerBook and the iPod digital music player. Microsoft has long dominated with its Windows operating system and software programs such as Word and Excel, but Apple scored big with its iPod, introduced in 2001, and its iTunes online music store. Next month, Apple introduces its much-anticipated iPhone mobile handset. This report includes information from The Associated Press. Add P-I Business headlines to Gates and Jobs share stage and memories Jeppesen provides added aviation services Ernst & Young partners charged New owners have 'big plans' for Wild Waves Court paved way for tribal wealth Qatar Airways orders 80 A350s China moves to cool a hot market Apple debuts songs that can be copied MySpace parent buys Photobucket Google takes its software offline Alaska to begin non-stop Seattle to Hawaii flights ACLU lawsuit says Boeing subsidiary enabled torture Gates and Jobs share stage and memories Microsoft Surface brings computing to the table Microsoft gets OK to stake claim for interactivity patent Northwest exits bankruptcy protection Precious metals prices climb Stocks up after takeover news, GDP data Gasoline futures off on inventory report Five cos. win gov't te