http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8i-0&fd=R&url=http://digital-lifestyles.info/2007/06/04/study-uk-most-active-internet-users-in-europe/&cid=1116958275&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Study: U.K. Most Active Internet Users In Europe : Digital-Lifestyles (alpha remix) Palm Sells Stake To Equity Firm, Ipod Genius Joins Team Study: U.K. Most Active Internet Users In Europe 4 June 2007 at 6:00 pm Online stats firm comScore have been busy with their rulers, clicky counters and tape measures to bring us curious folks &#8216;the first comprehensive review of European Internet activity.&#8217; Their cool-sounding &#8216;comScore World Metrix&#8217; study reveals that Europeans *heart* the Internet, with an average of 122 million Europeans aged 15 or older being online during an average day in April 2007, compared to 114 million in the U.S. According to comScore&#8217;s stats, the average European spent an average of 16.5 days in the month surfing around the web on their home or work PCs, notching up a total of 24 hours viewing time, looking at no less than 2,662 Web pages. Swedish surfers love web pages When it comes to the number of pages looked at, the Swedes romp home by a considerable margin, with the average user taking in 4,019 pages per month â 51 percent above the European average. The Netherlands and Scandinavian countries have the highest percentage of folks online, with anything from 68 percent to 83 percent online, but when it comes to numbers per country online, Germany takes the crown with an online population of 32.6 million people aged 15 and older. The Germans may have more people online, but us Brits can proudly claim to have most active online population, boasting the highest average number of daily visitors (21.8 million), the highest usage days per month (21 per user), and the highest average time spent per month per user (34.4 hours). We dread to think how many lost office hours are included in that impressive tally. Overall, European users average 16.5 usage days per month, with Russian surfers coming bottom of the access pile, mustering up just 11.4 average usage days. Other countries falling behind the European average are Austria (12.0), Italy (12.9), Ireland (13.0), Portugal (13.4), Norway (14.7), Denmark (14.7), Switzerland (15.1), Belgium (15.5) and Finland (16.4). Not surprisingly, Google was found to be the most popular property in 13 of the 16 countries, followed by Microsoft in most countries. Yahoo! trailed behind in third place across Europe, although it managed to bag the number one slot in Ireland, Italy and Spain. Last 3 posts in Business Palm Sells Stake To Equity Firm, Ipod Genius Joins Team - 4 June, 2007 TV, Music and Marketing: Their Current Response To Digital Media (pt 3/3) - 1 June, 2007 Last.fm Sells For Â£140m To CBS - 31 May, 2007 Last 3 posts in Research Blathering Work Bloggers Risk The Boot - 29 May, 2007 Google Rampant: Microsoft Search Slips Up - 22 May, 2007 Personal Audio Space: Microsoft Research - 17 May, 2007 Last 3 posts in UK First BBC Show Broadcasting In Second Life Tonight - 1 June, 2007 Last.fm Sells For Â£140m To CBS - 31 May, 2007 TV, Music and Marketing: Their Current Response To Digital Media (pt 2) - 31 May, 2007 Last 3 posts in Web Google Scoops Up FeedBurner - 4 June, 2007 Alan Johnston Video Online - 1 June, 2007 Lastminute.com Founders To Launch DIY Site - 29 May, 2007 On this day, years gone by ... Microsoft Scraps Major Online Game Before Launch Nvidia Expect Media Centre Shipments to Treble NPD Group: US CD Price Cuts Are Accelerating Amazon's New Preview Jukebox Sony UK release PS2 online - 11 June These icons link to social bookmarking sites where readers can share and discover new web pages. Subscribe to the comments through RSS Feed We get flooded with spam comments, so we have to put strange stuff like this maths in place, just so you can prove you're human. You can use these tags: 3 &times; 9 + 4 = ? Notify me of followup comments via e-mail Conten