http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-0&fd=R&url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/TECH/fun.games/06/04/bullet.witch/&cid=1116956272&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Review: 'Bullet Witch' casts a weak spell - CNN.com Review: 'Bullet Witch' casts a weak spell What's a video gamer to do while waiting for blockbuster titles such as "Madden NFL 08" (August 14), "Halo 3" (September 25) and "Grand Theft Auto IV" (October 16)? The answer is to rent some games for the weekend, such as Atari's "Bullet Witch," an average sci-fi shooter for the Microsoft Xbox 360. This third-person shooter takes place in the year 2013, after our planet has suffered fatalities in the billions because of natural disasters, war and infectious diseases. As if this weren't enough, an inter-dimensional portal opened up, allowing demons to seep through and attack those few people remaining. This is where you come in. You play as Alicia Claus, a beautiful witch who is as powerful with her magic spells as she is deft with a trigger finger. She wields a huge "gun-rod," a kind of broom-shaped weapon that can be upgraded over time. But gun battles with hoards of demons get tiring after a while. For one, while some might run for cover, the not-so-bright creatures basically stand there and let you shoot them down one by one. Another issue is that the action sequences repeat each other often, which works something like this: fight baddies, move ahead and watch a short story sequence, then fight more baddies and move ahead toward the end of the level. You start with the gun-rod as a machine gun, but in time it can be switched to a shotgun, sniper rifle and Gatling gun. Magic spells, however, produce a more exhilarating effect than the predictable gunplay. Pressing the left or right shoulder button brings up a magic wheel, whereby you can spin and select what kind of magic spell to invoke -- if you've earned enough skill points to unlock it. Highlights include "Willpower," which creates a shock wave that sends nearby objects hurling toward enemies, and "Lightning," where Alicia summons a bolt that kills the enemy instantly. Visually speaking, the effects of these spells (and others, including summoning a meteor shower) are quite gratifying. It's too bad the huge and detailed environments in "Bullet Witch," such as accurately modeled suburban neighborhoods, are as linear as they are. That is, you're given the impression you can go anywhere and do anything -- as in "Grand Theft Auto" -- but you soon realize you're on a short leash and must follow a specific path. Another problem with the game is that it can be cumbersome to control Alicia's movement with the Xbox 360's left analog stick while moving the camera with the right analog stick. It's like having to play actor and director at the same time, which might work for some games (usually when the camera is somewhat automated, but lets you swivel it around for a better view) but not when both are continuously mandatory, as in "Bullet Witch." This single-player adventure has its strengths -- namely, big and attractive outdoor environments and impressive spell casting effects -- but dumb artificial intelligence, repetitive gun battles and awkward controls bring the game down to a C-grade experience. And at only six or seven hours of play, you can easily tackle this single-player shooter in a weekend. But if you need to get your action fix while waiting for this year's more eagerly anticipated video games, you could do worse than "Bullet Witch." Next story in Technology What are E-mail Alerts? Democrats clash on Iraq Democratic presidential hopefuls traded barbs over the war in Iraq Sunday night in New Hampshire, with former Sen. John Edwards blasting two rivals for not ... Divers dismantle artificial tire reef Plane slams into California homes Culture reflects porn influence Charges against Guantanamo detainee dismissed Grand jury indicts La. lawmaker Who has most to lose in the GOP debate? Navarrette: Dems lack clarity on immigration Check out our new look U.S. congressman indicted in bribery case Missing word sees Gitmo charges dismissed Alicia Claus is a beautiful witch who is as powerful with her magic spells as she is deft with a trigger finger. 8.0 out of 10 Kensington Contour Balance Notebook Roller - notebook carrying case 8.5 out of 10 Kensington Contour Traveler rolling laptop case 8.0 out of 10 Verizon Wireless G'zOne Type-S 7.7 out of 10 What do the CNET.com ratings mean? Entry Level - New Grad Installation - Maint - Repair QA - Quality Control Restaurant - Food Service Skilled Labor - Trades &copy; 2007 Cable News Network. A Time Warner Company. All Rights Reserved. under which this service is provided to you. External sites open in new window; not endorsed by CNN.com Pay service with live and archived video.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-4&fd=R&url=http://www.itwire.com.au/content/view/12595/1103/&cid=1116735750&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg iTWire - Do the new DRM-free tracks have a worm in the Apple? IT and TELCO JOBS Do the new DRM-free tracks have a worm in the Apple? Do the new DRM-free tracks have a worm in the Apple? Saturday, 02 June 2007 iTunes Plus with DRM-free tracks are finally here, but each track, DRM-free or no, contains the name you used to register iTunes to dissuade you from placing your songs on P2P networks. Its official: Steve Jobs to launch iPhone June 29! Internode hikes ADSL prices for power users - UPDATE Why Apple will sell 10 million iPhones in 2008 Do the new DRM-free tracks have a worm in the Apple? Apple&rsquo;s gone partially DRM-free, but a surprising discovery reported online says that your name, your email address and other personal details are embedded into each track that you purchase from iTunes, whether it has DRM to protect it, or not. Following this discovery, the EFF said additional information had been found in iTunes files, possibly amounting to an additional &lsquo;digital watermark&rsquo;, allowing songs uploaded from iTunes to be easily identified. Unfortunately, hackers are already working on ways to strip this information from iTunes&rsquo;s DRM-free EMI songs, as well as &lsquo;spoof&rsquo; the information to make it appear as through from someone else, as surprise and mild outrage spreads that Apple has included this information with DRM-free music downloads. Apple&rsquo;s DRM-free tracks cost a US 30c premium over non-DRM tracks, and offer encoding at a higher quality bitrate &ndash; 256kbps instead of 128kbps, making songs played through an iPod to a large speaker system sound much better than the older 128kbps format. Clearly, users don&rsquo;t like the idea they are being tracked while paying extra for DRM-free(dom), but the chances are that most iTunes buyers will be happy, law-abiding citizens who have no plans to uploaded iTunes music content. Those that do want to upload music from EMI purchased from iTunes have been given fair warning- if you upload songs to P2P networks, chances are EMI and Apple will find out and will come down on you like a ton of bricks. At least, until the hackers release a DRM-free clean up patch to the iTunes files. No-one yet knows how successful the DRM-free experiment will be, or if it will sell more songs to consumers, but so far, Apple&rsquo;s sweet start has, at least for some, turned a little sour. Get stories like this delivered to our free Daily UPDATE email newsletter Get a WireTalker account to add your comments to this article. Login now to add your comment. Rubiks Cube  solved in 26, or 17.7 moves? Toshiba unveils slim HD DVD-RW for notebooks As iPhone goes on sale, what problems lie in wait? Its official: Steve Jobs to launch iPhone June 29! Why Apple will sell 10 million iPhones in 2008 Will Google and Salesforce bring on the Gooforce? Arrr! Sparrows Pirates is The One Google Maps becomes Go Ogle Maps Do the new DRM-free tracks have a worm in the Apple? Spam, spam, spam, spam, spam, spam, spam. Print joint venture heads towards Ricoh ownership Microsoft does patent deal with Xandros Linux Japan Wiis a lot: 5-to-1 sales over the PS3! Rubiks Cube  solved in 26, or 17.7 moves? Follow-up: NASA, Michael Griffin, global warming, and earth-science research Toshiba unveils slim HD DVD-RW for notebooks Submit your release now Start submitting to iTWire How to post video Submit your press release Security & Privacy Policy Australian IT Recruitment News
http://www.technewsworld.com/story/57670.html&cid Technology News: iPhone: iPhone Gets a Due Date Manage Remotely with the HP ProLiant DL360 G5 Server Letters to the Editor ECT News Network Map CRM Buyer Site Map E-Commerce Times Site Map Search ECT News Network June 4, 2007 02:14:32 PM PDT Read Next Article in iPhone iPhone Gets a Due Date Part of the ECT News Network 06/04/07 11:23 AM PT Always careful to orchestrate news of product rollouts on its own terms, Apple this weekend set a specific date on the launch of the iPhone: June 29. The news was conveyed in three television ads that featured lots of iPhone eye candy, with close-up images of the device's Web surfing, video playback and photo browsing capabilities. BlackBerry® Solutions Deliver Results Mobile business users are discovering how to make the most of their time in the field with wireless applications. Create a customized business case in less than five minutes and see what BlackBerry® Solutions can do for your organization. The date for the much-anticipated iPhone launch has been set for June 29. tipped the date Sunday with a trio of new television ads, which are also available for viewing on its Web site. If soon-to-be iPhone owners have been antsy for news of the June release date, there's a good chance they'll start drooling when they see the new ads, which feature close-up views of the iPhone playing high-quality video, surfing the Web, browsing through album covers, family photos, and a seafood restaurant search that shows off results on a handy street map. "The iPhones will be on sale in company-owned resale stores, and they'll be available in Apple retail stores as well as on their online store," John Kampfe, a spokesperson for AT&T, told MacNewsWorld. Apple confirmed the date but declined to comment on details. The iPhone will only be available via AT&T (formerly Cingular) service plans, and as Apple's iPhone video ads note, the use of the iPhone will require a minimum two-year activation plan. Apple may launch the iPhone with a special event rather than during regular events at which it has kicked off new products in the past, such as its Worldwide Developers Conference, going on next week in San Francisco. Will Apple and AT&T launch some pre-Fourth of July weekend fireworks? "We're not disclosing any other plans at this point beyond what we've said already," Kampfe noted. However, Apple already milked a great deal of hype when it unveiled the iPhone back in January at Macworld. A second event might be overkill. "To be honest, I don't think they need to do a whole lot to drive additional attention. There's a lot of hunger around this already," Charles Golvin, a principal analyst with Apple and AT&T may hold a launch event at the Apple Store in New York to help drive mass media coverage, Golvin noted. They may also let the iPhone go on sale at midnight the night before, he speculated. "I still see two waves of uptake, and the first is the Apple fan boys, the people who are devoted to all things Apple ... and there are plenty of them," Golvin explained. These Apple customers have been paying careful attention to their cellular service contracts and have been making sure they are off of competitors' contracts in advance of the iPhone launch. "The more interesting piece will be the second wave, those who are very interested, who maybe already have a BlackJack or Motorola Q -- or something in the same space that's more consumer-friendly than a BlackBerry," Golvin noted. "We'll see if they're still willing pay the premium [for an iPhone]." The iPhone will initially come in two versions -- a 4 GB model for US$499 and an 8 GB model for $599. The steep price tag could put quite a heavy burden on sales ; however, when adding the price of a new iPod to that of a cell phone, the total could be close enough to justify the expense to some consumers. After the initial wave of sales to Apple aficionados, the price may well hold strong. "There's so much attention paid on the price point, but if you go back to the initial price of the Motorola Razr, when also had an exclusive on it, it was $499, so this is not the first phone to be priced at this level," Golvin explained. "And they were able to hold that price point for quite a while." Next Article in iPhone: You've Got to Hide Your iPhone Away More by Chris Maxcer ListManager software is robust, scalable, integrated. Demo today. Free whitepaper on how you can grow sales with very little money using m-commerce. New White Paper: We know what you did last summer but we don't know why. Manage remotely with one interface -- the HP ProLiant DL360 G5 server. New Software Release: Advanced Features for IT Service Optimization Security Products for Your Business Learn more about Microsoft Forefront. It makes defending your systems easier. Raise employee productivity by reducing objectionable content. No per-server fees. You've Got to Hide Your iPhone Away Report: Quanta Cuts 5M iPhone Deal Gauging the iPhone's Ripple Effect CA Message Manager Enterprise Discovery & Archiving The Merits Of Hosted IP Service Relative To IP PBX s An Innovation Imperative Building Innovation Into Your Marketing DNA The Innovation Imperative Building Innovation Into Your Marketing DNA Technical Comparison DB2 HADR and Oracle Data Guard Don't miss a story -- sign up for our FREE e-mail newsletters and view the latest headlines at a glance. Tech News Flash [ ECT News Network Weekly Newsletter [ More Stories by Chris Maxcer GPL 'Last Call' Aims to Make MS-Novell Deal Last of Its Kind 5 Telcos Get a Shot at $20B in Government Contracts Microsoft Puts Surface on the Table Click here to send a letter to the editor... Click here to add your comment about this story... Sign Up for Business and Technology News Alerts This Week on ECT News Network Careers at ECT News Network Blu-ray Chases HD DVD Into the Bargain Basement McAfee: Search Engines Falling Down on Security Job Steve Jobs and Bill Gates, Milan, Foleo and Prod