http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/19033964/&cid=1116968868&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Mercury probe set for rehearsal at Venus - Space.com - MSNBC.com Mercury probe set for rehearsal at Venus Messenger to conduct science observations during close flyby NASA / JHU-APL / CIW A computer-generatedÂ animation shows the Messenger probe against the backdrop of Venus' disk during this week's flyby. June 4: This graphic of the inner planets chartsÂ Messenger's circuitous course from Earth to Mercury. NASA / JHU-APL / CIW By By Ker Than The upcoming flyby of a NASA spacecraft over Venus could provide new insights about the cloud-shrouded planet and will serve as a dress rehearsal for its first rendezvous next year with its main target, Mercury. On June 5, Messenger will fly over Venus in a maneuver designed to use the pull of the planet's gravity to slow it down enough that it can slip into the orbit of . During the flyby, Messenger will decelerate from 22.7 to 17.3 miles per second (36.5 to 27.8 km/s). "This change in Messenger's velocity is the largest of the mission," said Messenger mission systems engineer Eric Finnegan, of the Applied Physics Laboratory at John Hopkins University. the Venus on the planet's dayside at more than 30,000 miles per hour (48,000 km/h), pass over the boundary separating day from night, and pass within 200 miles (320 kilometers) of the planet's surface while on its night side. Second pass, with a first for science The upcoming flyby will be Messenger's second pass by Venus. During the first flyby, in October 2006, no scientific observations were made because the planet was at superior conjunction, placing it on the opposite side of the sun from Earth. The closest approach on that flyby was about 1,800 miles (3,000 kilometers) of the planet's surface. "Because of superior conjunction, because we knew we were going into radio blackout, and we knew we had the second flyby coming up in June, we elected not to turn on any of the instruments at the time of that flyby," said the mission's principal investigator, Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington. The second Venus flyby will mark the first time Messenger's full suite of scientific instruments is turned on simultaneously, allowing scientists to test and calibrate them before turning them onto their main planetary objective next January. "The approach geometry is sufficiently similar to that of Mercury, allowing the seven instrument-package to be turned on and operating collectively in scientific observing mode, just as they will be for Mercury," Finnegan said. Messenger is expected to collect more than 6 gigabytes of data about the Venus system and take more than 600 images during the 73-hour flyby. The information will provide new observations about Venus' atmosphere, cloud structure, space environment and perhaps even its surface. Click for related content NASA launches spacecraft to Mercury Venus probe sends back first images Cosmic Log: Slingshots in space During its brief sojourn, Messenger will join a European spacecraft, Venus Express, that is currently in orbit around Venus. The will work together to investigate how particles from the sun's solar wind affects and controls the upper layers of Venus's atmosphere. "By coordinating and comparing these observations, we will be able to maximize the science from both missions and potentially learn things that would not be revealed by one set of observations alone," said study team member Ralph McNutt, also of the Applied Physics Laboratory. Launched in August 2004, Messenger (which is actually an extended acronym for anging) is the first mission to visit our solar system's innermost planet in more than 30 years, ever since NASA's Mariner 10 mapped about 45 percent of its surface. Messenger's mission is to map the entire planet, as well as gather information about Mercury's composition and structure, its geologic history, and the makeup of its core and poles. Â© 2007 Space.com. All rights reserved. MORE FROM SPACE NEWS ShuttleÂ mission outshines NASA sideshows Mercury probe set for rehearsal at Venus ShuttleÂ mission outshines NASA sideshows A look at the shuttle Atlantisâ crew Sound cranks up the heat in sun's atmosphere Cosmic Log: Virtual moon trip coming up 'Serious jeopardy' for U.S. climate studies Space shuttle workers vote to strike Engineers descend on monster radio dish Cosmic Sightings:Â  Take anÂ interplanetary tour Quiz: Test your science and space smarts Space News Section Front Congressman indicted on 16 counts Al-Qaida group: Abducted GIs slain Putin offers warning on U.S. plan Charges nixed for Gitmo detainee Democrats debate in N.H. Miss USA on boos and the fall 69-year-old climber reaches Mt. Everest peak TODAY to broadcast from Cuba Prevent cancer by pumping up on vitamin D Medal of Honor tributes Going for the Throat Congressman indicted in bribery investigation Al-Qaida group says 3 abducted GIs were slain Putin: âWe will have to have new targetsâ Most viewed on MSNBC.com Would-Be Suicide Bomber Dies in Somalia U.S. Troop Drive Said Faltering in Iraq U.S. Military Deaths in Iraq at 3,479 Hamas Attack Wounds 4 Israeli Soldiers Iran Leader: Won't Beg for Nuke Power Most viewed on MSNBC.com Going for the Throat Rolling sneakers blamed for rise in kid injuries Congressman indicted in bribery investigation Komodo dragon kills boy, 8, in Indonesia Most viewed on MSNBC.com From Earth to stars New views of a storm from space and of a distant galaxy in these space image highlights.
