ess -- not just the new DRM-free tunes. But their inclusion on noncopy protected songs is significant, mordaxus said, because some people might be tempted to share bought music on a peer-to-peer (P2P) network. "If you're going to put music files up a P2P network, you cannot be paranoid. They are out to get you," said mordaxus. "It would be folly to take any music you bought from any service and serve it up." The Unofficial Apple Weblog posted a three-step set of instructions on how Mac OS X users can use Terminal to dig into an iTunes Plus file. Apple did not returns calls asking why iTunes tracks, whether protected by DRM or not, contain buyer data. For more enterprise computing news, visit . Story copyright &copy; 2007 Computerworld Inc. All rights reserved. / 1000 max characters U.S. Cracks Down on Copyright Microsoft Plans Music Promo Google Offers Book Search to Publishers Pornographer Indicted for Online Film Distribution Brits are Busiest Surfers People in the U.K. spend more time online than the rest of Europe or the U.S., a new study finds. Microsoft Accused of Endangering Users Internet user profiling could help repressive regimes identify dissidents, group warns. Bono Helps Bail Out Palm A private-equity firm is pumping $325 million into ailing mobile device manufacturer Palm. Open Source Pulls in $1.8 Billion Adoption of standalone open source software is accelerating, say researchers. LANDesk Offers Free Trial Tech management software for ThinkVantage is available for evaluation through Lenovo. but all the kings horses! Treason! Playing iTunes songs on... I would like to gradually repurpose my older desktop PC to an iTunes based music system... Receive the latest reviews, how-to's, news, and more. PC World's Free Whitepapers Enter your trial subscription and get 2 Risk-Free Issues plus Bonus CD-ROM . If you like , pay just $19.97 for 10 more issues (12 in all). Otherwise, write "cancel" on the bill, return it, and owe nothing. You will also get Weekly B