http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-5&fd=R&url=http://www.2theadvocate.com/features/7798366.html&cid=1116962609&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg 2theadvocate.com | Features | Religion Notes for June 2, 2007 -- Baton Rouge, LA Baton Rouge Temperature: 77Â° Former NASCAR chairman Bill France dies --> Monday, June 4, 2007 Religion Notes for June 2, 2007 Religion grows in Second Life By ADVOCATE STAFF REPORT Published: Jun 2, 2007 - Page: 2E Page 1 of 2 In Second Life, the online virtual universe that is attracting some 3.7 million users, you can light virtual candles for Shabbat, teleport to a Buddhist temple or consult the Oracle for some divine guidance. Second Life is a three-dimensional, online game produced by San Francisco-based Linden Lab in which participants create a virtual world, buy and sell land and products and interact in all the usual ways. Now religion has a growing presence there too, users say, and religious diversity and participation have skyrocketed since June 2006, when basic membership to Second Life became free. And just like in real-life churches, mosques and synagogues, there is diversity, debate, schism and yes, more than a few holier-than-thou types. With some real-life churches taking notice, it&rsquo;s not just for computer geeks, either. It all starts when users create an online 3-D persona, known as an avatar, taken from the Sanskrit word for a Hindu deity. The game&rsquo;s 3.7 million users control their 6.5 million avatars with their keyboards and communicate with each other via instant message. Noreen Herzfeld, professor of theology and computer science at Saint John&rsquo;s University in Collegeville, Minn., says Second Life reflects what she calls the &ldquo;external face&rdquo; of religion &mdash; community, identity, codes and creeds, ritual and practice. Beth Brown, a 33-year-old Orthodox Jewish artist from Dallas, says she didn&rsquo;t intend to start a community when she built the first synagogue, Second Life Synagogue-Temple Beit Israel, in September. Within an hour of its creation, two avatars were there, and now the virtual synagogue has more than 200 members. For some people, Second Life is their only chance to participate in religious rituals. Recently, Brown started lighting virtual Shabbat candles on Friday nights. Her mother, who lives in New York, attends online. &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t light Shabbat candles anywhere with my mother but Second Life,&rdquo; she said. Other faiths have found online expression there also. Yunus Yakoub Islam, who believes he&rsquo;s the only Muslim living in his village in England, uses Second Life to interact with more than 200 members of the game&rsquo;s Islamic Society. Another user, Trey Mu, co-founded Soli Deo Gloria, a Christian fellowship group which has weekly Bible studies and prayer sessions. Second Life enables Christians from around the world to gather at any time of day. In addition, the anonymity allows people to discuss spiritual problems that might not as easily happen in real life, Mu said. Pray away the storms The Diocese of Baton Rouge observed the second annual Day of Prayer and Fasting for Protection During the Hurricane Season with a noon Mass Friday at St. Joseph Cathedral. Bishop Robert W. Muench presided. Camp Quest is the antithesis of church camp. Families who send their children to the Ohio summer camp are &ldquo;atheists, freethinkers, humanists, brights or whatever other terms might be applied to those who hold to a naturalistic, not supernatural, world view.&rdquo; Learn more online at Zachary soldier dies in bomb attack North Gate hanging on to history Philâs Oyster Bar hauls in faithful for one final night Harrellâs Hardware closes its doors Smiley Anders for June 4, 2007 Go to complete list Philâs Oyster Bar hauls in faithful for one final night Zachary soldier dies in bomb attack Tembec to close paper facility Sleepless struggles create waking woes North Gate hanging on to history Go to complete list The Lady 