http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-0&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/04/america/NA-GEN-US-Mercury-Messenger.php&cid=1116968868&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg NASA probe passing Venus on way to Mercury - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings NASA probe passing Venus on way to Mercury Published: June 4, 2007 NASA&#039;s Messenger probe makes its second pass by Venus on Tuesday, helping guide the spacecraft on its circuitous journey to Mercury and giving scientists a close-up look at Earth&#039;s cloud-shrouded neighbor. The fly-by will give researchers the rare opportunity to pair with a European space agency probe studying Venus. "This is the first time that we are able to take observations from two different vantage points," said Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington, the principal investigator for the Messenger program. If successful, Messenger, launched in August 2004, will be the first spacecraft to orbit Mercury, arriving in 2011. It also will be the first to visit the planet since Mariner 10 zoomed by three times in the mid-1970s. During Messenger&#039;s first pass by Venus in October, the planet was on the opposite side of the sun, putting it out of radio contact for two weeks. The spacecraft did not pass as close to the planet, so researchers decided against turning on the probe&#039;s instruments, Solomon said. Huge setback to Bush&#x27;s military tribunals at Guant&#xE1;namo Efficient adoption system attracts American couples to Ethiopia JFK plot was short on means and smarts The spacecraft cannot fly straight to Mercury because it is not carrying enough fuel, so it is flying once past Earth, twice past Venus and three times past Mercury for gravity assists before slowing enough to slip into orbit around the small, hot planet. While planets are often used to give probes gravity boosts to speed their travel, Messenger is using Venus to slow down and help guide it into orbit around Mercury, said Andy Calloway, Messenger mission operations manager at the Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory. Messenger is the seventh in NASA&#039;s Discovery program of lower-cost, scientifically focused space missions. The Applied Physics Laboratory, which built and operates the probe, manages the mission for NASA. The Venus flyby begins a "veritable inner-planetary roller coaster" ride over the next 18 months as it homes in on its final destination, said Eric Finnegan, Messenger mission systems engineer at the Applied Physics Laboratory. Messenger will pass 209 miles (336.3 kilometers) above the surface of Venus, using the planet to decelerate from 22.7 miles (36.5 kilometers) to 17.3 miles (27.8 kilometers) per second, putting the probe on target to pass Mercury for the first time in January. The encounter with Venus will also provides an opportunity for researchers to team with the European Space Agency&#039;s Venus Express mission to observe the planet second-closest to the sun. Messenger and the European Space Agency&#039;s Venus Express spacecraft will make joint measurements, for example, of how solar wind affects the planet&#039;s atmosphere. Hakan Svedhem, a Venus Express project scientist with the European Space Agency, said astronomers on Earth currently have an excellent view of Venus, and many will be watching the planet as the two probes take measurements. "So, we will get lots of data," Svedhem said. The flyby "provides an excellent opportunity, really, to study Venus from two points close to Venus and also from many points on Earth." Applied Physics Laboratory Messenger site: ESA Venus Express site: Meanwhile: I am, therefore I need to dance The four circles of a changing world Speakers bureaus give book authors a new income stream Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps 3 mild earthquakes rattle New Hampshire Drug may be first effective medication for liver cancer Hear the first victims of climate change Russia says it will target European sites if U.S. missile shield proceeds Inmates say Paris Hilton is in for a stay in &#39;hell&#39; Commanders say push in Baghdad is short of goal U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; Corruption in China: The anger boils over Chinese drug commissioner is sentenced to death Understanding and coping with tremors An escapee tells of life and death in North Korea&#39;s labor camps Malaysia rejects Muslim convert&#39;s bid to be recognized as Christian A rare glimpse of 19th-century Iran With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers Genes take charge, and diets fall by the wayside U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Tracing a poison&#39;s global path back to China Jet lag: How to make the best of a bad situation Do not neglect culture In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy The assault on Assyrian Christians No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; IHT.com on the go Listen to IHT articles on your computer, and create custom podcasts for your portable music player. Today's Page One in Europe Today's Page One in Asia Advertise with the IHT Copyright &#169; 2007 the International Herald Tribune All rights reserved
