s are increasingly backing the software. Companies have become more comfortable with subscription models such as those pioneered by Red Hat. Copyright Â© 2007 vnunet.com >> Submit this story to Digg New business opportunities for security and mobility resellers New Switches for your Growing Business from Linksys New Linksys Business Series Network Storage Right here, right now The demise of the local consulting division of research and analyst outfit Gartn... It's snowing in Hades What is the world coming to? We've got white rap-artists, Aussie darts champions... All you need is love But all the workers want is money. Now there's a surprise. One of our recr... Hot Stories on CRN Linksys achieves 1000 resellers Sage Australia boosts partner support Jury slams Business Objects for US$25 million in Informatica patent suit Partners: Three wishes for Cisco Spam soars in 1Q, small businesses under fire Xerox to acquire Global Imaging Systems for US$1.5B Microsoft loosens grip on Vista Enterprise licensing NetApp signs CDW for small-biz array, VARs not worried HP sketches new vision for the smart home Old-timer tops March malware list Foundation won't punish Novell Open source license changes could kill Microsoft deal IBM looks to open up development Three scenarios for Microsoft's open source threat Open Source product gets a facelift Pirated software leaves firms open to hackers Google open to mergers Nortel and Microsoft open joint demo centres Whitepaper - Benefits for Fibre Channel (FC) SANs. As the volume and criticality of data grows, companies need efficient, scalable solutions for making data available to servers, applications and users across the enterprise. No polls are currently available. Linksys achieves 1000 resellers Sage Australia boosts partner support Jury slams Business Objects for US$25 million in Informatica patent suit Partners: Three wishes for Cisco Spam soars in 1Q, small businesses under fire Xerox to acquire Global Imaging Systems for US$1.5B Mi