http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-6&fd=R&url=http://news.com.com/Apple%2Bcriticized%2Bfor%2Bembedding%2Bnames,%2Be-mails%2Bin%2Bsongs/2100-1027_3-6188337.html&cid=1116735750&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Apple criticized for embedding names, e-mails in songs | CNET News.com Apple criticized for embedding names, e-mails in songs Songs available on iTunes Plus reveal users' personal information. Privacy group suspects Apple goofed. Staff Writer, CNET News.com Published: June 1, 2007, 6:15 PM PDT Last modified: June 2, 2007, 1:08 PM PDT A correction was made to this story. Read below for details. It used to be that music fans believed cryptic messages about Satan or the death of a band member were hidden within rock albums. Nowadays, the secrets buried in digital music are way too easy to find, according to the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF). The consumer watchdog group, which focuses on the Web, is taking issue with Apple's practice of embedding customer information within iTunes music. Apple includes customer names and e-mail addresses within song files purchased from iTunes, according to Fred von Lohmann, an EFF attorney. Several tech blogs wrote about the embedded information this week after Apple , a service that features music stripped of controversial copy-protection software. Von Lohmann pointed out that data could easily be compromised if an iPod is lost or stolen. "It's not as bad as losing a credit card number," von Lohmann said, "but it's still information that people wouldn't want floating around out there--especially without them knowing about it." Apple hasn't said why the company would leave customer information exposed. But some observers have speculated that Apple is adding watermarks to music files. Watermarking describes the practice of inserting identifying information into digital files so they can be tracked. Privacy groups frown on such practices, but von Lohmann doubts that these were Apple's Newsmaker: For F-Secure, it's all about the safety net Crave: It's the gear you've gotta see Extra: Don't call it a bubble Mike Goodman, a Yankee Group Research analyst, argued that watermarking is "certainly better than digital rights management. "Watermarking does not treat the consumer like a criminal," Goodman said. "DRM is also restrictive, telling you how many times you can play a song or which device it can be played on. Watermarking works on the assumption that a consumer is innocent but provides the industry an opportunity to catch someone that breaks the law." earlier reported on the personal information within iTunes' music. This story erroneously reported that Apple had in the past encrypted personal information of iTunes customers embedded within music files. The data is available in clear text. More from News.com on this story's topics Create an email alert Create an email alert Create an email alert I would want to know Jun 4, 2007, 12:17 PM PDT Good idea, bad implementation Jun 3, 2007, 8:25 PM PDT CNet jumping on the FUD bandwagon Jun 3, 2007, 11:28 AM PDT CNet jumping on the FUD bandwagon Jun 3, 2007, 11:15 AM PDT Jun 3, 2007, 10:54 AM PDT DRM way better then my info! Jun 3, 2007, 7:32 AM PDT Jun 2, 2007, 11:36 PM PDT Jun 2, 2007, 6:12 PM PDT People forget or don't care now Jun 2, 2007, 5:49 PM PDT If I lose my cell phone Jun 2, 2007, 5:33 PM PDT Jun 2, 2007, 4:01 PM PDT How's that medicine tasting? Jun 2, 2007, 2:16 PM PDT Jun 2, 2007, 1:23 PM PDT Jun 2, 2007, 1:20 PM PDT Just noise to put fear into buying iTunes Plus tracks Jun 2, 2007, 10:23 AM PDT Damned if you do... Jun 2, 2007, 10:11 AM PDT Well some of the comments are enlightening... Jun 2, 2007, 9:50 AM PDT CNET, are you going to clarify this article? Jun 2, 2007, 9:49 AM PDT This is like sewing my name in a shirt... Jun 2, 2007, 8:35 AM PDT Misleading! Old iTunes files have this too!! Jun 2, 2007, 8:31 AM PDT Just Relax and enjoy the music on other devices Jun 2, 2007, 7:40 AM PDT Jun 2, 2007, 7:36 AM PDT Jun 2, 2007, 6:42 AM 