on revenue as a business model, something common among open-source companies, while larger enterprises are also getting on board. Financial backing from venture capitalists is helping to boost growth, IDC said. Software distribution is growing, but revenues will take longer to follow suit, researchers found. That's partly because much open-source software is free, while other products use a subscription revenue model rather than getting users to pay a lump sum up front. Open-Source Software and Its Role in Space Exploration CIO.com Blog: The Open Source Why CIOs Dont Care About Open Source Five Compelling Reasons to Use MySQL Eight Sound Reasons Not to Use MySQL Open-Source Software and Its Role in Space Exploration Ask, Answer and Interact with the CIO Community IDC: Open-Source Market to Be Worth $5.8B by 2011 Microsoft Trounces Pro-ODF Forces in State Battles More Information, More Records Management Options Geoff Nesnow, Iron Mountain's senior manager of data protection market strategy, outlines some options and strategies for protecting everything from CRM data... Sponsored by Iron Mountain Remote Office Solutions with HP's Consolidated Client Infrastructure The drive for productivity is compelling organizations of all sizes to explore and utilize offshoring for important operational activities. Taking advantage... Successful Strategies for IP Business Communications How to effectively utilize and manage your mobile workforce... Sponsored by Interactive Intelligence Microsoft and Open Source CIO Publisher Gary Beach muses about the possibility of Microsoft making the Vista operating system open to the public. How would changing this business model impact Microsoft and its customers? Get the guidance you need to up-level IT service and deliver unparalleled value. An Interview with Eben Moglen, General Counsel for the Free Software Foundation Eben Moglen, Chair of the Software Freedom Law Center and General Counsel to the Free Software Foundation explains the hi