ot the shooter fans' system of choice. In short, the shooter was something that system did very well, and they were easy to localize since there was little to no text. There were many shooters for the Genesis and SNES too, but the VC is looking more at the big titles they had instead of the shooters. To be blunt, the TG16 didn't do very well outside Japan, and they are quickly running out of "quality" games for the VC. Unless they decide to make the CD games (which were often the best games on the system) you're going to see less and less in the way of TG16 games. Bloody Wolf - Top down contra style game. Legendary Axe - platform/action game, one of the marquee titles of the system. Legendary Axe 2 - see above not as good. China Warrior - This was a system seller. Imagine Street Fighter but you had to fight stuff on the way to each guy. The sprites were huge. Deep Blue - an underwater shooter where everything was a fish of some sort, this was before Darius. Cadash - Action RPG, the first Working Designs game. Keith Courage in Alpha Zones - This was the pack-in game for the system and a darn good one. Cyber Core - A shooter were everything was a bionic insect. One thing I miss from Virtual Console is the old box art. Every game should have the box art viewable, similar to itunes. The TG16 is hands-down the biggest offender on hoagly box art. I sometimes wonder if that was one of the contributing factors to its failure. I may have to upload some shots in a post. Posted Jun 4, 2007 1:39 pm PT to rate this comment Chirico_Cuvie Posted Jun 4, 2007 1:39 pm PT (does not meet display criteria. login to show) Zelda II is great! One of the best RPG's for the NES! You guys should just stop underrating it. Posted Jun 4, 2007 1:33 pm PT to rate this comment Deku_Grumble Posted Jun 4, 2007 1:33 pm PT (does not meet display criteria. login to show) Actually, some people got a disc with TLOZ, TLOZ 2 and some other stuff on it, and some people got OoT/Master Quest. I'm not sure exac