ding them to Live Digital.com. The episodes ended up scooping Fox -- showing up online more than a week before they aired in January. Romero is charged with one felony count of uploading copyrighted material to a publicly accessible computer network -- while knowing the work was intended for commercial distribution. He's to turn himself in at a federal court in Chicago tomorrow, when arrangements will be made for him to travel to Los Angeles. If convicted, Romero could get a maximum of 3 years in prison. ON THE WEB: SOCIAL NETWORKING FOR MOMS CYBERSPACE (AP) - When you think social networking sites on the Internet, chances are you think of teenagers or young adults. But in this case, it's a social networking site for moms. CafeMom is a site that already has some 300,000 members -- but can always make room for a few more. It's set up by Meridith Vieira and Andrew Shue and lets moms swap stories, discuss a variety of topics and share photos in addition to setting up public or private groups with other moms who have similar interests. IN STORES: APPLE iPHONE GETS LAUNCH DATE NEW YORK (AP) - Circle your calendar -- and save up your money. Apple has announced a date -- and price point -- for its iPhone. A company spokesman confirms what its tv ads have been saying: that the highly-anticipated device will be available for sale on June 29th. The iPhone is a combination of a cell phone, media player and wireless Internet device that will sell for either 499 or $599, depending on how it's configured. 1 of its main features is a touch-sensitive screen which is used instead of a keypad to activate the various features. The communications and media playing device is being offered exclusively by AT & T's wireless division, which used to be known as Cingular. by Oscar Wells Gabriel II Oscar Gabriel can be reached at ogabriel@ap.org. Copyright 2007 The Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. All content &cop