ogle, Yahoo, MSN, and AOL. Overall 4 percent of all search results link to risky Web sites. The good news is search engines have gotten safer compared to data from last year when McAfee found 5 percent of sites linked to questionable web sites. According to the results of the study, the top four most dangerous searches on Google are: 1. bearshare: yielding 46 percent "dangerous" links 2. limewire: yielding 37 percent "dangerous" links 3. Kazaa: yielding 35 percent "dangerous" links 4. winmx: yielding 32 percent "dangerous" links The study defined dangerous sites as those that have one or a combination of the following characteristics: its downloads contain spyware and/or adware; its pages contain embedded code that performs browser exploits; the content is meant to deceive visitors in some way; it sends out inordinate amounts of spam to e-mail accounts registered at the site. McAfee's SiteAdvisor browser toolbar identifies risky sites by flagging them (should you visit one) with a "red" warning or a "yellow" cautionary label that appears in your browser. You can download a free version of the McAfee SiteAdvisor Also at risk are sponsored ads which show up alongside search results. According to the study these links have even a greater chance of linking to risky sites. McAfee says 7 percent of such link to suspect sites (down from 8.5 percent in 2006). we've reported on some of the problems of dangerous sponsored links. In this blog posting colleague Erik Larkin wrote about booby traps hiding in Google sponsored links For its part, Google has made efforts to from its Google Sponsored Links. / 1000 max characters Western Digital Ships 750GB Hard Drive Mozilla Updates Thunderbird 1.5 Security Flaws Found In Up-to-date IE7, Firefox 2 Microsoft Cuts Patent Deal With Xandros Linux Study: Dangerous Side of Search Engines Plextor Introduces New 18X SATA DVD Burner Google Maps, Tabby Cats, Black Helicopters, and You LCD wide screen monitors &copy; 1998-2007, PC World Communications, Inc. Terms of Service Agreement PC World Latin America
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-0&fd=R&url=http://www.informationweek.com/news/showArticle.jhtml%3FarticleID%3D199900893&cid=1116953893&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Toshiba Set To Release Slim HD DVD-RW Drive For Notebooks -- HD DVD -- InformationWeek CMP - United Business Media Business Innovation Powered By Technology Part of the TechWeb Business Technology Network Get News On Your Phone Toshiba Set To Release Slim HD DVD-RW Drive For Notebooks The write speed for the new drives ranges from 4x to 16x, depending on the disc being written to. Jun 4, 2007 01:30 PM Toshiba plans to unveil on Tuesday a slim, rewriteable HD DVD drive for notebook PCs. The SD-L912A is a half-inch thick and can read, write, and rewrite to HD DVD-RW discs, and read and write to HD DVD-R discs and to standard DVDs and CDs. The Japanese company plans to start shipping samples of the drive to PC makers next month, Toshiba said in a statement. If the storage and editing of high-definition content increases as expected, then consumers will likely need additional storage capacity. Spurring demand for storage outside of a PC's hard drive are such devices as high-definition camcorders, Toshiba said. In addition, the increasing number of HDTVs is driving the overall demand for high definition content. During the 2006 holiday season, for example, LCD TVs capable of playing HD content led sales in consumer electronics, according to the NPD Group. Spending on LCD TVs soared by 109% over 2005 to $924 million. The write speed for the new drives ranges from 4x to 16x, depending on the disc being written to. Reading speeds have a maximum of 8x on a DVD, and 24x on a CD. A single-layer disc can store up to 20GB of information, which is about four times more than a standard DVD disc. Toshiba is scheduled to introduce the drive in Taipei at Computex 2007, which runs through June. 9. Make IT run. Make IT safe. Run IT run. BigFix IT.Next is now! Read how other organizations gain competitive edge with predictive analytics. Make informed decisions about spending, building, and managing storage technology with Byte and Switch A Day in the Life of a Business Process Analyst Top ten search terms from the TechWeb TechEncyclopedia Ready to take that job and shove it? Give your recruitment message influence. Advertise in the BTG - Now Hiring Union Telephone/Union Wireless seeking Network Administration Specialist in Mountain View, WY General Electric Transportation seeking Controls Design Engineer in Erie, PA American Home Mortgage seeking .NET Developer in Melville, NY Openlink Financial, Inc. seeking Java Developer in Uniondale, NY Union Telephone/Union Wireless seeking LAN/WAN Administrator in Mountain View, WY For more great jobs, career-related news, features and services, please visit our Senators Mull A Dual Track For Green Card, And More H-1Bs Compromise expected soon would keep employer sponsorship and merit points. It would also put no cap on visas for U.S.-educated recipients of advanced degrees. Indian Service Providers Turn To Software Market Talent crunch in financial market makes software sales more appealing. More articles from our career center Broadcom Ships PC Cards, Chipset For High-Def Playback Can Apple iPhone Live Up To The Hype? NXP Unveils 802.11n Module To Network Devices Flash Memory Use Expected To Soar In Portable Media Players Secure Mobile Access Using SSL VPNs Podcast: Securing Mobile Devices on Converged Networks Trusted Computing is Real and it &apos; s Here - Adopting the Trusted Platform Module (TPM) for ... Protect Your Business from Costly Data Theft Tips for Ensuring End User Adoption For A Global Enterprise Application Roll-Out Virtualized Infrastructures: Static Security to Virtual Shields Multiple Displays for Workstation Applications Planning Service Availability Improvements A Day in the Life of a Business Process Analyst Transform your Enterprise: Synchronizing Business and IT VIEW ALL BRIEFING CENTERS Apply for a free 52-we