http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-1&fd=R&url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/hidden-itunes-info-raises-privacy/story.aspx%3Fguid%3D%257B7B311376-A946-43F0-A7E1-170E17DB39F0%257D&cid=1116735750&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Hidden iTunes info raises privacy fears: report - MarketWatch Mutual Funds & ETFs Hidden iTunes info raises privacy fears: report Last Update: 10:31 PM ET Jun 3, 2007 LONDON (MarketWatch) -- Privacy fears were sparked after it emerged that Apple embedded personal details into music files bought from its iTunes music store, The Times in London reported Saturday. Technology Web sites examining iTunes products discovered that personal data, including the names and e-mail addresses of purchasers, were inserted into the files that Apple uses to distribute music tracks, The Times said. According to the newspaper, the information is also included in tracks sold under Apple's iTunes Plus system, where users pay a premium for music that is free from the digital rights management (DRM) intended to protect against piracy. The Electronic Freedom Foundation, the online consumer rights group, said it was possible that the data could be used to "watermark" tracks so that the original purchaser could be tracked down if a track appeared on a file-sharing network, the newspaper said. An Apple spokeswoman was unable to comment, The Times added. Newspaper Web site: http://www.timesonline.co.uk Related Blog Posts & Articles Investors embrace Wal-Mart's strategy change; shares gain Relations with Russia to overshadow Group of Eight summit U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Crude rallies on rising demand, Gulf storm, Russia Sign up to receive the Weekend TV Show Preview U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Shanghai tumbles 8.3% on concern about more cooling moves DRAM chipmakers to suffer worst quarter since 2001 U.S. stock futures drop with bond yield rise, China in focus Five littl