http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-4&fd=R&url=http://www.nj.com/news/ledger/index.ssf%3F/base/news-11/1180845174152040.xml%26coll%3D1&cid=1116863537&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Publishers plan for post-Potter market- NJ.com Monday, June 04, 2007 Today's Paper & More Publishers plan for post-Potter market Sunday, June 03, 2007 BY AMY ELLIS NUTT The center of the literary universe -- BookExpo America -- closes shop today at the Jacob Javits Convention Center in New York City, ending a weekend-long love-fest between booksellers and publishers. But despite the long, merry autograph lines and the rush for free copies of future bestsellers at this largest annual publishing event in the United States, the business forecast is mixed at best. The 2007 annual trade report from Book Industry Trends, released on Friday, indicated that U.S. sales were flat last year, with a meager 0.5 percent increase in the total number of books sold between 2005 (3.09 billion) and 2006 (3.1 billion). And while the big book chains continue their dominance of the market, independent book stores are continuing to take a hit, their numbers shrinking from 1,660 last spring to 1,580 in 2007, according to the American Booksellers Association. To counter declining sales, the paper-based, brick-and-mortar business of bookselling is increasingly turning to the Web. Sprinkled among the more than 2,000 exhibitors at the Javits Center were three Internet heavyweights -- Google, Microsoft and Amazon.com -- which all announced new marketing tools to help publishers and retailers better sell their wares. Microsoft launched a second segment of its online library. With author and publisher approval, the company now will include copyrighted works in its Live Search Books index, which allows users to find answers to questions by searching the content of specific books. "We are only scanning and uploading and indexing in-copyright content with express permission of the rights holders," said Microsoft spokesperson Clifford Guren. "People love what they see. They're liking it very much." Microsoft began its off-copyright library last December and the company's announcement this week comes on the heels of the controversy created by Google when it announced in December 2004 that it planned to digitize the world's books. The lawsuits from authors and publishers still making their way through the courts have forced other companies, such as Microsoft, to tread more lightly. "The value of Live Search Books has been apparent to most of our publishers," said Guren, "but lots of things had to be worked out. There hasn't been any resistance, just the normal give-and-take. It's been a learning experience for all of us." Among the handful of publishers that already have signed on are Cambridge University Press, McGraw-Hill and Simon & Schuster. Tucked behind the German books exhibit in one of the Javits Center's main halls, employees of Amazon.com were showing off their new Content Acquisition Program. The networking tool allows publishers who are interested in selling rights or increasing distribution of their work to make available online the sales and marketing data for designated titles. Editors viewing the data are then free to contact the publishers of those titles. Insider tore cloak off pipeline plot Youth won't hurt AG nominee Fear runs through Linden after plan to bomb pipeline &copy; 2007 The Star-Ledger. Used by NJ.com with permission. Spring Home and Garden Best of NJ Book 1 Best of NJ Book 2 RSS Terms and Conditions &copy; 2007 New Jersey On-Line LLC. All Rights Reserved. Use of this site constitutes acceptance of our
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-3&fd=R&url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/media/article1871173.ece&cid=1116735750&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Fresh privacy fears have been sparked after it emerged that Apple has embedded personal information into music files bought from its iTunes online music store. Technology websites examining iTunes products discovered that personal data, including the name and e-mail addresses of purchasers, are embedded into the AAC files that Apple uses to distribute music tracks." /> Personal data found hidden in iTunes tracks-Business-Industry Sectors-Media-TimesOnline Best of the weekend, from The Times and The Sunday Times Navigation - link to other main sections from here Bad films just needs the love of a good viewer Personal data found hidden in iTunes tracks Names, e-mails and other sensitive information embedded in files Fresh privacy fears have been sparked after it emerged that Apple has embedded personal information into music files bought from its iTunes online music store. Technology websites examining iTunes products discovered that personal data, including the name and e-mail addresses of purchasers, are embedded into the AAC files that Apple uses to distribute music tracks. The information is also included in tracks sold under Apple&rsquo;s iTunes Plus system, launched this week, where users pay a premium for music that is free from the controversial digital rights (DRM) software that is designed to safeguard against piracy. , the online consumer rights group, added that it had identified a large amount of additional unaccounted-for information in iTunes files. It said it was possible that the data could be used to &ldquo;watermark&rdquo; tracks so that the original purchaser could be tracked down were a track to appear on a file-sharing network. Google Street View privacy row iTunes releases copyright free music Jobs meets Gates - the web's verdict , among the first websites to unveil the hidden information, said: &ldquo;Everyone should be aware that while DRM-free files may lift a lot of restrictions on our personal usage habits, it doesn't mean that we can just start sharing the love, so to speak. Sharer beware.&rdquo; An Apple spokeswoman was unable to comment when contacted by The discovery of the data, of which most iTunes users will have been unaware, underscores the reluctance of music groups to allow music to circulate freely over the web. With estimates suggesting that 40 tracks are digitally bootlegged for every legally downloaded track, piracy remains a massive problem for the industry and music groups have largely proven reluctant to withdraw the controversial DRM technologies. Apple had sought to present itself as a consumer champion, with the group&rsquo;s chief executive, Steve Jobs, insisting earlier this year that his company would drop DRM &ldquo;in a heartbeat&rdquo; if allowed to by the labels. Previously, Apple&rsquo;s DRM system had been criticised by several European regulators for being anti-competitive because it only allowed tracks to be played on Apple's iPod digital music players. Apple's iTunes Plus service, launched this week, offers DRM-free music of a higher quality than standard iTunes tracks for 99p a song &ndash; compared with 79p for a standard track. Users who opt to pay extra for iTunes Plus tracks will be able to play the music without limitations on the type of music player or number of computers that purchased songs can be played on. The service is launching with EMI&rsquo;s digital catalogue of outstanding recordings, including singles and albums from Coldplay, The Rolling Stones, Norah Jones, Frank Sinatra, Joss Stone, Pink Floyd and John Coltrane. Steve Jobs, the Apple chief executive, said: &ldquo;We expect more than half of the songs on iTunes will be offered in iTunes Plus versions by the end of this year.&rdquo; Online music sales still account for only 10 per cent of the total market and are not yet growing at a rate which compensates for the decline in revenues from CDs &ndash; approximately 2 to 3 per cent per year. EMI, which has previously released tracks by Norah Jones and Lily Allen without copyright protection, shelved plans to drop DRM on a more widespread basis after iTunes competitors refused to make &ldquo;risk insurance&rdquo; payments designed to offset potential losses that would result from the move. It is unclear whether Apple has made any such payment. Other labels, including Universal Music and Sony BMG, have experimented with offering music without DRM, but none has pursued the strategy as aggressively as EMI. The iTunes Store has sold over 2.5 billion songs, 50 million TV shows and over two million movies, making it the leader in each of those markets. Perhaps people would feel more guilty about sharing music online if the price of tracks fell to reflect the record companies savings in pressing plants, packaging, cover printing, distribution, transport, staffing, shop rent and salaries produced by the download revolution. It might also help if British consumers did not have to pay more than consumers in the rest of Europe (common market anyone?) This is another example of rip-off Britain where consumers are taken for a ride by overpaid and under-talented recording artists and their greedy record labels. I wouldn't pay a pound a track from iTunes to load onto a player that scratches instantly and is only designed to last for a year before the battery fails. Still, ' a fool and his money are easily parted.' For those who don't know, radio stations pay licensing fees in order to broadcast music. The aren't allowed to do it for free. You can open the *.mp4 file with notepad (it will take a while) and see the information right there at the top. If you change it, it will not play in the ipod or itunes. Well hell, since there's no danger why don't we put some sensitive info from Apple or Steve Jobs in there? Shouldn't be a problem since that info's "already out there" right? Apart from that, do bear in mind that when you give any large entity an inch they will want to take a few more yards. This is true for both government and business. At least a business will have limits because it doesn't want to offend consumers though. People are stunned that their name, email, etc., is being embedded in files. In the US where identity theft is so big of a deal and everyone is so paranoid to even list the city they are from on forums like this, in a business sense it doesn't seem like a very smart move. I agree that this information isn't exactly that sensitive. But 1) It opens doors to other stuff (remember Sony's rootkit in their CDs?), and 2) Consumer ignorance can really hurt you. Whether something is true or not is irrelevant when feelings are involved. Gee, guys... my name and often my email address is found in many of the software applications that I have installed on my computer... What's different? It hasn't been hidden. Highlight the iTunes song, click "Get Info" on Macs, click "Properties" on Windows, and there is the so-called "hidden" information. It's been there since Apple instituted iTunes sales. This is merely FUD in anticipation of the WWDC announcements in a couple of weeks and the release of the iPhone on June 29th. Andrew Smith, Stockton, CA I don't see why people are complaining, if you bought a cd or an LP (remember those) with your name and address on it would you see it as a problem? I think not. Just don't buy anything from Apple if it's a problem, I don't. If you have a decent hi-fi even CD only sounds so-so anyway, so I don't see why you would want to degrade it any further unless on the move. Keith , Copenhagen, Denmark How can you possibly equate lending a book to someone with posting music on a website for people to help themselves to!!!? Try this then run off a couple of thousend copies of your favourite book and set up a website were anyone can request a copy for free. .... see