http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-4&fd=R&url=http://www.dnaindia.com/report.asp%3FNewsID%3D1100930&cid=1116692570&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg DNA - Evolutions - Space Shuttle ride for the earthbound - Daily News & Analysis Open in new window Space Shuttle ride for the earthbound Sunday, June 03, 2007 20:16 IST To reprint this article, contact CAPE CANAVERAL: If youre not one of the seven people scheduled to ride on the space shuttle next week, take heart: NASA has opened a launch simulator for the rest of us. It wont take years of training, and your commitment to space travel can be over in 30 minutes or so, depending on how long the lines are. Of course, it doesnt really go anywhere. But for a few minutes, as you tip backward in your seat and let the special effects of the simulated rocket ride take hold, its easy enough to suspend disbelief. Thats the appeal of the Shuttle Launch Experience, a $60 million attraction that opened last weekend at Kennedy Space Centers Visitors Complex in Florida. With input from 27 current and former shuttle astronauts, designer BRC Imagination Arts, spent years crafting an experience that would come as close as possible to a real shuttle launch. BRC chief Bob Rogers says the experience is more than a ride. Before people strap in, they get to hear a breezy, lecture about space shuttle technology given by veteran astronaut Charlie Bolden, he said. Its a good overview of the program, though the Shuttles impending retirement may make the details a bit irrelevant. The shuttles are being mothballed in 2010 because they did not meet their original intent of delivering people and cargo to low-Earth orbit safely, cheaply and often. There is no better reminder of this than the fact that after 25 years of Shuttle flights, ordinary people are relegated to a simulator, however realistic it may be. Nevertheless, the Shuttle Launch Experience is a good ride, with enough sound, vibration and special effects to launch imaginations, if nothing else. But for those who actually want to rocket into space, the experience might fall flat. At the end of the launch, the shuttles cargo bay doors open, and while the sight that unfolds may well be state-of-the-art, with an orbital view of Italy projected onto a curved screen and a black-sky background flecked with moving stars, it may be hard not to feel a bit let down. More articles in Evolutions &#187; Apple's iPhone to debut on June 29 Record distance set in quantum communication Index finger length could predict childrens intelligence (This name will appear below your comment.) (Will not be published.) (Please note: Comment moderation is enabled and may delay your comment. There is no need to resubmit your comment.) Total 2 comments | It's depressing. The shittle was a bad, half-assed compromise from the start, and now all we have left is a Disney ride? Monday, June 04, 2007 Is the shuttle going to be replaced with a vehicle that will provide "people and cargo to low-Earth orbit safely, cheaply and often?" Hardly. The so-called "crew exploration vehicle" has drastically less capability for servicing the ISS and it cannot deploy or service satelites such as Hubble. By retiring the Shuttle, the country will be walking away from a $200B investment in ISS/Shuttle infrastructure that could lead to solar power generation, space tourism, and long-term research benefits. For what are these benefits being abandoned for? Sending 3 or 4 astronauts to the moon for no reason? Yes, NASA hq. oversold the "routine" nature of Shuttle flights. Going into space with the limits of present technology is, and will remain, (1)very expensive, and (2) very dangerous. However, it is a shame that the United States is going to abdicate its present leadership in manned spaceflight that it has established with the Shuttle/ISS technology. The decision to retire the Shuttle fleet reveals, like the decision to invade Iraq, that the present administration lacks the wisdom to make the right calls on the big issues. K Thompson Monday, June 04, 2007 View all comments &#187; Get daily news in your inbox and read it at your convenience. Putin warns retribution for US missile system The big coach hunt Whatmore out, Ford is prime contender for India job Rajasthan burns... Delhi, NCR feel the heat Reliance Fresh set for a roll-out in Mumbai Shilpa Shetty to be honoured at IIFA for global impact BJP hopes hinge on an IITian engineer in Goa Cricket board to name new coach today My film not adapted: Siddharth Anand CMDA erred in sending notice to AIADMK: MK Al Gore against any attempt to impeach Bush Chennai's land prices costlier than London Woman commits suicide as husband refuses to have sex Google to make Web work offline Bollywood in the Big Apple Microsoft rethinks computer with coffee-table design The Universe is Riyo's! Mel Gibson buys $25.8m ranch in Costa Rica US anti-war activist Cindy Sheehan abandons campaign Regular use of laptop could be hazardous Dharavi man held for sexually abusing 11 kids Priyanka signs a three-film deal with UTV My sons are typical Deols Russia successfully test fires next generation missile Putin warns retribution for US missile system Six-month traineeship for new coach Russia ups the stakes in US missile shield row A prosecution-defence nexus in BMW case? US anti-war activist Cindy Sheehan abandons campaign Microsoft rethinks computer with coffee-table design Al Gore against any attempt to impeach Bush Puja did not deserve to be Miss Universe: Rohit Bal Bollywood in the Big Apple Indian American husband jailed for plotting wife's murder The Universe is Riyo's! © 2005-2007 Diligent Media Corporation Ltd. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-2&fd=R&url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ap/fn/4858703.html&cid=1116948986&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Sony Cuts Price on New Blu-Ray Player | Chron.com - Houston Chronicle " width="11" height="11" border="0"> Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Travel News & Features Legal & Public Notices June 3, 2007, 11:03PM Sony Cuts Price on New Blu-Ray Player By PETER SVENSSON AP Technology Writer &copy; 2007 The Associated Press NEW YORK &mdash; With dominance of the market for high-definition movie discs still up in the air, Sony Corp. said Monday it is including a small surprise with the new Blu-ray disc player it is shipping this week: a price tag $100 lower than previously announced. When Sony announced the BDP-S300 player in February, it put the price at $599, but it has now set a list price at $499. That means the new player costs half of what the company's first Blu-ray player cost when it launched just six months ago _ probably one of the fastest price declines in the consumer electronics industry. The new player has essentially the same capabilities as the older BDP-S1 but is smaller. The price cut is due to falling production costs and the growing demand for Blu-ray products, according to Chris Fawcett, vice president of Sony Electronics' home products division. Sony has been undersold in the market for high-definition disc players by Toshiba, which created the rival HD DVD format. Its players are now selling for less than $300, 14 months after Toshiba's first player appeared in U.S. stores. Neither Blu-ray nor HD DVD players have caught on strongly with consumers, who have been waiting for the market to settle on one of the formats. But dropping prices for players and HDTV sets in more homes mean a big showdown between the discs may be looming this holiday season. Hollywood studios are split on the issue, but Blu-ray has the strongest support. Most people buying Blu-ray discs are apparently buying them for their Sony PlayStation 3 game consoles. The cheapest version of the console costs $499, but its game-oriented wireless controller and relatively loud fan makes it a less than ideal movie player. Chittenden to Buy Community Bank & Trust Magna's Stock Jumps on UBS Report Homex Appoints New Chief Executive Printer Ink Retailers Await Ruling Kaman Declares Regular Dividend American Airlines' May Traffic Falls Diamond Foods Raises 2007 Sales View Josiah Sutton: One Year Later Hey Ray! I'm feelin' kinda Blu... Security group says it fixed DVD flaw that allowed hacks For many, journey begins at road's end Hollywood, consumer electronics makers hitch up Updated: Another one bites the dust: Blu-ray DRM compromised It's not just you: Penguins really are running Hollywood The rise of Ken Lay as dramatic as his fall Buy Photos & Page Prints 2005-Present Historic Page Prints 1901-2004 Copyright Notice & Privacy Policy
