next-generation games with budgets in the $10-20M range. You need to run on ordinary mass-market PCs as well. In reading PC gaming websites, one might get the impression that everyone owns a dual-core PC with a pair of $600 GPUs in SLI configuration, but the reality is very different. More than 80% of PCs sold today are still single-core, and have very low-end DirectX9 graphics capabilities. Unreal Engine 3 supports those configurations well. There really isn&#039;t a lot of solid info but the and Unreal Engine information is at least interesting for hardware minded folks. ESRB Initiative Supports Indie Retailers Posted by Shawn on Monday, June 4th, 2007 at 10:19 am Forests beware. The Entertainment Software Rating Board ( ) and entertainment product distributor Ingram Entertainment Inc. have announced a new initiative in support of Indie Retailers. 10,000 independent and small chain retailers nationwide will receive ready-to-use in-store signage explaining the ESRB rating system and supporting store policy of denying sale of M rated video games to children 17 and under. âThe ESRB actively supports retailers in their efforts with respect to the sale or rental of video games, and their support of the ratings has been tremendous, as evidenced by the most recent report from the FTC,â said ESRB president Patricia Vance. âOur partnership with national retail outlets continues to be strong, and with the help of Ingram Entertainment weâre helping smaller, independent retailers across the country inform their consumers about the rating system and support their store policies.â What this means for the consumer is more signs and shelving strips to inundate those parents who just don&#039;t get the ESRB ratings. Bob Geistman, chairman of the Entertainment Merchants Association (EMA) and Senior Vice President of Sales and Marketing for Ingram Entertainment asserts that this initiative can only bring retailers and consumers closer together. âIndie retailers are a vibrant and significant part of the video game market, tending to offer a neighborhood environment that endears them to their customers. Providing this signage to these thousands of stores will undoubtedly help foster that unique and personal relationship by enabling stores to offer their customers information that is vital to the way they buy and rent games.â This article is rated E for everyone. Lion&#039;s Gate Profits from Xbox Live Posted by Shawn on Monday, June 4th, 2007 at 10:17 am has the latest figures released by movie company Lion&#039;s Gate Entertainment. The company has a number of downloadable assets on Microsoft&#039;s Xbox Live service and is claiming a 50% boost in profit from downloads. &#034;Our VOD revenues grew by approximately 50% in fiscal 2007 from the previous year,&#034; said Lions Gate&#039;s Feltheimer, adding, &#034;our Internet delivered digital revenue grew by a multiple of 7 in fiscal â07 compared to the prior year, although obviously from a relatively small base.&#034; Employee of the Month , both Lion&#039;s Gate properties showed up on Major Nelson&#039;s best seller I&#039;ve personally only rented one film from the service so far, and I&#039;m not likely to do it again honestly. There is something about the digital limits imposed that just don&#039;t thrill me - especially when DVD offers special features and unlimited rewatching thanks to Netflix or purchase at Best Buy. Maybe I&#039;m just not the right consumer for these services though - I like physical things. RollerCoaster Tycoon Illustrates Housing Market History Posted by Shawn on Monday, June 4th, 2007 at 9:53 am The US Housing Market has been quite a wild ride. It had it&#039;s up the last several years although currently it&#039;s going down. has posted a unique graphical representation of the US markets rise and fall over the years. Richard Hodge posted A History of Home Values from 1890 to today as a roller coaster generated with . The data was compiled by Yale ec