n Document Format (ODF) for Office Applications, instead of Microsoft Corp.'s proprietary Office formats. The legislation was heavily backed by uses the file format in its Notes 8 software, and , which sells the ODF-compliant But a bill introduced earlier this year met a quick death. And in Florida, Texas and Oregon, would-be laws were all killed off within the past month while being debated in legislative committees, following fierce opposition from Microsoft lobbyists and allies of the software vendor. The most recent defeat occurred last Thursday in California, where a toned-down version of a bill open formats was declared to be stalled in the state assembly's Committee on Appropriations -- even though the bill's sponsor, a Democratic assemblyman for San Francisco, chairs the committee. A spokesman for Leno declined to comment on the fate of the bill, which was in February. But Microsoft also fought the proposal in California The only recent victory for advocates of open formats was a Pyrrhic one. Your Votes Tallied: The Biggest Tech Flop of All Time Q&A: Clearing up misconceptions about mixing blade servers and virtualization Don't Believe the Hype: The 21 Biggest Technology Flops " It's Monday's IT Blogwatch: in which we worry about Google's security. Not to mention I HAS 1337 CODE LOL!!1... " Zulfikar Ramzan is right on in his demolition of Mikko Hypponen's idea for a ".bank" top-level domain. Writing on..." Read more Desktop Applications posts Microsoft trounces pro-ODF forces in state battles over open document formats Spam spikes wreak havoc Group rips Microsoft over Internet user profiling research Stealthy attack serves malicious code only once New zero-day bugs crop up in IE, Firefox Shipboard offshore development plan still docked after two years Don't Believe the Hype: The 21 Biggest Technology Flops We fondly recall 21 overpromoted products and technologies that utterly failed to live up to their hype. You choose the biggest flop of all. Why cell phon