http://www.sci-tech-today.com/news/Open-Source-a--6B-Industry-by-2011/story.xhtml%3Fstory_id%3D010001472N2G&cid Sci-Tech Today | IDC: Open Source a $6B Industry by 2011 Technology, Discovery & Innovation Need to cut travel costs? Meet online instead - it's easy! GoToMeeting starts in seconds Try it FREE today. IDC: Open Source a $6B Industry by 2011 June 4, 2007 12:13PM One significant finding in IDC's study of open-source software is that revenues for open-source software companies will lag behind the adoption of the software itself. A significant portion of open-source software is free, while paid distributions typically derive revenue from ongoing subscriptions rather than up-front purchases. China Unveils New Global Warming Plan Bald Eagle Coming Off Endangered List? Liver Cancer Breakthrough Found Wildlife Watchdog Eyes Trade Limits Death Toll from Katrina Rising with HP's All-in-One Storage Systems. Simple and affordable ways to set I.T. free. A new report by IDC concludes that stand-alone, open-source software is poised to become a $5.8 billion industry by 2011, up from $1.8 billion in 2006. That represents a compound annual growth rate of 26 percent over that time period, and, according to IDC, it might go higher. "We are in the early stages of the development and deployment of OSS," Matt Lawton, program director of IDC's Open Source Software Business Models research program, said in press statement. "The market is still quite immature, especially now that we see active open-source projects in all layers of the software stack." The IDC report identifies several reasons for the increase, including increased interest in open-source software as a tool for negotiating with proprietary software vendors, more financial backing of open source by venture capitalists, increased comfort with a subscription-payment model, and a rising interest in open-source software in general. In a telephone interview, Lawton said that, despite the impressive growth in open-source software adoption, it still represents a tiny fraction of the worldwide software industry. One significant finding in the IDC study, Lawton said, is that revenues for open-source software companies will lag behind the adoption of the software itself. A significant portion of open-source software is free, while paid distributions typically derive revenue from ongoing subscriptions rather than up-front purchases. "Some of the barriers that have prevented customers from paying for open source are coming down," Lawton suggested. "There were concerns about the availability of support, but vendors are starting to offer professional support. There also has been a lot of publicity around the risk of infringement of patented software. We found that it is an issue, but not a huge one for customers. Also, vendors are getting more comfortable with getting revenue from open source." Overall, Lawton said, customers are realizing that the quality of open-source software is often quite high, and there is a lot that is commercial-grade. The steadily improving quality of open-source software, the increased availability of reliable support, and the projected growth in revenues are all helping to make proprietary software companies nervous. "Open-source software has two impacts on proprietary-software companies," Lawton said. "It helps open up new markets, where we're seeing a growth in software adoption and revenue generated. And as adoption rates increase, open-sources software also eats into the revenues of proprietary-software companies in existing markets." Do more, travel less with GoToMeeting  Online Meetings Made Easy . Host unlimited meetings for one low flat rate, anytime, anywhere. Increase productivity and avoid the stress and costs of travel. Collaborate in real time and stay productive. Try it FREE today! MetroPCS and the Unlimited Cell Plan Microsoft, Xandros Sign Patent Deal Sony Slashes Blu-ray Player Prices Palm Gets Capital Boost, New Leaders Apple's iPhone Debuts on 