http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-5&fd=R&url=http://www.itwire.com.au/content/view/12644/532/&cid=1116960048&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg iTWire - Microsoft does patent deal with Xandros Linux IT and TELCO JOBS Microsoft does patent deal with Xandros Linux Microsoft does patent deal with Xandros Linux Tuesday, 05 June 2007 Not content with one Linux deal with Novell, Microsoft has announced at the US Tech Ed that it&rsquo;s done a similar deal with Novell&rsquo;s competitor, Xandros, despite the latest draft of the GPLv3. Sony slashes 0 off Blu-ray players; is PS3 next? Gearbox dribbles out info on Aliens shooter More rumours quashed, no Gears of War for PS3 Wii-mote can digitise human speech PS3: Rumours of its death have been greatly exaggerated Days after the latest draft of the GPLv3 that was released, seemingly giving the all-clear to the Microsoft/Novell deal but wanting to prevent further such deals from arising, Microsoft and Xandros seem to have ignored it with their announcement of a 5 year deal. Microsoft said that they, and Xandros , had announced a &ldquo;broad collaboration agreement based on a set of technical, business, marketing and intellectual property commitments&rdquo;. Just as with the Novell deal, Microsoft says customers will get &ldquo;enhanced interoperability, more effective systems management solutions, and intellectual property assurances, all of which extend a bridge between open source and commercial software and deliver customers real value in mixed systems environments&rdquo;. Andreas Typaldos, the CEO of Xandros said in a statement that: &ldquo;Companies today are running a mixture of Linux and Windows systems. Cross-platform data centers are a reality. To meet evolving customer needs, vendors need to recognize the value of sharing intellectual property, developing more interoperable solutions, and providing management tools that are familiar and easy to use.&rdquo; Quite what Novell thinks about the deal is as yet unknown, but Microsoft paints it in a long line of collaborations with &ldquo;Linux platform and open source software providers&rdquo;. Microsoft points to Novell, JBoss, XenSource, Samsung, Zend and others. Bill Hilf, the GM of Platform Strategy at Microsoft said that &ldquo;Customers win when their platform providers build collaborative relationships. We have been working with commercial open source companies to deliver better value to our customers in areas like server interoperability, systems management and office document formats. We believe in and encourage respect for all licensing and development models, and intellectual property is an important component in this environment. Our announcement with Xandros is an exciting step to deliver what our mutual customers have been asking for.&rdquo; The deal covers systems management interoperability, server operability, office document compatibility, the all important intellectual property assurance, with a promise from Microsoft not to sue Xandros customers and also Microsoft sales and marketing support, all as with Novell, although there is no mention of Microsoft buying Xandros coupons as they did when the Microsoft/Novell deal included Microsoft buying millions of dollars worth of vouchers to redistribute and sell to Microsoft&rsquo;s existing customers. Get stories like this delivered to our free Daily UPDATE email newsletter Get a WireTalker account to add your comments to this article. Login now to add your comment. Print joint venture heads towards Ricoh ownership Microsoft does patent deal with Xandros Linux Japan Wiis a lot: 5-to-1 sales over the PS3! Rubiks Cube  solved in 26, or 17.7 moves? Follow-up: NASA, Michael Griffin, global warming, and earth-science research Toshiba unveils slim HD DVD-RW for notebooks Microsoft does patent deal with Xandros Linux Japan Wiis a lot: 5-to-1 sales over the PS3! Gearbox dribbles out info on Aliens shooter Come on Aussie tour with new Pokémon Will Real face any lawsuits fo