e, the use of the iPhone will require a minimum two-year activation plan. Apple may launch the iPhone with a special event rather than during regular events at which it has kicked off new products in the past, such as its Worldwide Developers Conference, going on next week in San Francisco. Will Apple and AT&T launch some pre-Fourth of July weekend fireworks? "We're not disclosing any other plans at this point beyond what we've said already," Kampfe noted. However, Apple already milked a great deal of hype when it unveiled the iPhone back in January at Macworld. A second event might be overkill. "To be honest, I don't think they need to do a whole lot to drive additional attention. There's a lot of hunger around this already," Charles Golvin, a principal analyst with Apple and AT&T may hold a launch event at the Apple Store in New York to help drive mass media coverage, Golvin noted. They may also let the iPhone go on sale at midnight the night before, he speculated. "I still see two waves of uptake, and the first is the Apple fan boys, the people who are devoted to all things Apple ... and there are plenty of them," Golvin explained. These Apple customers have been paying careful attention to their cellular service contracts and have been making sure they are off of competitors' contracts in advance of the iPhone launch. "The more interesting piece will be the second wave, those who are very interested, who maybe already have a BlackJack or Motorola Q -- or something in the same space that's more consumer-friendly than a BlackBerry," Golvin noted. "We'll see if they're still willing pay the premium [for an iPhone]." The iPhone will initially come in two versions -- a 4 GB model for US$499 and an 8 GB model for $599. The steep price tag could put quite a heavy burden on sales ; however, when adding the price of a new iPod to that of a cell phone, the total could be close enough to justify the expense to some consumers. After the initial wave of sales to Apple aficionados, the price may well hold strong. "There's so much attention paid on the price point, but if you go back to the initial price of the Motorola Razr, when also had an exclusive on it, it was $499, so this is not the first phone to be priced at this level," Golvin explained. "And they were able to hold that price point for quite a while." Next Article in iPhone: You've Got to Hide Your iPhone Away More by Chris Maxcer ListManager software is robust, scalable, integrated. Demo today. Free whitepaper on how you can grow sales with very little money using m-commerce. New White Paper: We know what you did last summer but we don't know why. Manage remotely with one interface -- the HP ProLiant DL360 G5 server. New Software Release: Advanced Features for IT Service Optimization Security Products for Your Business Learn more about Microsoft Forefront. It makes defending your systems easier. Raise employee productivity by reducing objectionable content. No per-server fees. You've Got to Hide Your iPhone Away Report: Quanta Cuts 5M iPhone Deal Gauging the iPhone's Ripple Effect CA Message Manager Enterprise Discovery & Archiving The Merits Of Hosted IP Service Relative To IP PBX s An Innovation Imperative Building Innovation Into Your Marketing DNA The Innovation Imperative Building Innovation Into Your Marketing DNA Technical Comparison DB2 HADR and Oracle Data Guard Don't miss a story -- sign up for our FREE e-mail newsletters and view the latest headlines at a glance. Tech News Flash [ ECT News Network Weekly Newsletter [ More Stories by Chris Maxcer GPL 'Last Call' Aims to Make MS-Novell Deal Last of Its Kind 5 Telcos Get a Shot at $20B in Government Contracts Microsoft Puts Surface on the Table Click here to send a letter to the editor... Click here to add your comment about this story... Sign Up for Business and Technology News Alerts This Week on ECT News Network Careers at ECT News Network Private Equity Firm Greases Palm RFID and the Military: Short Tour of Duty? 