http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-2&fd=R&url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/6720135.stm&cid=1116958275&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg BBC NEWS | Technology | Europe online '24 hours a month' The News in 2 minutes Your news when you want it Also in the news Monday, 4 June 2007, 16:51 GMT 17:51 UK E-mail this to a friend Europe online '24 hours a month' Europeans are spending more time online More than 122m Europeans aged 15 and above use the internet each day at home, school or in work, says a report. The average European accesses the net 16.5 days in a month, and spends 24 hours viewing 2,662 web pages, according to tracking firm comScore. The Netherlands has the highest net penetration, with 83% of the country online, the firm reported. Russia, which was included as a European state, has the lowest, at 11% of the population. More than 221m people across the 16 countries surveyed are online each month, comScore said. Germany had the largest online population, with 32.5m net users aged 15 and above, the survey for net usage in May 2007 found. *The percentage of a population aged 15 and above online The UK had the most active online population, spending more than 34.4 hours online each month and a peak of more than 21.8m people online in any given day. Google was the most popular online destination in 13 of the 16 countries, followed by Microsoft in second place and Yahoo in third. Internet penetration across Europe was 40% of the population aged 15 and above, with only Spain (39%), Italy (36%) and Russia (11%) falling below this level. Bob Ivins, managing director of comScore Europe, said: "Increased net usage is tied to broadband roll-out. The UK is an example of a country whose net usage has increased dramatically as broadband has reached more people." He said: "While the study reflects average net usage and penetration, 20% of users account for 60% of usage, with some people spending hundreds of hours online each month." He added: "As convergence takes place between TV and the internet, the nature of what is classed as online and offline will also have to change. "Is someone online when watching TV over the net?" According to comScore, the United States has 156m people online, with 121m online on average each day. E-mail this to a friend Living the converged media life 14 Feb 07 | Business Online and offline worlds merge 31 May 07 | Technology Children 'meet net friends often' 30 May 07 | UK The BBC is not responsible for the content of external internet sites Europe online '24 hours a month' Launch date for iPhone revealed Sony price cut for Blu-ray player MOST POPULAR STORIES NOW Launch date for iPhone revealed Cameroon girls battle 'breast ironing' Hirst unveils £50m diamond skull S Africa police clash with nurses Greek man shot in double-park row Most popular now, in detail Nato condemns Putin missile vow Moroccan family barred from toilet Greek man shot in double-park row Guantanamo Canadian case dropped Your alternative Olympic logos Most popular now, in detail Mixed views in Sierra Leone and Liberia to the Charles Taylor trial Preview the Royal Academy's Summer Exhibition 2007 Living in a toilet The Moroccan family blocked from going home - to a public loo Back to top ^^ Privacy and cookies policy
