apabilities, we should start seeing an upsurge in PS3 sales. But for now the Wii rules the roost, with a long hard slog ahead for Sony and Microsoft to take back the initiative, especially come the big holiday/Christmas season later this year, in what will be the biggest console gaming battle to be fought ever. Get stories like this delivered to our free Daily UPDATE email newsletter Get a WireTalker account to add your comments to this article. Login now to add your comment. Print joint venture heads towards Ricoh ownership Microsoft does patent deal with Xandros Linux Japan Wiis a lot: 5-to-1 sales over the PS3! Rubiks Cube  solved in 26, or 17.7 moves? Follow-up: NASA, Michael Griffin, global warming, and earth-science research Toshiba unveils slim HD DVD-RW for notebooks Microsoft does patent deal with Xandros Linux Japan Wiis a lot: 5-to-1 sales over the PS3! Gearbox dribbles out info on Aliens shooter Come on Aussie tour with new Pokémon Will Real face any lawsuits for new video recorder? PS3: Rumours of its death have been greatly exaggerated Submit your release now Start submitting to iTWire How to post video Submit your press release Security & Privacy Policy Australian IT Recruitment News
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.techshout.com/internet/2007/04/latest-mcafee-report-deems-music-and-tech-related-search-terms-the-riskiest/&cid=1116947848&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Latest McAfee Report deems Music and Tech-related Search Terms the Riskiest Add to My AOL Shout&#8217;s out the latest in Technology! Latest McAfee Report deems Music and Tech-related Search Terms the Riskiest Monday, June 4th, 2007 According to a study by McAfeeâs SiteAdvisor group, more than 276 million Web searches monthly link to sites deemed dangerous by SiteAdvisor. The study is part of a report called âThe State of Search Engine Safetyâ released today. For instance, the study found around 42 per cent of the results using the term âscreensavers,â led to sites flagged with a âredâ warning or a cautionary âyellowâ by McAfeeâs SiteAdvisor service. Besides, other keywords that McAfee deemed risky include names of popular file-sharing software such as âBearShareâ, âLimeWireâ and âKazaaâ. In many cases, the programs come bundled with adware and toolbars that McAfee considers unwanted. However, McAfee did find that it was slightly safer to use search engines on the whole. Although about 4 per cent of search results lead to sites deemed risky, this number has dropped down from 5 per cent a year ago. Mark Maxwell, senior product manager for SiteAdvisor , âWe&#8217;ve seen some incremental steps in the right direction. But the average Joe user should be aware there&#8217;s still plenty to be concerned about.&#8221; Risks are greater when clicking on keyword ads that make up much of search companies&#8217; revenues: According to McAfee, 7 percent of such links produce risky sites, down from 8.5 percent a year ago. SiteAdvisor rates sites based on whether they result in spyware, viruses, excessive pop-up ads, junk e-mail or other threats. The study was conducted by running about 2,300 popular keywords through the top five search engines _ Google Inc., Yahoo Inc., Microsoft Corp.&#8217;s MSN, Time Warner Inc.&#8217;s AOL and IAC/InterActive Corp.&#8217;s Ask. Search companies have taken steps to mitigate the risks. Google, for instance, sometimes flags links to sites it deems risky, and McAfee found a notable drop in risk when using Google, AOL and Ask. Ask and AOL get search ads from Google, and AOL uses Google to power regular search results as well. Tim Dowling, a McAfee VP , &#8220;an active search engine user, one that performs more than 10 searches per day, is likely to visit a dangerous site at least once a day.&#8221; Mark Maxwell noted that SiteAdvisor users average more searches than the general population, possibly because they feel confident they won&#8217;t wind up at a dangerous site. Naturally McAfee encourages all Internet users to download the free SiteAdvisor utility, or purchase the more powerful SiteAdvisor Plus ($24.99/year, $5 off for the first year). | You can skip to the end and leave a response. Pinging is currently not allowed. &#8220;Mapping the Mal Web&#8221; for riskiest country Web sites report revealed by McAfee McAfee Conferred as the Leader in Enterprise Antispyware by Forrester McAfee Worldwide Deployment Support for Host IPS v.6.0 Announced McAfee Wants Beta Testers For Its Latest Gateway Security Program Consumer Identity Theft Protection Products released by McAfee miCard, a new Global Memory Card Format developed by Taiwanese Institute Toshiba SD-L912A HD DVD-RW slim Drive for Mobile PCs announced Mail (will not be published) (required) You can use these tags: To prove you're a person (not a spam script), type the security word shown in the picture. Subscribe to comments (Email field must be filled in) Subscribe to Tech Shout! MPixx 2001 FM and MPixx 2002 FM Digital Audio Players unveiled by Grundig Proof-of-Concept Flaw discovered on Google Desktop Creative Zen V Plus MP3 Player launched in India Mozilla Firefox 1.5 Update released; will be the Last