http://www.earthtimes.org/articles/show/69205.html&cid Microsoft expands Live Search Books by including copyright content Microsoft expands Live Search Books by including copyright content Mon, 04 Jun 2007 16:42:00GMT Create your own RSS Internet Technology News | Microsoft announced that it has obtained permission from various publishers to include copyrighted material into the beta version of its Live Search Books. By obtaining permission from publishers, Microsoft hopes to avoid getting sucked into copyright battles over the content displayed on its service. Its main rival, Google Inc is already facing two lawsuits for displaying copyrighted material without prior permission from the publishers. Live Search program manager Betsy Aoki confirmed as much on the company's blog by stating, "We have paid particular attention to ensuring that we are only including books in our index that our publishing partners have given us permission to include. So our customers and partners can feel secure in our stance on copyright protection." This means that users of the service will be able to read books published by companies such as Cambridge University Press, McGraw-Hill, Rodale and Simon and Schuster. Some of the links can also point users to websites from where they can buy the books. Google has already launched such a service, but is currently battling problems related to copyright materials, with authors and publishers accusing the company of infringing on their copyrights. Google had to then modify its service and display only parts of the books for reading online, with information from where users can purchase those books. Copyright &copy; 2007 Respective Author Email this article (Click Here) Share this article on &raquo; - MSN goes Google, Yahoo way, announces book search service | 26 Oct 2005 - Microsoft unveils Windows Live Search and Live.com in Asia-Pacific | 08 Jul 2006 - Microsoft paying companies to use MSN Live search? | 19 Mar 2007 - Google subpoenas rivals in book scanning project law suit | 06 Oct 2006 - Microsoft, Sprint in search alliance | 16 Nov 2006 Porn websites safer than digital music websites Search the web faster, smarter Computer and internet briefs - June 3 2007 Google confirms Feedburner acquisition The computer helper: Alternatives to eBay - Live Search Books The views expressed in the articles are not necessarily those of earthtimes.org and we accept no responsibility for the views or opinions expressed in the articles either direct or indirect. , All Rights Reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12-0&fd=R&url=http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9588_22-6188497.html&cid=1116960765&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg MySpace seeks advice in sex offender investigation | Tech News on ZDNet MySpace seeks advice in sex offender investigation June 4, 2007, 9:34 AM PT MySpace.com filed a request Monday in a Pennsylvania state court asking for guidance as the social-networking service responds to demands for information about convicted sex offenders using the site. In the request, which was filed in the Court of Common Pleas in Dauphin County, home to the state capital of Harrisburg, MySpace said it is actively seeking advice on how it can legally provide authorities with registered sex offenders' contact information. MySpace came under fire last month when a group of state attorneys general, including Tom Corbett of Pennsylvania, wrote an open letter to the social-networking site demanding that it turn over data pertaining to registered sex offenders who have profiles on the site. MySpace initially refused, citing federal and state privacy laws, including the Electronic Communications Privacy Act (ECPA) of 1986, that the company said from releasing such information. But two weeks ago, that it planned to comply with the request to provide the states with sex offender data, acknowledging that it would have to deal with varying legal requirements in each state. The request filed in Pennsylvania is part of that ongoing plan. "We're very pleased with how this process is working but our desire to provide certain information, such as the content of e-mail messages, is proving complicated under applicable law," the social network's executive vice president and general counsel, Michael Angus, said in a statement on Monday. "Attorney General Corbett has requested we provide the content of e-mail messages of specific registered sex offenders identified by Sentinel Safe," Angus said, referring to the database that MySpace has developed through a partnership with identity verification firm Sentinel Tech Holding. "We want to provide those messages and today have filed a request with the state court in Pennsylvania, asking a judge for guidance on how best to provide the e-mail content without tainting any potential evidence that could help put a registered sex offender behind bars." MySpace members can privately message each others' profiles through an e-mail system within the site. According to MySpace, a federal court determined that the ECPA requires that a search warrant be issued before the social-networking service turns over the content of e-mail messages sent through the site, and that a positive identification through the Sentinel Safe database would not by itself suffice. Talkback - Add your opinion Latest Web Tech Content MySpace seeks advice in sex offender investigation Microsoft turns Ignition for music marketing iTunes crosses language barrier with Foreign Exchange YouTube signs licensing pact with Hearst-Argyle TV How to Tame Your Boss Need help managing your manager? Try these techniques from BNET to master the proper care and feeding of your most important professional relationship. Whitepapers, webcasts & resources from our Power Center Sponsors Web Event: Hats off to Solaris 10 In this video, Sun's Peder Ulander, Sr. VP, Software Marketing, talks about the opportunity for Sun to help customers leverage the power of Solaris as they build out the next generation of services. See why Solaris is the platform of choice>> How To Prepare for IP Telephony Microsoft Dynamics Customer Solution Case Study - Leading Financial Services Firm Implements New Software for Improved Client Service BNSF Railway Automates Change Management to Keep Business on Track Webcast: Managing Complex Programs: Governing Software Development and Systems Engineering A Lifecycle Approach to Software Quality: Venturing Beyond the QA Imperative Ensuring Security and Compliance through Automated Patch Management Network printers: the often overlooked piece to the security puzzle Five-point checklist for multifunction printers Let this Webcast help you make the right MFP decision for your business. 10 ways HP MFPs save you time and money Learn how you can consolidate and save with multifunction products from HP. Site Support & Feedback &copy; 2006 CNET Networks, Inc. All Rights Reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-3&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601087%26sid%3Dajx0sRwPoO2M%26refer%3Dhome&cid=1116813354&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg , Jun 04 17:18 , Jun 04 22:18 , Jun 05 06:18 Apple to Sell IPhone June 29, According to New Ads (Update7) By Adam Satariano and Connie Guglielmo June 4 (Bloomberg) -- Apple Inc. plans to start selling the iPhone June 29, setting up a showdown with Nokia Oyj and Motorola Inc. in the market for advanced mobile phones. The release date was announced in three advertisements posted on Apple&#39;s Web site yesterday. Until now Cupertino, California-based Apple had only said the device, which combines a mobile phone with the iPod music player, would go on sale in late June. Apple has shipped more than 100 million iPods since Chief Executive Officer Steve Jobs introduced the player in 2001. He&#39;s seeking to parlay that popularity into sales of the iPhone, setting a goal of selling 10 million units in 2008. Availability may be limited, which could build ``buzz&#39;&#39; for the product, JPMorgan Securities Inc. analyst Bill Shope said in a report today. ``Users may put off iPod purchases for the iPhone, but they may have to deal with a long wait,&#39;&#39; Shope said. He also said Apple will ``need to go beyond just buzz&#39;&#39; to justify the phone&#39;s price and two-year contract for consumers. JP Morgan is keeping its ``neutral&#39;&#39; rating on the shares, he said. Shares of Apple, which also makes the Macintosh computer, climbed $2.93, or 2.5 percent, to $121.33 at 4 p.m. New York time on the Nasdaq Stock Market. They have risen 42 percent since Jobs announced the iPhone on Jan. 9. Apple&#39;s market capitalization topped $100 billion for the first time last week. Two iPhone models will be available: a $499 version with 4 gigabytes of memory and an 8-gigabyte model for $599. Apple will sell the device with help from AT&T Inc., the largest U.S. mobile-phone service. The iPhone will be available in Europe later this year and in Asia in 2008. AT&T CEO Randall Stephenson said last week that expectations are ``too low&#39;&#39; for iPhone sales. He said San Antonio-based AT&T has attracted interest from more than 1 million customers for the device, which features a touch-screen display instead of a physical keyboard and lets users access e-mail and surf the Web. ``I think they&#39;ll ship 10 million this calendar year,&#39;&#39; said Stephen Coleman, chief investment officer at St. Louis-based Daedelus Capital, which has owned Apple&#39;s shares since February 2004. Coleman said he plans to be among those buyers. The iPhone may buoy sales as Apple introduces new iPod and Mac models. Analysts expect a new video iPod based on the iPhone design as well as updated computers in coming months. That may spur back-to-school and holiday orders. Jobs, 52, last quarter also introduced Apple TV, a $299 set- top box that beams digital videos from computers to widescreen televisions. And he announced a deal last week to display videos from Google Inc.&#39;s YouTube online service using the device. In April, Apple said second-quarter profit rose 88 percent to $770 million as more customers bought iPods and Mac computers. Declining prices for memory chips and screens also helped boost the company&#39;s profit margin. Of the analysts who follow Apple shares, 23 rate them ``buy,&#39;&#39; four have ``hold&#39;&#39; ratings, and none advise selling, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. To contact the reporters on this story: Adam Satariano in San Francisco at ; Connie Guglielmo in San Francisco at Last Updated: June 4, 2007 16:08 EDT U.S. Stocks Rise to Records, Led by Oil Producers; Wal-Mart, XTO Advance Loews, XTO Will Buy Dominion&#39;s Onshore Oil, Gas Business for $6.5 Billion Ritchie Hedge Fund, Facing Losses, Plans Bankruptcy for Insurance Holdings
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-6&fd=R&url=http://www.sci-tech-today.com/news/Open-Source-a--6B-Industry-by-2011/story.xhtml%3Fstory_id%3D010001472N2G&cid=1116949951&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Sci-Tech Today | IDC: Open Source a $6B Industry by 2011 Technology, Discovery & Innovation Maximize your BPM Investment: IDC: Open Source a $6B Industry by 2011 June 4, 2007 12:13PM One significant finding in IDC's study of open-source software is that revenues for open-source software companies will lag behind the adoption of the software itself. A significant portion of open-source software is free, while paid distributions typically derive revenue from ongoing subscriptions rather than up-front purchases. China Unveils New Global Warming Plan Bald Eagle Coming Off Endangered List? Liver Cancer Breakthrough Found Wildlife Watchdog Eyes Trade Limits Death Toll from Katrina Rising with HP's All-in-One Storage Systems. Simple and affordable ways to set I.T. free. A new report by IDC concludes that stand-alone, open-source software is poised to become a $5.8 billion industry by 2011, up from $1.8 billion in 2006. That represents a compound annual growth rate of 26 percent over that time period, and, according to IDC, it might go higher. "We are in the early stages of the development and deployment of OSS," Matt Lawton, program director of IDC's Open Source Software Business Models research program, said in press statement. "The market is still quite immature, especially now that we see active open-source projects in all layers of the software stack." The IDC report identifies several reasons for the increase, including increased interest in open-source software as a tool for negotiating with proprietary software vendors, more financial backing of open source by venture capitalists, increased comfort with a subscription-payment model, and a rising interest in open-source software in general. In a telephone interview, Lawton said that, despite the impressive growth in open-source software adoption, it still represents a tiny fraction of the worldwide software industry. One significant finding in the IDC study, Lawton said, is that revenues for open-source software companies will lag behind the adoption of the software itself. A significant portion of open-source software is free, while paid distributions typically derive revenue from ongoing subscriptions rather than up-front purchases. "Some of the barriers that have prevented customers from paying for open source are coming down," Lawton suggested. "There were concerns about the availability of support, but vendors are starting to offer professional support. There also has been a lot of publicity around the risk of infringement of patented software. We found that it is an issue, but not a huge one for customers. Also, vendors are getting more comfortable with getting revenue from open source." Overall, Lawton said, customers are realizing that the quality of open-source software is often quite high, and there is a lot that is commercial-grade. The steadily improving quality of open-source software, the increased availability of reliable support, and the projected growth in revenues are all helping to make proprietary software companies nervous. "Open-source software has two impacts on proprietary-software companies," Lawton said. "It helps open up new markets, where we're seeing a growth in software adoption and revenue generated. And as adoption rates increase, open-sources software also eats into the revenues of proprietary-software companies in existing markets." Forrester applies their Total Economic Impact model to assess the value of Managed Security Services to a multibillion dollar international media company. View Forrester's Study on MSS offered to you by SecureWorks MetroPCS and the Unlimited Cell Plan Microsoft, Xandros Sign Patent Deal Sony Slashes Blu-ray Player Prices Palm Gets Capital Boost, New Leaders Apple's iPhone Debuts on June 29 Internet Ad Derby Shifts into Overdrive Making sense of the many deals. OLPC Laptop Caught in the Crossfire MIT prof says Intel undermining effort. Palm Gets Capital Boost, New Leaders Cash infusion amounts to $325 million. Sony Slashes Blu-ray Player Prices Sony is slashing the price of its new BDP-300 Blu-ray disc player, which will be available in retail outlets for $499. That's $100 less than originally announced. New Era Dawning in Mobile Computing Palm and its new Foleo laptop-like device are just the latest evidence that the electronics industry is determined to create a new category of mobile computing devices. Virtualization Cutting Storage Costs Storage virtualization technologies, showing signs of maturity, have become an appealing option for some large companies looking to make better use of installed physical resources. NewsFactor Network Enterprise I.T. Sites NewsFactor Network Enterprise Applications Sites NewsFactor Business and Innovation Sites How To Contact Us &#169; Copyright 2000-2007 NewsFactor Network. All rights reserved. Article rating technology by
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-0&fd=R&url=http://www.itwire.com.au/content/view/12636/1066/&cid=1116692570&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg iTWire - NASA busy with space schedule, but has labor troubles on Earth IT and TELCO JOBS NASA busy with space schedule, but has labor troubles on Earth NASA busy with space schedule, but has labor troubles on Earth Tuesday, 05 June 2007 NASA plans six missions in the next 12 months, however they first must overcome an aerospace strike at the Kennedy Space Center (KSC) tentatively scheduled two days after its June 8th launch of STS-117. Follow-up: NASA, Michael Griffin, global warming, and earth-science research NASAs STS-117 heading to space station June 8, 2007 Global Exploration Strategy coordinates space plans of NASA and others NASA boss Michael Griffin on Global Warming South Korea announces plans to explore planets as soon as 2017 Already three months behind in its 2007 schedule after its March 15th delay of STS-117 due to a , NASA hopes to pick up its mission schedule with the launching of Space Shuttle on June 8, 2007. International Association of Machinist and Aerospace Workers union is planning a strike involving nearly 600 space shuttle program workers at the Kennedy Space Center. The union represents the spaceflight operations employees of the (USA). The company is one of the largest space operations companies in the world. Most of the contractor employees at NASA&rsquo;s Kennedy Space Center are USA employees. The Boeing Company and Lockheed Martin Corporation own USA jointly. In all, USA employs around 10,000 people in the states of Florida, Texas, and Alabama, and the Washington, D.C. area. Primarily, USA possesses a NASA contract&mdash;called the Space Program Operations Contract (SPOC)&mdash;to operate and process the fleet of Space Shuttles and to handle operations for the International Space Station. Talks between union officials with the Bargaining Committee for Local 2061 (Cocoa, Florida) and representatives of USA resumed on May 29, 2007, with respect to a proposed new contract. However, ratification of the contract, which was voted on Saturday, June 2, 2007, did not succeed. was cited as being &ldquo;substandard&rdquo; on the union side and &ldquo;fair, competitive and responsive&rdquo; from the company side. The primary issues for these 600 workers center around job security and retirement benefits as NASA shifts its work force from Space Shuttle operations to the new Orion/Ares operations over the next three years. (Space Shuttle operations are planned to conclude in 2010 and Orion/Ares operations are scheduled to start up in 2015.) Negotiators have instituted a five-day cooling-off period for both sides of the issue. These 600 aerospace workers plan to strike as early as June 10th, two days after the planned launch of and its Space Shuttle crew going to the International Space Station for NASA&#39;s continuing assembly missions. NASA and USA contend that a strike will not affect its support of the mission. However, NASA admits that a drawn-out strike could affect the processing of the next mission&mdash; and the Space Shuttle &mdash;as these striking workers help to join the orbiter with the solid rocket boosters (SRBs) and the eternal tank (ET). STS-118 is currently scheduled to launch on October 9, 2007. USA officials state that even with a strike, they will have enough fully certified, trained, and qualified people to perform all of its functions with regard to current and future flights of the NASA Space Shuttles. Only the future will decide if NASA will be able to keep on schedule safely along with resolving this strike with part of its KSC contractor employee work force. Get stories like this delivered to our free Daily UPDATE email newsletter Get a WireTalker account to add your comments to this article. Login now to add your comment. Print joint venture heads towards Ricoh ownership Microsoft does patent deal with Xandros Linux Japan Wiis a lot: 