4". (AP Photo/2005 Fox Broadcasting Co., Anthony Mandler) Email to a friend Romero was charged with one felony count of uploading copyrighted material to a publicly accessible computer network knowing the work was intended for commercial distribution. He has agreed to surrender at the US District Courthouse in Chicago on Tuesday, when arrangements will be made for his travel to Los Angeles, Department of Justice Spokesman Thom Mrozek said. It was not immediately known whether Romero had retained an attorney. E-mails and phone calls to addresses listed in court documents as Romero's were not immediately returned. If convicted, Romero faces a maximum of three years in prison. Â© The Canadian Press 2007 Scandal Sheet: Brad Pitt Brad Pitt was spotted in Montreal... Mexican crime won't stop Canadians Canadians took more trips abroad... Go topless this summer A sure sign of spring is the sight... Fox Sports World Canada Copyright & Permission Rules &copy; 2007 CanWest Interactive, a division of CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. . All rights reserved. Unauthorized distribution, transmission or republication strictly prohibited.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-0&fd=R&url=http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2007/06/04/ap3784963.html&cid=1116813354&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Apple Rises With IPhone Launch Date - Forbes.com Apple Rises With IPhone Launch Date 06.04.07, 11:14 AM ET Shares of Apple Inc. rose in midday trading Monday after the company confirmed its long-awaited iPhone will go on sale June 29. On Sunday, Apple spokesman Tom Neumayr confirmed the product's launch date following the airing of television commercials touting the iPhone. The ads illustrated some of the hybrid cell phone, media player and wireless Internet gadget's features - such as its shiny touch screen - and ended by stating the phone will be available "Only on the new AT&T" and "Coming June 29." The ads were also posted on Apple's Web site. Apple shares gained $2.33 to $120.73 in midday trading. In a note to clients Monday, JP Morgan analyst Bill Shope wrote that he thinks the iPhone will be available in limited supply because it faces a "difficult production ramp." "In this case, it may be reasonable to conclude that limited availability will only heighten the buzz surrounding the product's launch," he wrote. Shope, who has a "Neutral" rating for the stock, thinks shares of Apple are "priced for perfection," and wrote that he worries limited availability of the iPhone could hurt the company's iPod business. Some customers might not buy iPods in favor of waiting for the iPhone, but this could entail long waits, he said. The analyst also expressed concern over the product's price, which runs $499 for a 4GB iPhone and $599 for an 8GB iPhone. "In our view, Apple will need to go beyond just buzz to convince a large number of users to bear this expense," Shope wrote. Apple's stock has risen steadily over the last few months as anticipation has mounted over the product. On May 25, the company's stock climbed after a media report stated the iPhone would be available June 20. At the time, AT&T and Apple would neither confirm or deny that date. AT&T shares added 13 cents to $40.66. Copyright 2007 Associated Press. All rights reserved. This material may not be published broadcast, rewritten, or redistributed More On This Topic ",">"); transformedStoryStr=transformedStoryStr.replaceAll(""","\""); out.write(transformedStoryStr); %--> Starting A Small Business Brought to you by the sponsors below A new book from brings the Himalaya experience home.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-4&fd=R&url=http://www.ecommercetimes.com/story/9h0NEJVW7bqz1z/McAfee-Search-Engines-Falling-Down-on-Security-Job.xhtml&cid=1116947848&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg E-Commerce News: Portals & Search: McAfee: Search Engines Falling Down on Security Job Career Center | Search Jobs | Post Resume Letters to the Editor ECT News Network Map CRM Buyer Site Map E-Commerce Times Site Map Search ECT News Network June 4, 2007 02:19:33 PM PDT Read Next Article in Portals & Search McAfee: Search Engines Falling Down on Security Job By Fred J. Aun Part of the ECT News Network 06/04/07 10:43 AM PT In their pursuit of the bottom line, search engines have put consumers at risk, according to findings from McAfee SiteAdvisor. The company's latest study has found that, while Web search results are generally getting safer, there is much work to be done in weeding out unscrupulous advertisers bent on jilting buyers. However, when does weeding out amount to Net censorship? Visual Sciences & WebSideStory: One Brand. One Mission. Learn how Visual Sciences' breakthrough technologies enable over 1500 clients to correlate data across channels and perform ad hoc query analysis in real-time, delivering fast answers to hard questions. Discover the New Visual Sciences Today! The latest search engine safety report by states that Web search results are slowly getting safer, but it also asserts that search providers can do more to weed out sponsored links from scammers, malware spewers and other "bad actors." Search engine companies have the ability to clamp down on unscrupulous search-based advertisers (such as those buying ads through AdSense program) but seem to ignore the problem for fear of losing revenue, the report said. So-called organic searches, wherein Web surfers seek sites by entering search terms in search windows, are significantly safer than clicking on the sponsored search results that often result from those initial queries, according to the study. McAfee SiteAdvisor found that sponsored results contain 2.4 times as many risky sites as organic results. Watch Where You Look "Search engines vary most in the safety of their sponsored results," stated the report. It noted that 4.1 percent of the sites served up via sponsored results at met McAfee SiteAdvisor's definition of "risky" while 9 percent of those produced on were unsafe. "So users clicking on an ad are more than twice as likely to encounter a risky site on Yahoo than on Ask," noted the authors. The fact that the numbers vary means search engine providers have some control over the quality of their advertisers, said the report. "Search engines can look the other way while dubious ads run rampant, but they can also set and enforce tough editorial policies to keep bad ads out," said the study's writers. "Unfortunately, current guidelines primarily focus on ensuring appropriate ad copy as opposed to Web site safety." "I am not exactly sure that it is the search engines' responsibility to provide safe search results anyway," said Kevin Finisterre, a security researcher with Digital Munition, told TechNewsWorld. "In my mind, a search engine is simply indexing what is out there already. I should honestly be able to receive my search results in an unfiltered manor. What is to stop the search engine company from deciding that my personal site is malicious and subsequently deciding to not list it in their page rankings?" He enjoys "the fact that you can use search engines to dig up all kinds of random bits and bytes that you may not normally be able to find," Finisterre said, and a search engine would "begin to lose value" if it began filtering results. Censorship or Consumer Protection? The main problem is with bogus sponsored links, said Ben Edelman, a Harvard University assistant professor and a coauthor of the report. The study is not calling for censorship, he stressed. "We don't call it censorship when publishers protect users from scams and frauds," Edelman told TechNewsWorld. "There is no proper place on Google for an ad trying to sell you , which sophisticated users know is actually free." Some cases, agreed Finisterre, are over the line. "I guess where I would take concern personally would be if the images being served up by AdSense became tainted with a Windows , for example," he said. "[But] if some jerk company pays Google for an ad and has enough page rank for people to click on the link ... I don't know. I think that's a pretty thin line between customer ignorance and Google's responsibility." There is a "tension between free speech and consumer protection," Edelman acknowledged, but he said nobody should be free to cheat consumers. "In my view, that is actually not a hard question," said Edelman. "There's no free speech to defraud. We're talking about ads right now, not organic results. In that context, usually there's a human making the decisions ... including a right of review. So if your ad is rejected by Google, you can write to Google and ask why." Some sponsored link filtering seems to be taking place, the report said, but it isn't happening as much as it should. "Still, we are struck by search engines' failure to block even the most notorious and widespread of scam ads -- a decision we suspect arises out of search engines' business objectives," wrote the authors. "Excluding bad ads would reduce search engines' revenues by leaving fewer bidders buying ad space -- so search engines have strong incentives to retain even unsavory advertisers." The good news, according to the report, is that search results have become safer during the past year. "Both organic and sponsored results on Google, and Ask now contain a lower percentage of sites rated red or yellow by McAfee SiteAdvisor than they did last year," says the report. "However, Yahoo and have become less safe over the past year. MSN and Yahoo were the two safest search engines in our May 2006 tests, but now their search results contain the highest percentages of risky sites." AOL, the report said, is the safest place to conduct a Web search, and searches for digital music and technology "continue to be among the most dangerous search terms." Next Article in Portals & Search: Steve Jobs and Bill Gates, Milan, Foleo and Product of the Week More by Fred J. Aun eBay Dips Toe Into Social Networking Waters Free Mac Software Serves Up Easy Search, Menu Tools Google Mixes It Up to Widen Search World On-Demand Integration: Addressing the SOA Challenge Domain Name Portfolio Services from BuyDomains Search Engine Marketing: Maximizing Profit with Web Analytics US Government Portal Deploys Enterprise Search Solution Don't miss a story -- sign up for our FREE e-mail newsletters and view the latest headlines at a glance. Tech News Flash [ ECT News Network Weekly Newsletter [ More Stories by Fred J. Aun Nokia Shoots for the Moon With High-End Models Palm Unveils a Two-Hander Murdoch Swings Photobucket Deal Click here to send a letter to the editor... Click here to add your comment about this story... Sign Up for Business and Technology News Alerts This Week on ECT News Network Online Retail Transaction Performance Indices Private Equity Firm Greases Palm Putting King in Clink Won't Can Spam Murdoch's Bid for Journal Is Talk of Wall Street The Best E-Commerce Host for You? Steve Jobs and Bill Gates, Milan, Foleo and Product of the Week GPL 'Last Call' Aims to Make MS-Novell Deal Last of Its Kind Outsourcing: The 20-Year Overnight Success Story Game Company to Create a Massive Chinese Virtual Realm McAfee: Search Engines Falling Down on Security Job Microsoft's Raikes on the Role of BI in Corporate Strategizing Blu-ray Chases HD DVD Into the Bargain Basement China Promises to Curb, Not Cap, Emissions Frenzy of Shuttle Missions to Follow Atlantis Launch Plugging the Holes in Colleges' Tech Brain Drain iPhone Gets a Due Date RFID and the Military: Short Tour of Duty? Movie Customers' Defense: Pipe Down or I'm Telling! Netflix,