http://www.theherald.co.uk/business/law/display.var.1444214.0.0.php&cid The Herald : Business: LAW & ACCOUNTANCY A day in the life News to your PDA 225 Years of News LAW & ACCOUNTANCY - IN THIS SECTION Click here for news menu Click here for related articles menu KPMG expert calls for tax on fortunes earned in virtual world The government should give serious thought to taxing the revenues earned in virtual worlds such as Linden Labs' Second Life, according to a leading Scottish-based tax specialist. Launched in 2003 by San Francisco-based Linden Labs, Second Life has more than five million registered users and two million unique users, with the majority based in Europe. Residents create characters called "avatars" who can earn money by developing properties and starting businesses. Second Life is different from other virtual worlds in that its residents retain full intellectual property rights for any digital content they create. This has led to a burgeoning virtual economy in which thousands of people already make part or all of their real life income from their Second Life businesses by converting Linden dollars to US dollars at an exchange rate of L$268 to US$1. More than 150 Second Life residents are earning US$5000 a month from Second Life, according to Linden Labs. One of the biggest opportunities for making Linden dollars is in real estates and land speculation. Russell Hills, head of tax with KPMG in Scotland, said the Treasury ought to take a more proactive stance towards the taxation of profits earned in online worlds including Second Life. Hills said: "The amount of publicity around people in the game means some are using it as a business opportunity to make a profit." A resident named Anshe Chung - who is really a woman named Ailin Graef - has become the website's most successful businesswoman by developing themed communities, accumulating US$1m in assets within Second Life. Hills stated: "The issue is the extent to which wealth that is being generated in the virtual world is being recycled and remaining there - or being withdrawn into the real world and converted into real money. "I do also wonder if Linden Labs has missed a trick - perhaps they themselves could have taxed revenue in order to help fund the development of their platform." KPMG believes that the UK government should assess the scope for tax planning and fraud, as well as considering the tax implications for virtual businesses. Hills added: "I have yet to hear whether KPMG will be opening an office in Second Life. It depends how far people's imaginations can go." &copy; All rights reserved. Reproduction in whole or in part without Please note: All HTML tags will be ignored. * Your email address will not be displayed This website is &#39;live&#39; and contributions are not monitored or moderated. But we have the right to intervene to stop misuse. You may only use this site if you agree to the and use will indicate agreement to those terms. If you have any concerns over the contents on our site, please contact us - please select - -- please select -- Western Isles (Na H-Eileanan Siar) Copyright &copy; 2007 Newsquest (Herald & Times) Limited. All Rights Reserved
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-3&fd=R&url=http://www.thejournalnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070604/NEWS01/706040332/1018/NEWS02&cid=1116827240&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg When it comes to climate change, the cities are taking the lead Monday, June 4, 2007 Varsity Tipoff: Boys Hoops Varsity Tipoff: Girls Hoops Letters to the Editor NewsCenter Now - All Videos NewsCenter Now - News NewsCenter Now - Sports NewsCenter Now - Life & Style NewsCenter Now - Entertainment NewsCenter Now - Opinion Black History Month Videos Search the Lower Hudson area: When it comes to climate change, the cities are taking the lead (Original publication: June 4, 2007) Yonkers is trying to reduce pollution. It prohibits trucks from idling for more than three minutes. It has a seasonal leaf blower ban. It's got a Green Policy Task Force that has just been introduced to the public and which hopes to start small and move on to bigger things. Cities are taking the lead on curbing greenhouse emissions and trying to moderate climate change, and Yonkers is among the latest to join the effort. "When it comes to global warming, cities are both the problem and the solution," writes the U.S. Conference of Mayors on its climate protection page. Cities take up less than 1 percent of the Earth's land but generate 80 percent of greenhouse gases, so their actions can make a difference. That was the idea behind the meeting of mayors of more than 40 large international cities in New York last month. Those attending the climate summit said they could not wait for national policies to combat global warming. That's just as well. In the United States, the drive to address global warming has been coming from the bottom up. President Bush resisted global goals for curbing greenhouse gas emissions. He rejected the Kyoto Protocol on the grounds that the measure to limit emissions did not bind India and China, two major polluters, in the same way as it did the United States. But Bush has been under pressure from the international community too, and last week, for the first time, he proposed setting "a long-term global goal" for cutting emissions. If the United States follows through, it could mean a shift in U.S. policy, though environmentalists remain skeptical of exactly what Bush plans. But here's a funny thing. Bush's announcement came just as the administrator of NASA, Michael Griffin, went on National Public Radio and said he did not know whether climate change was a long-term concern. "I am not sure that it is fair to say that it is a problem we must wrestle with," Griffin said on "Morning Edition" on Thursday, the same day Bush was giving his speech. "To assume that it is a problem is to assume that the state of Earth's climate today is the optimal climate, the best climate that we could have or ever have had and that we need to take steps to make sure that it doesn't change." Deciding that our climate now was the best climate for all human beings was an arrogant position, he concluded. It was startling to hear him, and as you can imagine, the criticism came fast. The Associated Press pointed out that Griffin's own agency had just put out a press release about a research paper written by nearly 50 scientists from NASA and Columbia University. It showed how "human-made greenhouse gases have brought the Earth's climate close to critical tipping points, with potentially dangerous consequences for the planet." James Hansen, a top NASA climate scientist and the lead author of the paper, was quoted by the AP as saying that millions of people will likely be harmed by global warming in the future. It was Griffin's comments that showed arrogance. Even if all of these top scientists turn out to be wrong, what is the harm in finding ways to pursue economic growth while curbing our pollution? Shouldn't that be what we are trying to do? On the other hand, can you imagine the harm if Griffin is wrong? "The devastation with sea level rise of several meters, with hundreds of millions of refugees, would dwarf that of New Orleans," Hansen wrote an e-mail to the AP. Contrast Griffin's statements with what the mayors, Republicans and Democrats, are doing. More than 500 have signed the U.S. Mayors Climate Protection Agreement, committing their cities to: - strive to meet or beat the Kyoto Protocol targets, - urge the federal government to meet or beat the Kyoto Protocol targets for the United States, that is, a 7 percent reduction from 1990 levels by 2012, and - ask the U.S. Congress to pass legislation that would establish a national emission-trading system. Greenburgh, Irvington, Mount Vernon, New Rochelle and White Plains are taking part. They are leaving the federal government behind. At the international climate summit last month, former President Clinton announced that 15 cities would renovate buildings with green technology under a program spearheaded by Clinton's foundation. The AP reported that major banking institutions had committed $1 billion to finance the improvements to the city-owned buildings. New York is among the cities participating. Cities are the front line of pollution. Mayors cannot afford to have theoretical discussions like Griffin's. Because here's something to think about. Last Thursday, the state Department of Environmental Conservation announced an air-quality advisory for the metropolitan area. Too much ozone in the air. Reach Noreen O'Donnell at or 914-694-5017. And read her blog, "and another thing," at This article does not have any comments associated with it Read More About This Topic Photo exhibit of homeless people highlights lack of housing Like the mandala, our actions and resources are connected Land Trust gets a fitting home: house on 22 acres of Bedford land NYC has mixed memories of Rudy Giuliani Trash, and our impact on the planet London mayor has lessons for NYC on congestion pricing Clinton's base - surburban women - used to be her concern Leaks make Indian Point hard to defend Blythedale moms provide a lesson in caring Westchester lags in meeting affordable-housing goals Copyright &copy; 2007 The Journal News, . Inc. newspaper serving Westchester, Rockland and Putnam Counties in New York. All rights reserved. Use of this site signifies your agreement to the Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Rights , updated March 7, 2007.
