http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-5&fd=R&url=http://www.azcentral.com/business/consumer/articles/0604biz-googletops05-ON.html&cid=1116958275&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Google tops European searches Stocks of AZ Interest Google tops European searches Jun. 4, 2007 09:00 AM Google Inc. is the most visited Web site in Europe and leads in 13 countries including Germany, France and the U.K., a study found. Microsoft Corp. had the second-largest number of visitors and Yahoo! Inc. was third, according to data gathered from 16 countries for the month of April by researcher ComScore Inc. Google's strength in Europe illustrates how the company, the world's most-used Internet search engine, taps markets beyond the U.S. to boost advertising sales. About 47 percent of its revenue came from outside the U.S. last quarter. The U.K. alone accounted for 16 percent of Mountain View, California-based Google's $3.66 billion in first-quarter sales. Europe had an average of 122 million Internet users ages 15 and over each day in April, compared with 114 million in the U.S., ComScore said. Germany had the biggest online population, at 32.6 million people. The Netherlands had the largest percentage of its population using the Internet, at 83 percent, the Reston, Virginia-based researcher said. Shares of Google rose $6.66 to $507.06 at 11:18 a.m. New York time on the Nasdaq Stock Market. They had gained 8.7 percent this year through June 1. Ground beef recalled in Arizona iPhone in stores June 29 Krispy Kreme still reeling from expansion Airline shares fall as fuel prices rise Avis adds chauffeur service for car rentals iPod guru joins Palm board Music, tech terms lure viruses Kidney cancer drug offers patients hope High Court sides with business on credit ratings Google tops European searches Stay in the know. Get expert insights. Weigh in on the issues. Biz 360: Around the Valley Get Arizona business news and stock quotes on your phone or PDA. Visit on your device, or enter your m