posed to DRM). It doesn't infringe on the rights of the purchaser, but it ties a purchase directly to the purchased item so that if someone does engage illegal redistribution of the product, the copyright owner has a name and address of the person they need to sue. The only people that suffer are those who actually violated the law. Jun 2, 2007 4:51:57 AM You would'nt go into a house and STEAL their tv set, but I am sure the owner of the tv set would'nt mind if you looked at it and made your own version of it. Jun 2, 2007 5:51:44 AM fell free to read . If you still hang folks out in the west then think about yhos appla bosses, ok. Jun 2, 2007 8:10:23 AM fell free to read . If you still hang folks out in the west then think about yhos appla bosses, ok. Jun 2, 2007 8:10:31 AM fell free to read . If you still hang folks out in the west then think about yhos appla bosses, ok. Jun 2, 2007 8:10:35 AM if you convert it to mp3 does the tag still exist? Jun 2, 2007 8:30:37 AM By your pro Apple replies I see many of you subscribe to the Orwellian world where a kids iPod gets stolen and the songs wind up on some Napster site that it's OK for the RIAA to sue her grandmother into the street because it's better to prosecute etn innocent people than to let one guilty one get off without punishment. Welcome to the land of guilty until proven innocent and only then for those with cash to burn on lawyers. Enjoy your new world - we'll be installing monitor cams in every room of your house tomorrow. Relax it's what you wanted!! Jun 2, 2007 9:33:42 AM interesting some people gave out their real names... and cry about privacy... the solution to privacy on the internet is to not to try to hide your privacy. THat looks like you got something. Just don't proclaim it either. If you email me, microsoft will give you my real name addy and phone number on an "electronic contact card". I freely give that information out because I only email my friends. That and I'm big and ugly so no need to wor