5 PM bp has it correct, it's all about your information being put on display. Think about tjx compromise.200 million compromised ought to know Jun 2, 2007 9:04:13 PM The successful prosecution of someone for violating copyright by sharing a file on the web will take more than just the watermarking of the name of the purchaser, it will require proof that the purchaser was the one who actually shared it and not just someone who stole it from the original purchaser. Its not guilty until proven innocent, its just a good starting point for an investigation. Its the same with a registered gun used in a crime. Just because it was registered to the original purchaser, doesn't necessarily mean that person committed the crime and certainly isn't enough evidence by itself to convict them of that crime. It just gives the police a good starting point in their investigation. No its not DRM. DRM is digital rights management. DRM actively attempts to control access to the digital property. There's no software or hardware scheme attempting to control access to the music purchased in watermarking or fingerprinting. Jun 2, 2007 9:09:14 PM "In terms of sharing files, you're not legally permitted to do that anyway," he said. "You weren't supposed to that in the first place. You've technically violated the service agreement." Does anybody else think it is funny that there are options under at least two setting tabs concerning sharing your library? Jun 2, 2007 11:05:41 PM Like so many others have already stated, the watermarking has been in place since iTunes Music Store's inception. And it's not like there aren't utilities out here on the ZOMGINTARWEBZ that will allow you to convert a m4p file to mp3 (so long as you have a legitimate license to the file), which doesn't support the AAC atoms and therefore wipes out the info. In fact, even though i purchase alot of my music from iTunes simply because it's convenient, i typically convert it to mp3 format, mainly because i tend to always be 