 or the patents covered by the agreement. Novell in May announced details of its November deal with Microsoft , which likewise offers patent assurances for Novell Linux customers. Aside from patents, the Xandros agreement will also focus on systems management and server interoperability, Office document compatibility, and Microsoft sales and marketing support. If you're a Linux user and are wondering whether these patent machinations mean that Redmond is going to send you a bill, PC World's Matthew Newton says you can stop worrying . For more backstory on the whole Microsoft/Linux patent saga, check out the What do you do as super rich manufacturer, when you have an ailing product that starts to fall apart under it's own weight? You don't make a better product; instead you simply buy up the competition or sue them to death. How marvellous for the customers. In a related announcement, the newest operating system by Mircrosoft has been released. It combines features of both VISTA and LINUX and will be called VISUX. Once again money prevails!!!! Hey Redmound go jump off a cliff. Do something yourselves for once. I can just imagine the staff meating: "Say can we get away with the same old story again????" . Just curl up and die already! This is disgusting and to see other companies actualy bend over is pathetic! / 1000 max characters Western Digital Ships 750GB Hard Drive Mozilla Updates Thunderbird 1.5 Security Flaws Found In Up-to-date IE7, Firefox 2 Microsoft Cuts Patent Deal With Xandros Linux Study: Dangerous Side of Search Engines Plextor Introduces New 18X SATA DVD Burner Google Maps, Tabby Cats, Black Helicopters, and You LCD wide screen monitors &copy; 1998-2007, PC World Communications, Inc. Terms of Service Agreement PC World Latin America
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-1&fd=R&url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/business/1700AP_Microsoft_Xandros.html&cid=1116960048&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg Microsoft strikes another Linux deal Skip ads and navigation Last updated June 4, 2007 9:55 a.m. PT Microsoft strikes another Linux deal SEATTLE -- Microsoft Corp. said Monday it will share technology with Linux distributor Xandros Inc., the latest in a string of deals meant to help the patent-protected Windows operating system work more smoothly with open-source programs. Under the terms of the agreement, New York-based Xandros, which makes and distributes open-source desktop and server software, will license server code from Microsoft and develop software tools that work with Microsoft's systems. The companies also will work on technology to translate between two types of documents, Microsoft-developed OpenXML format and the Open Document Format. That could improve interoperability between Microsoft's Office software and open-source rivals. Microsoft also said in a statement it will endorse Xandros Server and Desktop programs as a preferred Linux distribution. Key to the agreement is a clause that protects Xandros customers from running afoul of Microsoft's legal machine for patent infringement. A growing number of companies and government agencies rely on elements of both Microsoft's Windows and various versions of Linux to run their office networks, but fear being sued by the software maker, which claims open-source software infringes on hundreds of its patents. Financial terms of the arrangement weren't disclosed. The Linux server software segment is dominated by Red Hat Inc. and Novell Inc.; Xandros' share of that worldwide market is so small that research group IDC doesn't track it. Xandros captured less than 1 percent of the desktop Linux operating system market in 2006, according to IDC, far behind big players like Red Flag Software Co., based in China, and Turbolinux Inc. in Japan. The deal with Xandros is similar to one Microsoft struck with Novell last November. It sparked considerable outcry from some open-source programmers, who make all of their code - and any software that includes their code - available without charge to users and other developers. Free software proponents argued that under the public license governing Novell's code, Microsoft must give up patent claims on its software if it makes exceptions for some customers. In a May filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Novell noted that Microsoft could conceivably back out of the deal to avoid extending its patent covenants to a broader range of recipients. Add AP Tech headlines to Palm sells 25 percent stake Study: Music, tech search terms riskiest Microsoft strikes another Linux deal China bars new Internet cafes Apple to launch iPhone on June 29 Sony cuts price on new Blu-ray player Company to create Chinese virtual world Woman sues eHarmony for discrimination Firms race to update E. Africa telecom Sweden cracks down on web credit checks Boeing drops 787-3 request with Europe Microsoft, Linux vendor Xandros to work together Software Notebook: Is Microsoft turning into a hardware company? The Insider: Jones Soda loses Pepsi challenge in Cincinnati Workplace Coach: Don't underestimate emotional intelligence Microsoft, Linux vendor Xandros to work together Software Notebook: Is Microsoft turning into a hardware company? China could abuse Microsoft research, group says Gates and Jobs share stage and memories Todd Bishop's Microsoft Blog Microsoft's ad business: Single, looking for love How Microsoft-Xandros compares to Novell pact Flashback: Bill Gates, in 1987, forecasts 2007 John Cook's Venture Blog Monday roundup: Redfin in Nashville?, Ignition versus Ignition, etc. Data I/O cutting 28 employees Facebook community likes iLike James Wallace on Aerospace BA stock -- to buy or sell A380 finally arrives in Paris UPDATED! No composite barrels for A350 XWB Group claims captured troo