http://news.com.com/8301-10784_3-9725193-7.html&cid Open format document bills in states derailed | Tech news blog - CNET News.com Subscribe to News Blog June 4, 2007 11:16 AM PDT Open format document bills in states derailed Bills introduced over the past year to promote open digital document formats in U.S. state governments have foundered, according to a review of state-level standards activity. on Sunday published an article that found that bills in Minnesota, Texas, Florida, and Oregon around open formats did not pass. The bills called for the use of standards and open document formats in desktop software. A number of European governments have adopted Open Document Format (ODF) as the standard for electronic documents from productivity applications. Microsoft's rival Open XML format has been certified as an Ecma standards and is now being considered by the International Standards Organization. Apart from the high-profile case of Massachusetts, U.S. states have not adopted policies that mandate the use of standard, open document formats. Marino Marcich, the managing director of lobbying group the , said that bills in Florida, Oregon and Texas did not come up for vote in committee. A California bill he characterized as a "work in progress" while Minnesota's bill was altered to study the issue of open documents. Massachusetts has continued to stick with its policy of mandating standard document formats for executive branch offices; it said last year that it intends to use a that will allow Microsoft Office to work with documents and the OpenDocument format. The call for standards and desktop applications has spread to governments around the world, in part because of the standardization and growing viability of OpenDocument. The process has been marked by by Microsoft and IBM, which backs OpenDocument, at the government level. Despite the derailing of the state bills, Marcich said he expects discussion around open formats at states will be common in a few years, driven by either legislative action or executive policy. click here to start it Recent posts from News Blog Shutterstock photogs to get press credentials Olympus camera housings cater to the wet set Feds footing the bill for municipal broadband? Report: JFK terror plotters used Google Earth Report: Google and Salesforce.com to partner Recent posts on technology, trends, and more. Subscribe to this blog Click this link to view this blog as XML. Add this feed to your online news reader Add to my Yahoo Deal of the day Esoteric post of the day Find the Technical Resources You Need Faster with Our Virtual Librarian! See how formatting is easier >> Take business PCs to the next level with Intel. See the big picture>> What CEOs think: Innovation Insights for CIOs See tools for control >> Popular on CNET Networks: Copyright &copy;2007 CNET Networks, Inc. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-4&fd=R&url=http://www.efytimes.com/efytimes/fullnews.asp%3Fedid%3D19431&cid=1116949951&ei=h4BkRvOzHJGoqwPdn5maBg IF IT'S TECHNOLOGY IT'S HERE Tuesday, June 05, 2007 Jetway Launches M28GT3-SDG Motherboard Track Devices With Mobile Eye Acer Launches TravelMate 6292 Lenovo Launches New ThinkPad Notebooks frontFoot: Connect Right Candidates ... Scratch Card, Redeem Cash: Kingston Lage Raho Acer Bhai For Retail ... Become Dax Drona, Win Exciting ... XFX Announces Channel Promotion ... Brother International Pampers ... Airtel Slashes Blackberry Rental ... Fujitsu Introduces First Flash ... Grab An Acer Aspire 5101ANWLMi ... Skype To Slash Call Rates? MTNL Revises 'One India' Plan T-Online Venture Fund Invests ... Accel Transmatic Records Rs 35.03 ... Gemini Q4 PAT Up 52 Per Cent Mformation Gets $20 Million Funding Cambridge Technology PAT Up 64 ... Celanese Showcases Mowilith Nano India On The Track Of Nano Mission Major Breakthrough In Chip Manufacturing: ... MRI Technology Enters Nanometre ... Disposable Insulin Pump To Replace ... Worldwide Open Source Revenues To Hit $5.8 Billion: IDC Worldwide Open Source Revenues To Hit $5.8 Billion: IDC Growth in revenue, however, will lag behind the growth in distribution of open source software. (Monday, June 04, 2007 10:26:08 AM) Growth in revenue, however, will lag behind the growth in distribution of open source software. Monday, June 04, 2007: A new study from IDC reveals the market for standalone open source software (OSS) is in a significant growth stage. Adoption of OSS will accelerate over the forecast period of 2007 through 2011 as barriers to adoption get knocked down. IDC says worldwide revenue from standalone open source software reached $1.8 billion in 2006 and will reach $5.8 billion in 2011, representing a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 26 per cent from 2006 to 2011. "We are in the early stages of the development and deployment of OSS," said Matt Lawton, programme director, Open Source Software Business Models research programme, IDC. "The market is still quite immature, especially now that we see active open source projects in all layers of the software stack." He added, "Although we see healthy growth in revenue from standalone open source software, we must keep in mind that revenue will substantially lag behind the distribution of open source software. Many distributions of standalone open source software are free, while paid distributions typically are based on pay-as-you-go subscriptions rather than pay-up-front licence fees." IDC's study shows that the drivers for OSS adoption, and in particular commercial adoption of OSS, include increased customer interest in OSS as customers realise that OSS provides them with more choice and leverage with proprietary software vendors. In addition, more financial backing from venture capitalists, more comfort with subscription revenue as a business model, and increased interest in OSS within larger enterprise organisations are helping to accelerate the OSS adoption rate. Software vendors are advised to consider several factors when evaluating how best to leverage open source software as a business opportunity, including the most appropriate business model, the appropriate usage of partnerships and alliances, and the characteristics of the community supporting the open source software. (Monday, June 04, 2007 10:26:08 AM) Growth in revenue, however, will lag behind the growth in distribution of open source software. IBM Leads Asia-Pacific Server Market: Gartner Software Piracy Costs $40 Billion Global Losses Indian SMBs To Spend $330 Million On Printers Saugatuck Technology Reports On SaaS Telco Brand Is Weak In Media Space: Ovum A Regional Convention On FOSS 24 Nov: FOSS.IN 2006 Quantum Ships StorNext FX v 1.4 Oracle Application Server 10g In Gartner Leaders Quadrant LIC Migrates To Red Hat Enterprise Linux Mformation Gets $20 Million Funding FSA Authorises Firstsource Solutions KPN